<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Criticism leveled against Thruway toll hike plan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A plan to allow New York State Thruway tolls to
go up by as much as 3 percent each year drew a barrage of criticism at a public
forum in Rochester.
<P>
	   The Thruway Authority wants to tie future toll increases to a national
construction cost index. If the "indexed toll adjustment plan" is approved, the
first hike of 1.8 percent would begin June 1.
</P>
<P>
	   Toll increases are "a last resort - I didn't want to be the one that had to
do it," the agency's executive director, John Platt, told a group of
Rochester-area lawmakers at the first public hearing on the toll hike proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   After wrapping up an hourlong presentation Friday, Platt then took an earful
of complaints from civic and business groups and state Assemblyman David Koon, a
Rochester Democrat.
</P>
<P>
	   "Once this plan is in place, future toll increases of 3 percent or less
would not be subject to further public comment or review," Koon complained. "In
plain English, that means there will be little or no public accountability over
future toll increases - and that's wrong."
</P>
<P>
	   The Automobile Association's local chapter also argued that tying toll
increases to the Construction Cost Index - an average of construction material
and labor costs in 20 U.S. cities - "clearly diminishes the accountability of
the Thruway Authority."
</P>
<P>
	   Legislators should ensure that any extra tolls are used exclusively for
transportation needs such as maintaining roads and bridges and not "diverted to
unrelated projects" the Thruway has assumed control of in recent years, such as
the state Barge Canal system, said AAA Rochester spokesman Jim Ver Steeg.
</P>
<P>
	   Truckers are "diametrically opposed" to toll increases on what is already
"one of the most highly priced limited access highways" in the nation, piped in
Charles Goodwin, vice president of international trade and transportation at the
Rochester Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
	   Tolls were last raised in 1988 along the 641-mile Thruway, the nation's
longest toll road. The proposed hike would be used to fund about $1 billion in
improvements over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
	   Two more public hearings were scheduled in Syracuse and Albany next week.
Thruway officials plan to hold further public hearings before finalizing their
plan this spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-12-00 0003 </TRAILER>
