<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Space mapping project will help Cornell geologists studying Andes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) - The unrivaled three-dimensional map that will be
developed from the space shuttle Endeavour mission also will help unlock some of
the secrets of the Andes Mountains' geology, says a Cornell University
geologist.
<P>
	   "There are parts of the Andes that have never been topographically mapped
because of cloud cover, especially parts of the eastern side of the range," said
Bryan Isacks, chairman of Cornell's Department of Geological Sciences and
director of its Institute for the Study of the Continents. Not even satellites
have been able to penetrate the cover, Isacks said.
</P>
<P>
	   Isacks is one of six Cornell faculty members working on a 20-year-old
topography study in the Andes in collaboration with several Latin American
scientists.
</P>
<P>
	   The Endeavour lifted off Friday on a mission to map up to 80 percent of the
Earth's surface using a new high resolution radar antennae.
</P>
<P>
	   The radar will resolve details as small as 30 meters across, said an
enthusiastic Isacks. Except for limited areas, existing maps of many remote
mountainous regions such as the Andes, whether from radar or conventional
ground-based mapping, have a resolution of only about 1 kilometer, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   As important as the images are to scientists, Isacks and his colleagues are
equally interested in the raw data used to generate the detailed topographic
maps.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're not just looking at a color picture of topography. That's what you
get at the end, but there's a lot of analysis before that. It will answer basic
questions about how the world works," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Much of the Cornell work will focus on the Altiplano, a huge plateau
surrounded by higher peaks that spreads through northern Argentina, western
Bolivia and southern Peru. The two-mile high plateau is some 188 miles wide and
625 miles long that is home to Lake Titicaca, the highest navigable lake in the
world.
</P>
<P>
	   "How this thing got raised up that way is still a fairly big mystery,"
Isacks said.
</P>
<P>
	   In a general way, geologists know how the Andes mountain range formed.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the floor of the southeastern Pacific Ocean rests on a single huge
slab of the Earth's lithosphere, the outer skin comprising the crust and the
uppermost mantle, called the Nazca plate that is floating on semimolten magma.
</P>
<P>
	   Some 200 million years ago, the eastern edge of the Nazca plate began
shoving its way under the western edge of the South American plate, which makes
up the continent itself and part of the South Atlantic Ocean floor.
</P>
<P>
	   The land above was lifted and squeezed. The crust folded and began thrusting
up mountains so sharply that there is a drop of about 40,000 feet from the
western edge of the Andes to the Peru-Chile trench in the Pacific Ocean, a
distance of only 200 miles. A chain of volcanoes erupted along the mountain
range.
</P>
<P>
	   Understanding more about the region's geology might help scientists predict
and prepare for quakes and eruptions, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The new information also could provide more understanding about the
hydrology of the Amazon River system by giving scientists more information about
the topography of its upper headwaters.
</P>
<P>
	   "It will fill in huge gaping areas that we don't know about," Isacks said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-12-00 0004 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
