<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State assemblyman charged with burglarizing aide's home  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   GENESEO, N.Y. (AP) - After a two-week stay in a psychiatric ward, a
state assemblyman surrendered to police and was charged with burglarizing a
female aide's home.
<P>
	   Jerry Johnson, 57, a four-term Republican whose district extends across
Livingston, Monroe and Allegany counties in western New York, was arraigned
Friday on a charge of second-degree burglary, a felony that carries a maximum
sentence of five to 15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   Johnson pleaded innocent and was freed on $10,000 bail. The judge ordered
him to stay away from the woman and her husband, who live near this village 35
miles south of Rochester.
</P>
<P>
	   Flanked by relatives outside Geneseo Town Court, a solemn Johnson declined
to answer questions. But his attorney made it clear Johnson has neither
considered taking a leave of absence nor resigning from his post "at this time."
</P>
<P>
	   Johnson, who is divorced and has three daughters, was first elected in his
mostly rural district in 1992 and is up for re-election in November. He is a
ranking minority member of the mental health committee in Albany.
</P>
<P>
	   "He is on medication and we continue to receive medical care," his attorney,
John Parrinello, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
	   Johnson booked into Bry Lin Hospitals, a psychiatric center in Buffalo, on
Jan. 27 with the approval of Livingston County Sheriff John York, a personal
friend. York drove him to the courthouse Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The investigation began in December when the woman, who was not identified,
told police her pocketbook had been stolen from her car. Authorities turned up
evidence that Johnson had entered her house without permission Oct. 22 and
placed a telephone call, York said, adding further charges could be filed soon.
</P>
<P>
	   "He has been treated the same as anybody else ... in a similar type of
investigation," the sheriff said. "It is very difficult. He's been a long-time
friend. But it's also been very difficult for the victim."
</P>
<P>
	   WOKR-TV in Rochester reported the woman alleged that Johnson stalked her,
made harassing phone calls and broke into her home to steal her underwear. York
declined to elaborate on the investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   After serving in the U.S. Air Force, Johnson worked his way up the ranks at
Genesee and Wyoming Railroad to become president and general manager in 1977. He
began his political career in 1972, serving on the education board, as a town
councilman and then as town supervisor in the village of Nunda for seven years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
