<DOCNO> APW20000212.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Wiranto Said Resigning  </HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK MCDOWELL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Indonesian Security Minister Wiranto, accused of
allowing pro-Indonesia militias to devastate East Timor, will resign next week,
the country's president said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   President Abdurrahman Wahid, in Bangkok for a U.N. trade meeting, said he
would meet with Wiranto after his return to Indonesia Saturday night and expects
him to resign within two days.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid, who has been traveling outside Indonesia for about two weeks, first
called for Wiranto's resignation on Jan. 31 after an Indonesian government
investigation blamed the general for the mayhem in East Timor last year when the
territory voted to break away from Indonesia in a U.N.-supervised ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   Wiranto, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, has refused to budge
from his Cabinet position, sparking fears of a coup attempt by the country's
powerful military.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid said Wiranto had not resigned already because the two had not had a
chance to meet face to face.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You can expect the day after tomorrow, the announcement of his
resignation,'' Wahid said.
</P>
<P>
	   In Jakarta, an aide to Wiranto refused to comment on Wahid's comments.
</P>
<P>
	   Any agreement for Wiranto to step down is expected to provide a safe exit
for him, while establishing Wahid's authority over the once all-powerful
military.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid had asked the general to quit the Cabinet over the recent bloodshed
and devastation in East Timor. However, Wahid also recently suggested he might
pardon Wiranto if he were convicted of human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
	   Such a trade-off could protect Indonesia's fragile democracy after decades
of authoritarian rule.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked why he believed Wiranto would resign, Wahid said: ``Because of his
sense of patriotism, his sense of loyalty to the country.''
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid said he understood that Wiranto was concerned that he would have to
face questions in a court, and that his resignation might be seen as an
acknowledgement of guilt.
</P>
<P>
	   But he said it would be better for Indonesia if Wiranto steps down because
it would be sign that the country is serious about democratic reforms and
restoring stability.
</P>
<P>
	   ``His resignation will be seen by other countries as a sign we are serious,
that you can invest in Indonesia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Wiranto has continued to attend Cabinet meetings despite Wahid's calls for
him to resign.
</P>
<P>
	   But in an interview published Friday in Singapore's Straits Times newspaper,
Wiranto said Indonesia's military is loyal to the president and will not stage a
coup.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It never crossed my mind to seize power,'' Wiranto was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
	   When Wahid's foreign trip ends, he will have visited 18 cities in 16 days.
He had wanted to recruit foreign investment for his country, the world's
fourth-most populous nation, after its worst economic crisis in a generation.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead, his trip was dominated by Indonesian government and U.N. reports
that accuse Wiranto's troops of backing militia gangs that terrorized East Timor
after its people voted overwhelming to end Indonesian rule last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Wiranto was military commander at the time, but denies responsibility for
the violence.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid said repeatedly while visiting European and Asian capitals that if
Wiranto refused to quit, he would be fired. Back in Jakarta, Wiranto defiantly
took part in Cabinet meetings.
</P>
<P>
	   A showdown previously seemed inevitable. But in recent days, Wahid has
tempered his resignation demands by praising Wiranto as an honest soldier who
had once thwarted a plot to murder him.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid took office last October as its first freely elected president in 44
years. Since taking office, he has reined in the power of the military by
replacing Wiranto as armed forces commander and insisting that he and other
generals in the Cabinet become civilians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0026 </TRAILER>
