<HEADLINE> South Elects Black Episcopal Bishop  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- Episcopalians in North Carolina have made their
diocese the first in the South to elect a black bishop, choosing a Baltimore
minister to lead their 33,000 members.
</P>
<P>
	   The Rev. Michael Curry was elected Friday from among six candidates at the
annual convention of the Episcopal Diocese of North Carolina. He will be
installed June 17, replacing the Rt. Rev. Robert Johnson Jr., who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
	   About 40 of the 500 delegates were black.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is both a joyous and a humbling experience,'' Curry said. ``I'm very
grateful and very thankful, and really looking forward to being part of the life
of the church in North Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
	   Curry will oversee 250 pastors, confirm new members and participate in a
rulemaking body within the national denomination.
</P>
<P>
	   Blacks have served in Southern dioceses as suffragan bishops, essentially
assistant bishops, but never as bishop. Curry, who has led the St. James Church
in Baltimore for 11 years, is considered moderate to liberal.
</P>
</TEXT>
