<HEADLINE> Congressional Notebook: Elections  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID ESPO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- First the House Republicans, then Democrats, decamped
from Washington for brief retreats recently, and both sides came back saying
they were encouraged by election-season reports from their pollsters.
</P>
<P>
	   The Republican survey reported that that a hypothetical GOP candidate
outpolled a hypothetical Democratic candidate, 41-36, with 23 percent undecided,
in a poll taken in 41 key, targeted congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans were urged to stick to an agenda with four main points: Social
Security, education, a flexible spending freeze with attention paid to
eliminating government waste and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
	   The Democratic poll, by contrast, had Democrats at 38 percent and
Republicans at 33 percent, with 29 percent undecided, in a survey taken in 35
targeted districts.
</P>
<P>
	   Democrats also were cheered by the finding that among the 29 percent
undecided on the so-called generic ballot test, the issues that mattered most
were education, Social Security and health care, favorable terrain for their
party.
</P>
<P>
	   The two parties in the House are focused firmly on the fall elections, in
which the GOP is defending a narrow, 222-211 majority. The House also has two
independents, one in the Republican orbit, the other aligned with the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite a persistent public claim from Democrats that victory is only a
matter of time, officials speaking on condition of anonymity said House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., told his troops to guard against overconfidence.
They said he put the odds of a takeover at 50-50.
</P>
<P>
	   Gephardt has also told fellow Democrats he believes the House may be on the
verge of a political realignment, and if the Democrats win control, moderate
Republicans could defect to their side. Several conservative Democrats switched
to the GOP in the months after the Republicans won a majority in the 1994
elections.
</P>
<P>
	   --------
</P>
<P>
	   One of the oddities in this election season is the steady growth in the
number of House members without major party opposition this fall -- 16 Democrats
and 10 Republicans thus far.
</P>
<P>
	   Recent additions to the list include Republican Reps. Bud Shuster and Jon
Peterson of Pennsylvania and Richard Burr and Howard Coble of North Carolina.
Coble serves on the Judiciary Committee, which conducted President Clinton's
impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
	   Democrats without GOP opponents include Reps. Chaka Fattah and William Coyne
of Pennsylvania and Alan Mollohan and Nick Rahall of West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
	   --------
</P>
<P>
	   With two weeks remaining until the filing deadline, Democrats are still
hoping former Nebraska Gov. Ben Nelson will decide to enter the race to succeed
a retiring Sen. Bob Kerrey. Nelson won two terms running statewide for governor,
although he lost a Senate race in 1996 to Republican Chuck Hagel. Even so,
Democrats view Nelson as their best hope to hold onto Kerrey's seat.
</P>
<P>
	   There are four Republicans in the race, including the state attorney
general, Don Stenberg; the secretary of state, Scott Moore; as well as Elliott
Rustad, a physician, and George Grogan, a businessman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
