<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Charter Schools Movement Growing  </HEADLINE>
   By ANJETTA McQUEEN AP Education Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Four hundred new charter schools opened last school year,
reflecting families' increased interest in alternatives to more traditional, but
often lower-performing public schools.
</P>
<P>
	   About 250,000 children are now served by 1,500 charter schools, a 40 percent
increase in such institutions in the 1998-99 school year, the Education
Department reported in its fourth annual study on charter schools.
</P>
<P>
	   Charter schools -- public schools created by parents and teachers and run
with exemptions from most state laws and regulations -- represent a public
school-choice for parents in poor communities, where schools often struggle.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We can see that there is a continued need for our support of these
schools,'' Education Secretary Richard Riley said in releasing the report
Friday. ``Public charter schools are providing parents and students with choice
they want and deserve.''
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton and Republicans alike have supported public charter
schools with increased public funding since the nation's first charter school
opened in 1992.
</P>
<P>
	   The administration, though, favors public school choice over conservatives'
proposals to use public funds to send children to private or parochial schools.
Clinton is seeking a $30 million increase to a total $175 million for the
federal program that helps states open more of the public charter schools.
</P>
<P>
	   Just eight years ago, when Clinton was first elected, there was one such
school -- in Minnesota. Today, 1,484 schools, many with multiple sites, operate
in 27 states and the District of Columbia, with 37 states and the District
having laws supporting their establishment. New York, Oklahoma and Oregon passed
the latest measures last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Nearly 90,000 children were served by 421 newly opened charter schools in
the last school year, the department reported.
</P>
<P>
	   A charter school, created by a group of teachers, community members or
parents, is free of most state laws and regulations but must be approved by a
local chartering authority. A charter outlines its goals, procedures and
standards to that authority. Charters that fail to meet them are shut down; 27
schools closed under those circumstances last year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   Though charters serve less than 1 percent of all public schoolchildren, the
charter school movement remains popular. Seven in 10 schools told department
researchers they have waiting lists.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet charters have opponents who note that they could drain the most
motivated students and families from traditional public schools -- not to
mention the public money needed to fix the failing schools in the first place.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, charters schools have run into trouble for serving specific
populations and about a quarter of them do just that, the report said. By virtue
of being based in minority communities where they have been especially popular
or opened with specific purposes such as helping troubled children, some schools
have ended up being predominantly black.
</P>
<P>
	   A growing number of parents are challenging decades-old desegregation orders
to protect their charter schools.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Justice Department has blocked just three charters; roughly 50 more
could be affected by court-ordered actions to end patterns of racial separation
in school districts.
</P>
<P>
	   Unlike the schools in Lufkin, Texas; Oktibbeha County, Miss.; and Georgetown
County, S.C., most charters -- which are small -- usually don't affect racial
patterns, Justice Department officials have said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0114 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Helps Steel Industry  </HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN CRUTSINGER AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. steel manufacturers have further protection from a
flood of foreign imports with a decision by President Clinton to impose penalty
tariffs of 19 percent and 10 percent on two types of steel.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House announced late Friday that Clinton had decided to impose
higher tariffs on certain imports of steel wire rod, which is used to hundreds
of products from coats hangers to fencing, and steel welded line pipe, used in
the construction of natural gas and oil pipelines.
</P>
<P>
	   The administration had delayed a decision in both cases for several months
as an internal debate raged over what action to take.
</P>
<P>
	   Supporters of tariffs argued that in an election year the administration had
to act to protect the domestic industry and its workers. Opponents contended
that the higher tariffs would impose inflationary costs on steel users in the
United States and signal a further U.S. retreat behind protectionist barriers.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan has already said it will bring cases against the United States before
the World Trade Organization, arguing that U.S. actions to impose penalty
tariffs on imports of various types of steel from Japan and other countries
violated WTO rules.
</P>
<P>
	   Vice President Al Gore, campaigning for the Democratic presidential
nomination, has had to fend off criticism from labor groups, including the
United Steelworkers union, that the administration's trade policies have failed
to protect American workers.
</P>
<P>
	   Steel companies and the Steelworkers union praised Clinton's decision in the
two cases.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The relief announced today should help an industry that has been devasted
by an onslaught of wire rod imports that swelled to record levels in 1999,''
said Charles Owen Verrill Jr, a lawyer representing the domestic industry.
</P>
<P>
	   Roger Schagrin, an attorney for the domestic steel pipe industry, said the
action ``sends a strong message to our foreign trading partners that import
surges which lead to serious injury to the industry and its workers will not be
tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
	   Some 4,000 U.S. workers are employed making steel rod and 1,000 produce
steel line pipe.
</P>
<P>
	   South Korea, one of Asian countries hardest hit by the currency crisis, is
the largest foreign supplier of steel line pipe to the United States, accounting
for half of overall imports of the product.
</P>
<P>
	   Trinidad and Tobago, Brazil, Ukraine and Germany are among the biggest
suppliers of wire rod that will be subjected to the penalty tariffs.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The action that the president has announced represents a clear statement
of the administration's commitment both to the vigorous enforcement of U.S.
trade laws and to the application of international trade rules,'' White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   The tariff on steel rod will be an additional 10 percent on imports that
exceed 1.58 million tons in the first year. The level of imports will be allowed
to increase by 2 percent a year in the second and third years, while the tariff
penalty will drop by 2.5 percentage points a year.
</P>
<P>
	   For pipe, Clinton imposed an additional 19 percent tariff, although the
first 9,000 tons of steel from each supplier country will be exempt from the
higher tariff each year. The penalty tariff will drop to 15 percent in the
second year and 11 percent in the third year.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton acted following rulings by the U.S. International Trade Commission
that increased imports of wire rod and line pipe threatened serious injury to
American producers.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, the administration approved tariff cases affecting other types of
steel as the industry filed a wave of complaints alleging that various countries
were selling steel at unfairly low prices in the United States, a practice known
as dumping.
</P>
<P>
	   The companies involved in the pipe case decided Friday were Geneva Steel,
Vineyard, Utah; IPSCO Tubulars Inc, Camanche, Iowa; LTV Copperweld, Youngstown,
Ohio; Lone Star Steel Co., Dallas; Maverick Tube Corp., Chesterfield, Mo.;
Newport Steel, Newport, Ky.; Northwest Pipe Co., Portland, Oregon, and Stupp
Corp., Baton Rouge, La.
</P>
<P>
	   In the wire rod case, the companies involved were Birmingham Steel Corp.,
Birmingham, Ala.; Connecticut Steel Corp., Charlotte, N.C.; Keystone Steel &AMP;
Wire Co., Dallas; North Star Steel Co., Minneapolis; Northwestern Steel &AMP; Wire
Co., Sterling, Ill., and Atlantic Steel Industries Inc. of Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
