<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Sees Cracks in Opposition  </HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT H. REID Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Despite a diplomatic cold shoulder suffered by her
Cabinet colleague, Austria's foreign minister believes cracks are emerging in
Europe's opposition to the new government and its far-right-wing members.
</P>
<P>
	   France and Belgium have taken the most vocal stance within the European
Union against Austria's new coalition; their ministers walked out on a speech by
Austria's social affairs minister at an EU gathering in Lisbon, Portugal, on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   But Foreign Minister Benita Ferrero-Waldner insisted that other EU nations
were not as adamant in punishing Vienna for the inclusion of Joerg Haider's
far-right Freedom Party in the government.
</P>
<P>
	   ``One thing is clear,'' Ferrero-Waldner said Friday after the snub. ``Two
countries stand at the very front. The others have gone along out of solidarity
but many of them don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``A handful'' of governments have privately expressed sympathy for Austria,
she said in an interview due to be published today in the Linz-based Neue
Volksblatt newspaper, though she refused to identify them.
</P>
<P>
	   A prominent German conservative, Bavarian state Gov. Edmund Stoiber,
criticized EU measures against Austria on Friday as ``completely exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
	   During a visit Friday to the Bavarian capital Munich by Austrian President
Thomas Klestil, Stoiber said the EU must respect democratic decisions of a
sovereign member state.
</P>
<P>
	   In a clear reference to Haider, however, Stoiber said he was commenting
about a European political issue and not ``about a person with whom I have
nothing in common politically and don't want to have anything in common.''
</P>
<P>
	   The 14 other members of the European Union reduced ties with Austria after
the coalition of the Austrian People's and Freedom parties took office last
week. Haider has gained notoriety for past comments praising some Nazi policies,
though he has since apologized.
</P>
<P>
	   The Lisbon ministerial session was the first EU gathering since. The French
and Belgians walked out when Austrian Social Affairs Minister Elisabeth Sickl
rose to speak.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Austrians opposed to the presence of Haider's party in the
coalition showed no sign of easing up on their protests. Several thousand turned
out despite a cold rain for anti-Haider rallies Friday evening in Graz and
Salzburg.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have not elected this government,'' political scientist Barbara Wicha
told a crowd of about 3,000 people in Salzburg. ``We want to make it known that
this government is not Austria. Austria is something else.''
</P>
<P>
	   About 1,000 others marched in Graz. A major protest rally is planned today
for the capital, Vienna.
</P>
<P>
	   Wicha pointed out that more than 70 percent of the electorate did not vote
for the Freedom Party in Oct. 3 parliamentary elections. She said those that had
voted for the Freedom Party were ``shamelessly exploited by a demagogue and
right-wing populist.''
</P>
<P>
	   Haider's party, which seized on fears that immigration and EU expansion
would cost Austrians jobs, finished second in the balloting with 27 percent of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
	   The center-left Social Democrats came first in the election but was unable
to cobble together a coalition or stand alone to rule. So the Freedom and
People's parties put together their 52 seats each in the 183-member parliament
to form a coalition.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite opposition to the government, a survey by the newspaper Die Presse
found that 73 percent of 500 Austrians expressed opposition to the international
measures against the country.
</P>
<P>
	   Opposition to the foreign reaction cut across party lines, the paper said.
Sixty-four percent of Social Democrat supporters in the poll believed the
international measures were unfair.
</P>
<P>
	   No margin of error was given for the survey, taken nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0119 </TRAILER>
