<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials Seek Calm in Kosovo City  </HEADLINE>
   By ELENA BECATOROS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- After a week of violence that sent
hundreds of ethnic Albanians fleeing their homes, the head of the embattled U.N.
mission is promising new measures to restore calm to Kosovo's most volatile
city.
</P>
<P>
	   The violence, sparked by an attack that killed two Serbs, has claimed eight
lives and injured dozens of people, prompting the NATO-led command to send
reinforcements to help French troops barely able to control the deteriorating
situation.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.N. refugee agency estimates about 800 ethnic Albanians have been
driven from their homes in the Serb-controlled part of Kosovska Mitrovica. U.N.
officials fear that if the trend continues, all the 4,500 Albanians who lived in
the Serb area will soon be gone.
</P>
<P>
	   After a visit Friday to ethnic Albanians living in the Serb-held north side
of the Ibar River, U.N. mission chief Bernard Kouchner announced a series of
measures to bolster security.
</P>
<P>
	   New checkpoints will be set up in the city, new armed patrols will be
conducted and an additional 300 U.N. police will be deployed -- although
Kouchner did not say where they would come from. The United Nations has already
complained it lacks enough police to guarantee security province-wide.
</P>
<P>
	   Kouchner also said the United Nations would enforce a decree issued last
year authorizing police and troops to expel from the city or even the province
any ``troublemakers'' who foment discord. He also said a ``security zone'' would
be established where public protests would be banned.
</P>
<P>
	   About 140 British reinforcements have already moved into the city to
reinforce French troops. Several U.N. policemen have complained that the French
were slow to respond when the violence exploded last week.
</P>
<P>
	   The British joined about 150 German, Dutch, and Italian troops already sent
here as reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
	   The trouble started after a grenade attack on a U.N. relief agency bus
killed two elderly Serbs last week. That triggered a wave of grenade attacks,
shootings and clashes.
</P>
<P>
	   During his brief visit to the Serb area, Kouchner tried to reassure ethnic
Albanians still there of their safety.
</P>
<P>
	   On his way to the north side, Kouchner stopped briefly on the bridge to chat
with three elderly Albanians -- two men and a woman -- who were lumbering across
to the south side carrying clothes and personal items in plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
	   The ethnic Albanians said they were leaving after Serbs banged on their
doors and threatened them if they did not leave immediately.
</P>
<P>
	   Kouchner said he also visited an elderly couple who had been living in the
Serb part of the city for 25 years. He said they wept at the prospect of having
to leave.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I remember it was the same tears when I visited elderly Serbs in
Pristina,'' he said, referring to the Kosovo capital from which most Serbs have
been driven from their homes too.
</P>
<P>
	   ``People are suffering on both sides,'' Kouchner said. ``People are
suffering on the north side. They are looking desperate, and they believe they
have no future. And it's not true at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
