<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Uses Iced Tea Defense  </HEADLINE>
   By PETE YOST Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Call it the iced tea defense.
</P>
<P>
	   Vice President Al Gore told the FBI he may have been in the bathroom during
key parts of a strategy meeting about fund-raising telephone calls. He drank a
lot of iced tea and was out of the room when the subject came up, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
	   Trying to raise questions about the vice president's truthfulness, the
Republican Party this week seized on Gore's statements in the fund-raising
investigation, circulating an e-mail message titled ``Did Al Gore Mislead the
FBI?''
</P>
<P>
	   On the campaign trail in this year's race for the presidency, Gore has tried
to neutralize his role in the fund-raising controversy of 1996 by saying he made
a mistake in phoning prospective donors from the White House during the
Clinton-Gore re-election effort. But political opponents from Bill Bradley to
the GOP are bringing up the topic in a search for vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
	   The Gore camp says the search is fruitless and that political opponents
could end up hurting themselves.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This whole matter has been investigated for years now by everyone from the
FBI to partisan Republican members of Congress, and absolutely no one has ever
made any credible allegations of wrongdoing,'' spokeswoman Laura Quinn said
Friday night. ``There is absolutely nothing new here.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Republican Party has no agenda, they have no vision and they have no
message,'' Gore campaign press secretary Chris Lehane said. ``The only thing
they can do is focus on discredited charges from the past and they do that at
their own peril.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Voters have showed time and time again that they reject that approach in
favor of candidates who talk about the voters' future,'' Lehane added.
</P>
<P>
	   One FBI summary stated that in a 1997 interview, Gore said ``discussions of
the fund-raising calls for him and the president would not have been discussed''
at a key 1995 meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   The summary added that ``the issue of the vice president and the president
making fund-raising calls would have probably been referred to in the November
21 (1995) meeting, but probably only in passing.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore also said ``the number of telephone calls to be made by the president
and vice president was never discussed with him and he doubts that the issue was
ever discussed with the president,'' the FBI summary added.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore's account of the meeting took a new turn 10 months later when
handwritten notes turned up that appeared to quote the vice president as talking
about fund-raising phone calls at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   In the later FBI interview, Gore said 23 times that he was unable to recall
aspects of the Nov. 21, 1995 meeting and other fund-raising issues brought up by
questioners.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said he normally sits next to President Clinton in such meetings and
that the two sometimes consult while the meeting is going on, thereby missing
the surrounding discussion.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The vice president also observed that he drank a lot of iced tea during
meetings, which could have necessitated a restroom break,'' the FBI summary
stated. ``It was not uncommon for him, and for that matter the president, to
excuse themselves from meetings to use the restroom.''
</P>
<P>
	   One handwritten note from the Nov. 21 meeting states: ``VP: `Is it possible
to do a reallocation for me to take more of the events and the calls?''' The
vice president's allocation is typed in as 10 calls. Another note states: ``VP:
`Count me in on the calls.'''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore ``did not specifically recall the (reallocation) quote, seemingly
attributed to him,'' said the FBI summary. ``He offered that ... it sounds like
the kind of thing he would have said. ... He felt it was the role of the vice
president to take the load off the president. ... He also could not recall'' the
count-me-in ``quote on that page, also seemingly attributed to him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
