<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Leads Payroll; Bush in TV Ads  </HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN D. SALANT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush spent more money on television
advertising last year than any of the other presidential candidates still in the
race, a computer analysis of their latest spending reports shows.
</P>
<P>
	   Former Sen. Bill Bradley was second in TV spending, while his rival for the
Democratic nomination, Vice President Al Gore, had the largest payroll and
Republican Sen. John McCain's campaign spent more than one-third of its money on
fund raising, according to the analysis by the Campaign Study Group, a private
research organization.
</P>
<P>
	   Republican Bush, who has raised more than $70 million -- more than any other
presidential candidate ever -- spent more on television ads, $6.3 million, than
on payroll, $5.5 million, in 1999. Bob Dole, the 1996 GOP presidential nominee,
spent $7 million on TV throughout his campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush spent $10.1 million on fund raising, more than a fourth of the $37.3
million he spent on his campaign through Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
	   Unlike the other candidates, Bush is not accepting federal funds and
therefore can spend as much as he wants. The other candidates are limited to
spending about $40 million before the nominating conventions next summer.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush also spent $6.9 million on other ways to reach voters, including
campaign rallies, bumper stickers, phone banks, and mail such as a brochure sent
to Virginia voters touting his record on education.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's important to look at it in terms of voter contact,'' Bush spokesman
Scott McClellan said. ``We are maximizing our resources to reach the greatest
number of voters in the early key primary states.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, meanwhile, spent $14.2 million through Dec. 31, with more than a
third, $5.7 million, going for fund raising. He raised $15.7 million last year,
including $2 million transferred from his Senate campaign account.
</P>
<P>
	   ``That was the disadvantage McCain faced,'' said Herbert Alexander,
professor emeritus of political science at the University of Southern
California. ``Back then, he had to scrounge. He had a relatively impoverished
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
	   Since the reports were filed, McCain turned his Feb. 1 victory in New
Hampshire into a fund-raising bonanza, taking in more than $1 million over the
Internet the next day.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Democratic side, Gore spent almost as much money last year on his
campaign payroll than President Clinton spent during the entire 1996 re-election
campaign. Clinton spent $6.4 million on salaries. Gore spent $5.7 million
through Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
	   The vice president moved his campaign headquarters from Washington to
Nashville, Tenn., in October to cut costs and pare staff. Even so, he spent $1.1
million on rent and utilities in 1999, more than any other candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   Alexander noted that Gore must limit his spending because he is accepting
taxpayer funds for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He's got to worry about what happens once he gets the nomination,''
Alexander said. ``Because of the challenge by Bradley, he had to spend
considerably more than he should have. He didn't conserve enough for the year
2000.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore raised $29 million for his campaign while spending $23.2 million,
including $6.9 million to raise the money.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley took in $27.8 million while spending $19.5 million, including $3.8
million -- far less than Gore -- to get it.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley's payroll was almost $1 million less than Gore's for the same
period, allowing the former New Jersey senator to spend 50 percent more than the
vice president on TV ads -- $4.2 million to Gore's $2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Bill Bradley has outspent us on television everywhere, but we've
out-organized him on the ground,'' Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley campaign officials did not return a call seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0125 </TRAILER>
