<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Drops Negative Bush Ads  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURA MECKLER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fearing a backlash from his sharp attacks, Sen. John
McCain is returning to the campaign strategy that fueled his remarkable rise in
the Republican presidential race, again focusing on his dramatic personal story.
</P>
<P>
	   The abrupt change of strategy came after advisers determined the commercials
that went after Texas Gov. George W. Bush were compromising McCain's campaign as
a self-styled political outsider. McCain's new ad, released Friday, embraces his
character and courage, early themes for the maverick senator from Arizona.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In Vietnam, John McCain stood up to his communist captors and refused
early release from prison,'' an announcer tells views. ``In Washington, he's a
leader attacking big government waste. Attacking the special interests.''
</P>
<P>
	   A week away from this state's critical Republican primary, McCain urged Bush
to follow suit and pledge to run strictly positive ads.
</P>
<P>
	   ``For the rest of this campaign, we will put up positive ads,'' McCain told
reporters in New York City. ``I'd like to encourage Governor Bush to do the same
thing. I hope that he will recognize the damage that this kind of thing does to
the electorate.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush quickly rejected the proposal, suggesting that McCain's decision was an
act of politics, not principle.
</P>
<P>
	   ``That's an old Washington trick. It's a bait-and-switch trick. He runs ads
for 18 days defining me for something I'm not, and then all of a sudden says,
`OK, let's all be quiet.' I'm going to make sure that the people understand
exactly what I believe and exactly where I stand,'' Bush said between campaign
stops in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
	   The fracas began in the New Hampshire primary campaign, when a McCain ad
said that Bush did not set ``one dime'' from the surplus to protect Social
Security's future -- a charge whose accuracy depends on how the surplus is
defined.
</P>
<P>
	   When that spot aired in South Carolina, Bush fired back with an ad saying
McCain was distorting the truth. That prompted a pair of McCain ads that
compared Bush and his truth-telling to President Clinton. A Bush ad then
suggested McCain is a hypocrite on campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
	   But after a surge of momentum generated by a landslide New Hampshire
victory, McCain's own polling showed his progress slowed because of negative ads
by both campaigns. The surveys did not pick up major slippage but confirmed the
suspicion of some advisers that McCain's ads -- particularly ones linking Bush
to Clinton -- tarnished his clean-scrubbed political image.
</P>
<P>
	   Exit polls from Tuesday's Delaware primary showed about one quarter of the
Republican voters said McCain had made unfair attacks on his rivals.
</P>
<P>
	   The primary concern in McCain's camp, however, was voter turnout. His
advisers fear that the campaign's nasty tone is alienating independent and
Democratic voters who are the cornerstone of his campaign. Regardless of who
voters blame for the negative turn of events, McCain stands to lose the most if
the atmosphere suppresses turnout, his advisers concluded.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's no question that a negative war is going to lower turnout. We want
more people to come,'' said campaign manager Rick Davis. ``The more people who
show up the better off we are.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's camp, believing that McCain's ads only hurt McCain, had little
interest in letting the issue die. Bush released a new ad Friday that begins by
reminding viewers of McCain's charge: ``Politics is tough,'' Bush says, ``but
when John McCain compared me to Bill Clinton and said I was untrustworthy,
that's over the line.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's advisers say they plan to air another ad this weekend that is sharply
critical of the Arizonan. Though they may be forced to tone down upcoming ads in
response to McCain's challenge, aides said they do not plan to abandon their
strategy to redefine McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This guy runs two weeks of negative ads comparing us to Bill Clinton and
now he wants ease up? This is a guy who will say one thing and do another,''
said Bush strategist Karl Rove. ``He's bowing to the negative consequences of
accusing us of being like President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain strategist Mike Murphy said his candidate was forced to attack after
Bush went negative, and was returning to his positive instincts. ``We had to
punch back to let our supporters know we're not like Bill Bradley,'' Murphy
said, referring to the Democratic candidate who was slow to respond to Al Gore's
criticisms.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's top advisers, including Murphy and Davis, had tentatively decided
to recommend a change in strategy Thursday, when a woman stood up in a McCain
event and emotionally accused Bush's campaign of making negative calls to South
Carolina Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain denounced Bush's campaign. The decision was sealed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The senator has good instincts,'' Davis said. ``He knew we couldn't go
negative after that.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE -- AP Writer Beth Beth Gardiner in New York contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0125 </TRAILER>
