<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Defends His Record in Senate  </HEADLINE>
   By MATT KELLEY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite some high-profile losses, Sen. John McCain's
legislative record includes successes in giving the president line-item veto
power, banning lobbyist gifts and helping elderly wage-earners.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's defeats on campaign finance reform and the 1998 tobacco settlement
are well known. His GOP presidential rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, portrays
McCain as a do-nothing lawmaker rather than the maverick reformer McCain claims
to be.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said Friday he succeeded during his 17 years in Congress in reforming
Washington politics and helping to cut government regulation of business.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I've passed more legislation than any other senator in the last session of
Congress,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   The record shows McCain successfully backed laws banning senators from
taking lobbyists' gifts, reducing the ``earnings test'' that cuts Social
Security benefits for the working elderly and giving the president line-item
veto authority, which the Supreme Court later struck down.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain also has worked to block taxes on Internet commerce and has helped
pressure TV networks make their ratings system more understandable.
</P>
<P>
	   At least one Bush supporter, Sen. Bob Bennett, R-Utah, said the governor's
criticism was off base.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's not fair to say McCain has been an ineffective senator,'' said
Bennett, citing McCain's work on military and business issues as successes.
</P>
<P>
	   Conversely, McCain has been on the losing side of issues ranging from
changing rules for telephone and cable television companies to authorizing
ground troops in the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He's had a series of amendments on domestic and international issues that
haven't gone anyplace,'' said American University political science professor
James Thurber. ``His best coalition was behind campaign finance reform, and he
didn't get 60 votes to overcome a filibuster.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain entered the campaign finance fray during his first term as one of the
``Keating five'' senators with links to Arizona financier Charles Keating, whose
Lincoln Savings &AMP; Loan went under and cost the government $3.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate Ethics Committee said in 1991 that McCain had shown ``poor
judgment'' -- but did not break the rules -- by meeting with thrift regulators
after taking campaign money and vacation trips from Keating. Stung, McCain began
a drive to curtail political spending by special interest groups.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain and Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., have offered a series of campaign
finance reform bills, failing every year since 1996 to get the 60 supporters
needed to force a vote.
</P>
<P>
	   The fight has alienated some of McCain's Republican colleagues in the
Senate, who said his talk of the insidious influence of special interests tarred
all senators as corrupt.
</P>
<P>
	   Another uphill battle for McCain was tobacco. Asked by GOP leaders to handle
the legislation needed to implement a settlement of states' health lawsuits,
McCain became a zealous advocate of a measure that would have raised at least
$156 billion over 25 years by raising cigarette taxes. Republican opposition
killed the measure, and opponents criticized McCain for offering a tax increase.
</P>
<P>
	   As chairman of the Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee,
McCain backed laws to limit businesses' liability for Y2K glitches and to impose
a moratorium on taxing Internet businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was the lone Republican to vote against the sweeping 1996
telecommunications bill, saying it did not go far enough to spur competition in
telephone and cable television markets.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain also has pressed for more and longer flights to and from Reagan
National Airport near Washington, saying that would lead to lower fares and more
room for smaller airlines.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics have pointed out that the rules McCain championed would help some
large campaign donors, such as Arizona-based America West Airlines and regional
telephone company U S West. McCain says he has often voted against the interests
of campaign donors.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain headed the Indian Affairs Committee before taking over at the
Commerce Committee in 1997. He has drawn praise from tribal leaders for writing
bills that help tribes run government programs themselves, protect Indian
religious freedom and promote reservation economic development.
</P>
<P>
	   On social issues, McCain has opposed abortion and gun control and has
supported the death penalty and government-funded vouchers for private schools.
</P>
<P>
	   He voted last year to convict President Clinton on both impeachment counts.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain is a former Navy pilot who was shot down and spent 5 1/2 years as a
prisoner of war in Vietnam. He led a drive to restore formal relations with the
communist country.
</P>
<P>
	   He has criticized U.S. military involvement in Lebanon, Somalia and Bosnia,
but has worked to block efforts to cut funding for the Bosnia mission after
troops were stationed there.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, a member of the Armed Services Committee, has supported efforts to
raise military pay and boost military readiness but repeatedly voted against
what he called unnecessary Pentagon spending, such as the Seawolf submarine and
the B-2 bomber.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
