<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Voting Record of Sen. John McCain  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   From the voting record of Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.:
ABORTION:
</P>
<P>
	   Has opposed abortion, voting against allowing abortions at federally funded
clinics or military hospitals, supporting a ban on a late-term abortion
procedure opponents call ``partial birth abortion'' and voting to deny federal
employees insurance coverage for abortions. Some anti-abortion activists have
criticized McCain's vote in 1997 against a ban on research using fetal tissue.
CRIME/GUNS:
</P>
<P>
	   Voted repeatedly against gun control measures such as a five-day waiting
period before buying a handgun. Supported 1999 measure requiring background
checks for purchasers at gun shows and mandating trigger locks. Supported the
federal death penalty, including for killers who were under 18 at the time of
the crime, and measures to restrict death row inmates' appeals.
MILITARY:
</P>
<P>
	   Opposed some military spending he called unnecessary, such as the Seawolf
submarine and the B-2 bomber. Voted against delaying the military base-closing
process. Opposed a 1991 measure to lift the ban on women flying combat missions,
but also opposed a 1998 measure to require separate training for male and female
troops. Opposed allowing homosexuals to serve openly in the military. Criticized
sending troops to Lebanon, Somalia and Bosnia but voted in 1999 to preserve
funding for the Bosnia military mission.
EDUCATION:
</P>
<P>
	   Supported plans to issue government-funded vouchers to send students to
private schools. Supported cutting federal funding to schools that deny students
the right to voluntarily pray. Opposed allowing schools to distribute condoms or
other contraceptives without parental consent. Opposed President Clinton's
proposals to hire 100,000 new teachers. Supported merit pay and national testing
for teachers.
ENVIRONMENT:
</P>
<P>
	   Opposed allowing ``salvage'' logging in spotted owl habitat. Supported
charging mining companies market value for mining claims on federal land.
Opposed raising grazing fees on federal land. Opposed setting aside California
desert wilderness area.
SOCIAL SECURITY:
</P>
<P>
	   Sponsored several unsuccessful measures to eliminate the ``earnings test,''
which reduces Social Security benefits for the working elderly. Supported
successful drive to raise the amount of income exempt from the earnings test.
CAMPAIGN FINANCE:
</P>
<P>
	   Co-sponsored a series of bills that failed to gain the 60 votes needed to
end a filibuster. First version would have banned donations from political
action committees and would have offered free and reduced-cost broadcast time to
candidates who adhered to voluntary spending limits. Next version would have
restricted some political advertising by groups not directly affiliated with
candidates and banned ``soft money'' -- the unlimited donations to political
parties that may be used to buy ads supporting or opposing candidates on the
issues. Latest version would only ban soft money.
INDIAN ISSUES:
</P>
<P>
	   Blocked a drive to repeal the Indian Child Welfare Act, which gives Indian
relatives the first opportunity to give foster care or adopt Indian children.
Sponsored bills to expand and streamline the process for tribes to take over
operations of government programs. Backed the Indian Gaming Regulatory Act,
which sets the framework for tribes to offer gambling on reservations. Backed
measures to protect Indian sacred sites and promote Indian religious freedom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0126 </TRAILER>
