<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Sites 'Clinton Fatigue'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- ``Clinton fatigue'' is the term politicians use for the
suspicion that voters may tilt Republican this year because they're growing
tired of President Clinton and those associated with him after seven years in
office.
</P>
<P>
	   Tongue in cheek, Clinton gave the term a different twist Friday when asked
by a reporter what he thought of ``Clinton fatigue'' and whether ``Clinton
fatigue'' might limit his campaigning for Democrats this year.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Well, I get tired from time to time,'' he said. ``That's the only one I'm
familiar with.''
</P>
<P>
	   But he went on to say that he gets more requests to appear at political
events than he can handle.
</P>
<P>
	   Anyway, ``I always feel that people running for office are the best judge of
what's in their own interest, not me,'' he added. ``And I got plenty to do
here.''
</P>
<P>
	   CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Another stretch on the road has yielded another
batch of ``Bushisms.''
</P>
<P>
	   Texas Gov. George W. Bush remarked to an audience at the seaside resort of
Kiawah Island on Friday that he was raised in the desert.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Last time I saw this much money, I mean water,'' Bush said, as the
well-heeled crowd laughed. Bush ignored his slip and plowed ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   Later, addressing a student audience at the College of Charleston, Bush
said: ``I'm loving because I can't stand the politics of pitting one generation
of people against another.'' He was trying to explain why he is running for
president.
</P>
<P>
	   At another point, Bush spoke about a generation that has become wealthy
through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These young kids, who have become rich beyond their means,'' he said,
intending to say rich beyond their years.
</P>
<P>
	   During an earlier 18-day stretch through Iowa and New Hampshire, the
governor showed he could flub words just like his dad, former President Bush.
The governor congratulated pupils at an elementary school on their theme of the
month, perseverance, but repeatedly called it preservation.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   BY THE NUMBERS:
</P>
<P>
	   $2.3 million -- Amount of money raised by Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch in his
failed bid for the GOP nomination, as of Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
	   $2.1 million -- Amount of money raised by perennial Democratic candidate
Lyndon LaRouche in his 2000 campaign, as of Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   VOTER'S VOICE:
</P>
<P>
	   ``McCain seems like a fresh, hard-charging guy. Besides, I could wreak havoc
on them Republicans.'' Naylor Smith of Camden, S.C., a loyal Democrat who plans
to vote for McCain in the Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   THIS DATE FOUR YEARS AGO
</P>
<P>
	   Republican Lamar Alexander predicted: ``By the time we get out of New
Hampshire, there will be two candidates who really have a chance to be nominated
and elected. And one will be Senator Dole and the other will be me.''
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton drew huge crowds in two frenzied days of Iowa campaigning.
In a state soaked with negative GOP ads, he let Iowa sidekick Sen. Tom Harkin
carve up the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   The Democrats' real opposition is the Republican House speaker, Harkin said.
``It's Newt Gingrich and his radical right-wing agenda.'' He added: ``Actually,
I like to call them Newtie and the blowhards.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   FRIDAY'S ROUNDUP
</P>
<P>
	   Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura broke free of the ``hopelessly dysfunctional''
Reform Party and recommended his state party do the same.
</P>
<P>
	   George W. Bush called on McCain to release names of all his Internet donors
and mocked McCain for raising money from special interests while championing
campaign finance reform. McCain, raising money in New York City, said it is a
``legitimate concern'' that fighting between the Republican candidates could
weaken the eventual nominee in the general election. He also said he won't run
any more negative ads.
</P>
<P>
	   Vice President Al Gore conceded his position on abortion has shifted over
the years and accused Bill Bradley of trying to drive a wedge between Democrats.
Bradley said Gore, who now speaks in favor of abortion rights, should explain
why he changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   WEEKEND'S TRAIL:
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley and Gore both campaign in California today, speaking to the state
Democratic convention. Bush campaigns in South Carolina today before flying to
Texas and taking Sunday off. McCain campaigns in South Carolina through the
weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
