<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Party Strikes Back at Ventura  </HEADLINE>
   By ROCHELLE OLSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Reform Party is striking back at its dissenting
top officeholder, Jesse Ventura, by moving to oust chairman Jack Gargan, an ally
of the Minnesota governor.
</P>
<P>
	   Ventura's break with the national party on Friday was timed to pre-empt the
national party's meeting here today, at which members loyal to founder Ross
Perot were expected to vote to topple Gargan.
</P>
<P>
	   Gargan, who took office Jan. 1, has been unable to control the warring
factions loyal to Ventura and Perot. Members have fought each other over the
Internet, in the press and in court over the direction of the party, its rules,
where to hold the nominating convention and whom to support for president this
year.
</P>
<P>
	   The battling has hobbled the Reform Party on the cusp of an election year in
which it will bestow $12.6 million in federal funds upon its presidential
candidate. Indeed, it threatens the future of a party that put Ventura into the
highest elective office in the organization's history.
</P>
<P>
	   At a news conference Friday outside the governor's mansion in St. Paul,
Ventura said the Nashville meeting today would only cripple the party's national
growth.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Jack Gargan was elected through a total, fair process to be the leader of
our party, and tomorrow they're holding a meeting where they're going to try to
vote him out as the leader of the party,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They're trying to do it illegally,'' Ventura added, referring to the much
fought-over party rules. ``You have a small group of power brokers in this party
that won't allow it to grow nationally, and that's not conducive to what we want
to do in Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gargan arrived Friday afternoon at a Nashville airport hotel, the meeting
site, while maintaining that the gathering would be held in violation of the
party's rules.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the Minnesota state Reform Party was holding its own meeting
today, at which Ventura ally and state chairman Rick McCluhan was expected to
ask the state central committee to call a convention March 4 to vote on
disaffiliation.
</P>
<P>
	   Ventura and his supporters have never been close to the national Reform
Party. Perot, who ran for president in 1996 under the Reform banner, provided no
help in the governor's 1998 victory.
</P>
<P>
	   The party has been struggling ever since, not only to settle on leadership
but to find a unifying set of beliefs aside from a common disenchantment with
the Democratic and Republican parties.
</P>
<P>
	   Ventura said the national party had played ``zero'' role in his election;
meanwhile, former Reform chairman Russ Verney, a close Perot ally, said Ventura
provided ``zero'' leadership for the party. The governor's departure will have a
minimal impact, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It means that we're free of threats and we can once again go back to
grass-roots democracy where every elected leader of the party can respond to
their constituents instead of to ultimatums,'' Verney said.
</P>
<P>
	   Indeed, Ventura has never shown much interest in building the Minnesota or
national Reform parties. Some political observers considered Friday's move
merely the latest in a continuing sideshow.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It would be comical if it weren't so pathetic: the range of candidates
considering a Reform Party candidacy, the squabbling, the egomania,'' said
Thomas Mann, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, a Washington think
tank.
</P>
<P>
	   Former independent presidential candidate John Anderson called the Reform
Party ``badly fractured,'' but he held out hope for Ventura's role in a
third-party movement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think he could be the modern-day equivalent of the leader of a populist
revolt against the two-party system,'' Anderson said. He added that he, at 77,
would consider another presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
	   The third-party movement now represented by Reform was founded by Perot as
his vehicle in presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
	   The Texas billionaire won 8 percent of the popular vote in 1996, down from
19 percent in 1992 when he barreled onto the scene as an independent voice
agitating for balanced budgets, a tough stance on trade and campaign reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0130 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Church Battle Over First Amendment  </HEADLINE>
   By AMALIE YOUNG Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- A United Methodist church has been told by a city
official to limit worship services, sparking what could be a landmark fight over
the church's constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
	   Derek Davis, a Baylor University religion scholar, said he believes this is
the first time a government official has tried to limit attendance at a
particular church.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's astonishing,'' said Mark Reid, co-pastor at Sunnyside Centenary
United Methodist Church. ``It's really out in left field to say that you can
only have a certain number of people in worship.''
</P>
<P>
	   Elizabeth Normand, the land-use hearing officer who issued the Jan. 17
ruling, said she doesn't understand what all the fuss is about. The target of
her ruling was a meals program for the homeless at the church.
</P>
<P>
	   Between 70 and 100 people attend the twice-a-week meals program, which is in
its 16th year. Normand's ruling would cancel the dinners.
</P>
<P>
	   Sunnyside is one of many older neighborhoods in Portland that has gone
upscale recently. Neighborhood concerns about the meals program have escalated
in the last two years, with some residents complaining of alcohol- and
drug-related activities and disturbances by people who attend the Wednesday and
Friday dinners.
</P>
<P>
	   The neighborhood association had asked the city to end the meals program at
the 100-year-old church.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We've been there for a long time, and the congregation has a long history
of trying to do social ministries,'' said Tim Lewis, co-pastor at the church.
``Some people in the neighborhood who haven't been there very long have very
little understanding of what the church has been doing.''
</P>
<P>
	   Lewis said that the church voluntarily shut down the meals program for three
months. They also started a telephone line for neighbors to call in concerns,
hired a security guard and trained a foot-patrol to walk the neighborhood during
the program.
</P>
<P>
	   Even so, problems persisted.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Somehow, the people seem to blame us for whatever happens in the
neighborhood,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
	   But Normand's 30-page ruling also put a limit on the number of people who
can attend worship services, although it is not clear why she did that.
</P>
<P>
	   She has declined to explain her reasoning, calling the matter a
``quasi-judicial process.''
</P>
<P>
	   Her ruling also places conditions on the operation of Sunnyside's nighttime
shelter, a day-care center and its Indochinese Socialization Center.
</P>
<P>
	   Normand is perplexed that her decision to limit attendance at Sunnyside has
so passionately stirred the emotions of Portland's religious community.
</P>
<P>
	   ``That was not the main focus of the decision and it's interesting that this
is the thing everyone is talking about,'' she told The Oregonian. ``I'm getting
calls from citizens, newspapers, television stations, you name it.''
</P>
<P>
	   The church plans to appeal the decision in a March City Council hearing.
</P>
<P>
	   Reid said the ruling has brought some blessings, because local religious
groups have banded together to denounce the decision.
</P>
<P>
	   Rabbi Joseph Wolf of Havurah Shalom called Normand's ruling an infringement
of religious freedoms protected by the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think very clearly the distinction being drawn in very arbitrary and
specious,'' he said. ``The church or synagogue is open to celebrate all week
long ... especially to dine and come to the table with one another and offer
prayer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0133 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
