<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Citrus Canker Emergency Declared  </HEADLINE>
   By JACKIE HALLIFAX Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Florida has already cut down and burned 500,000
trees in the war on citrus canker, many of them in back yards in Miami and Fort
Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
	   But state leaders say more must be done -- and fast.
</P>
<P>
	   The goal is to eradicate canker in south Florida in a year to protect the
state's $8 billion citrus industry and residential citrus trees. The cost: $110
million and the destruction of probably a million more trees.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, Bush declared a state of emergency in Miami-Dade, Broward and
four other counties to free money to speed the state's eradication program. The
state has been battling canker, mostly in Miami-Dade and Broward counties, since
1995.
</P>
<P>
	   Now, Bush said, ``it's time to take it up a notch or two.''
</P>
<P>
	   Agriculture Commissioner Bob Crawford said the state must fight harder to
block the canker's destructive spread.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If we don't do it, the scientists assure me that it's all over and we've
lost, and it'll spread throughout the state,'' he said. ``Next we'll lose our
citrus industry, and people will lose their backyard trees as well.''
</P>
<P>
	   The emergency declaration allows a $35 million withdrawal from a state
emergency fund to fight the disease. Florida officials hope the federal
government will cover some of the rest.
</P>
<P>
	   Canker-infected trees show lesions on the leaves, stems and fruit. The
disease causes the fruit to fall prematurely and ultimately can kill the tree.
Burning exposed trees is the only way to prevent its spread.
</P>
<P>
	   Growers consider canker the primary threat to their industry and support the
eradication plan, according to Ron Hamel, executive vice president of Gulf
Citrus Growers Association, which represents 160 growers in southwest Florida.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The sooner the better as far as we're concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The state already has lost 200,000 residential trees and 300,000 trees in
commercial groves to the disease. The plan announced Friday increases the range
in which exposed or infected trees must be cut and the number of crews working
to cut and burn the infected trees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0139 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grozny Refugees Fear of No Return  </HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW KRAMER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SLEPTSOVSKAYA, Russia (AP) -- A push by Russian troops to flush out the last
remaining rebels in Grozny raises little hope among refugees of returning soon.
There is hardly anything to go home to in the ruins of the Chechen capital.
</P>
<P>
	   ``When I left, whole buildings just didn't exist anymore,'' said Adam
Aktamirov, 41, who fled the city for neighboring Ingushetia in January as
Russian troops battled rebels for Grozny.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There are no roofs left. Nobody will go back. Where will they go?'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Nearly a week after Russian troops claimed to have the city under control,
Russian authorities appear to have no firm plans on returning the population of
the nearly deserted city. For now, they remain in tent camps near the border.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In principle, not one important question regarding the refugees has been
decided,'' said Timirkhan Akiyev, an official in the Migration Service in
Ingushetia, the Russian province on Chechnya's border.
</P>
<P>
	   Although Russia has pressured refugees from other parts of Chechnya to
return home as towns are secured, officials often express doubts about whether
Grozny residents can ever go home.
</P>
<P>
	   The military commander of Grozny, Maj. Gen. Vasily Prizemlin, has said the
city is uninhabitable.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's unlikely that the peaceful population will come back because the
entire city is ruined,'' he told the NTV television station last week after
troops raised a flag over the city center.
</P>
<P>
	   Former Grozny residents interviewed in camps said most apartment blocks in
the city were destroyed beyond repair, although some private homes may be
salvageable.
</P>
<P>
	   The city that now is a grim ruin -- its streets so wrecked that even tanks
have difficulty on them -- once was far different. Before the first Chechen war
started in 1994, Grozny had a population of 675,000, spread out in leafy suburbs
overlooking two rivers in the foothills of the Caucasus Mountains.
</P>
<P>
	   That war, which ended in 1996, wrecked much of the city. But 400,000 people
still lived there as of last summer, when the new fighting began, said Magomed
Gireyev, director of the Ingush Migration Service.
</P>
<P>
	   About 70,000 former residents are now refugees in Ingushetia, he said.
Others left for villages and towns inside Chechnya, and an estimated 15,000 to
40,000 remained in the city through five months of bombing.
</P>
<P>
	   The hardest-hit areas of the city were neighborhoods of high-rise apartment
blocks, refugees say. The buildings were used as fortresses in the street
fighting, and are now porous ruins.
</P>
<P>
	   Many refugees from these areas said they despair of ever returning.
</P>
<P>
	   Some people who lived in private homes on the city's outskirts said they
want to return eventually, but for now fear attacks on civilians by the Russian
troops and the possibility that rebels will stage a sneak attack on the city, as
they did during the 1994-6 war.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Russian officials appear to have stalled on deciding what to do
with the city, won at the cost of hundreds of dead soldiers and at least
hundreds of civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
	   President Vladimir Putin's envoy to Chechnya, Nikolai Koshman, said that
``today there is no money,'' to repair the city.
</P>
<P>
	   ``First we must study the scale of the destruction, then we can speak about
the future of the Chechen capital,'' he said. Koshman has earlier suggested
moving the capital to Gudermes, a smaller city east of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
	   Only a few refugees contemplate going home, and for them it is not a joyous
choice.
</P>
<P>
	   Magomed Usmanov, 34, who lived in the suburb of Staraya Sunzha on the city's
outskirts, said he hopes to return and rebuild his one-story house, explaining
``I have nowhere to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0146 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani: 'Give me a break, I'm running'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - Five days after Hillary Rodham Clinton
formally announced she is running for the U.S. Senate, Rudolph Giuliani
informally did the same.
<P>
	   "Give me a break, I'm running," the New York City mayor said in his feisty
fashion. For Clinton, it had been, "I am honored today to announce my candidacy
for the U.S. Senate from New York."
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani's statement was no surprise. Like Clinton, he has been campaigning
for months, but it was the first time he had announced it so forthrightly. It
came after a stump speech on the porch of the clapboard house that serves as
party headquarters for the Westchester County Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked if he was an official candidate, he said, "I don't know what an
official candidate is. I am very interested in running. I am running. Look what
I'm doing, I'm not walking. ... Give me a break, I'm running."
</P>
<P>
	   Until Friday, Giuliani had found various ways to avoid saying that. He came
closest when he said, "Looks that way" when a questioner asked if he planned to
run.
</P>
<P>
	   But he also said, "There's always doubt."
</P>
<P>
	   His campaign manager, Bruce Teitelbaum, said Friday that the mayor's
statement "should not be construed as his official announcement. ... There may
not be one."
</P>
<P>
	   Westchester County Republican Chairman Jim Cavanaugh said the mayor told
lunch companions that he didn't want to make "a Hollywood-style announcement."
</P>
<P>
	   "By kind of slipping it in like that, that seems to be how he wants to do
it," Cavanaugh said.
</P>
<P>
	   But the chairman himself was happy that his party headquarters was the scene
of the announcement. "Maybe we'll put up a plaque," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton campaign spokeswoman Karen Dunn said, "We welcome the mayor to the
race. Maybe now he will start talking about what he would do as a United States
senator."
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton made her formal announcement Sunday, in a college gymnasium packed
with thousands of supporters and bedecked with red, white and blue posters.
Giuliani's statement Friday came before about 150 people, many of them local
Republican officials, on the porch, the snowy lawn and the sidewalk outside the
party headquarters.
</P>
<P>
	   In his speech, the mayor poked fun at Clinton's house-hunting in
Westchester.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't know what all the fuss is about," he said. "I'm just hanging around
here looking for a house."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-12-00 0147 </TRAILER>
