<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Jets Found With Tail Problems  </HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW FORDAHL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- An equipment problem suspected in the crash of Alaska
Airlines Flight 261 has cropped up in at least five other jetliners this week
during government-ordered inspections.
</P>
<P>
	   The MD-80 and MD-90 aircraft were found with unusual metal shavings in or
around a control mechanism in their tail wings, National Transportation Safety
Board officials said Friday. The same equipment in the doomed plane was found in
a similar condition.
</P>
<P>
	   The latest cases, involving one Alaska Airlines and two Delta Air Lines
jets, were uncovered Friday during inspections ordered by the Federal Aviation
Administration. Two Alaska Airlines jets were grounded earlier for the same
reason, prompting the FAA's action.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials have not determined whether the damaged horizontal stabilizer
assembly found in Flight 261's wreckage caused the crash or was a result of the
crash's impact. But pilots had reported trouble with the stabilizer, which helps
keep a plane flying level, before Flight 261 plummeted into the Pacific Ocean on
Jan. 31, killing all 88 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
	   FAA officials declined to comment on the NTSB's announcement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have initial, unconfirmed reports that we need to verify before we
release any information,'' said Paul Takemoto, an agency spokesman.
</P>
<P>
	   The FAA's inspection order affects about 1,200 planes, including MD-80s,
MD-90s, Boeing 717s and DC-9s. The first part of the inspections must be
completed by Monday, but the FAA is giving airlines 30 days to perform a more
detailed check.
</P>
<P>
	   Delta mechanics found two MD-90s with a gritty residue below the horizontal
stabilizer and took the aircraft out of service at least until today.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're continuing to look at the planes and analyzing the residue, but we
strongly suspect we'll have these planes back in service tomorrow,'' said Clay
McConnell, a Delta spokesman. ``There is absolutely nothing to indicate anything
other than normal wear.''
</P>
<P>
	   Alaska Airlines confirmed it had pulled a third plane from service due to a
mechanical problem discovered during the inspection in Portland, Ore. The
carrier would not disclose whether the problem was related to metal shavings.
</P>
<P>
	   Alaska Airlines canceled a dozen flights Friday as it repeated inspections
made before the FAA issued its order, said spokesman Jack Evans.
</P>
<P>
	   Other airlines reported no major schedule disruptions, but several reported
finding irregularities during the inspections.
</P>
<P>
	   Continental Airlines said a quarter-inch metal shaving was found in the tail
wing mechanism of an out-of-service MD-80 undergoing scheduled maintenance. The
problem was reported to the FAA, but all other inspections were uneventful, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Northwest Airlines pulled a DC-9 from service after unspecified
irregularities were found in the tail wing assembly. The section was removed for
analysis and the plane was expected to fly again today, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
	   American Airlines mechanics in Reno, Nev., discovered an MD-90's tail wing
assembly needed lubrication, but there was no evidence of unusual wear,
spokesman John Hotard said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The FAA was there and signed off and the aircraft was returned to
service,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Investigators probing the crash of Alaska Flight 261 are focusing on a part
that moves the stabilizer, a 40-foot wing high on the tail that controls the
up-and-down pitch of the aircraft's nose.
</P>
<P>
	   A 2-foot, rod-like jackscrew that drives the stabilizer was recovered with
metal shavings believed to have come from an 8-inch gimbal nut -- also retrieved
from the Pacific -- and found to have damaged threads.
</P>
<P>
	   An Associated Press review of maintenance records from 1990 through 1999
found no reports of stripped gimbal nuts in the jetliners covered in the order.
</P>
<P>
	   During voluntary inspections early this week, Alaska mechanics in Portland
and Seattle found two MD-80s with similar shavings in the horizontal stabilizer
assemblies, prompting the FAA's nationwide mandatory inspection order.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the Ventura County Medical Examiner's office has identified the
remains of 35 of the passengers, a spokeswoman said Friday. The office has not
received any new remains since Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Navy reported it recovered significant pieces of wreckage from the ocean
Friday. Among them were large portions of the plane's left and right elevators,
which are part of the horizontal stabilizer system. Also found was an 8-foot
section of the plane's outboard right stabilizer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0204 </TRAILER>
