<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blake Signs With Saints  </HEADLINE>
    By JOSH DUBOW AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   While the New Orleans Saints and Atlanta Falcons began the NFL free-agency
period by filling holes, the San Francisco 49ers still need to shed some salary
before they can begin rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
	   The three bottom teams in the NFC West made some of the biggest news in the
NFL on Friday, the first day teams could sign free agents.
</P>
<P>
	   The Saints signed quarterback Jeff Blake to a $17.4 million, four-year
contract, and the Falcons reportedly agreed to terms with cornerback Ashley
Ambrose and wide receiver Shawn Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
	   The 49ers, meanwhile, told Jerry Rice he could be forced out of San
Francisco unless he makes financial concessions to help the 49ers gain
maneuvering room within the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
	   "We would very much like to have Jerry back," 49ers coach Steve Mariucci
said. "The question would be, how do we work it out?"
</P>
<P>
	   Over the last three weeks, the 49ers restructured the contracts of 14
players, including quarterback Steve Young, in an effort to wipe out a $24
million cap overrun.
</P>
<P>
	   However, the 49ers still need more room under the cap to be able to take
part in free agency and to pay their draft picks.
</P>
<P>
	   Rice, 37, the NFL's career receiving leader, has a 2000 cap figure of $5.49
million that the 49ers want to reduce.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, Rice and his agent, Jim Steiner, have balked at the 49ers'
insistence he lower his salary and try to make up for it through an
incentive-based package.
</P>
<P>
	   San Francisco did sign one player, agreeing with cornerback Monty Montgomery
to a one-year contract worth $385,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Blake started most of last season for Cincinnati after rookie Akili Smith
was hurt. Blake completed 55.3 percent of his passes for 16 touchdowns with 14
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
	   The presence of Smith, the third overall pick in last year's draft, made
Blake expendable in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
	   "I see this as a fresh start and a great opportunity," Blake said. "I'm very
happy to be in a position where I don't have to look over my shoulder all the
time. I can just relax and play here. My confidence is very high."
</P>
<P>
	   Blake will step in for Danny Wuerffel and Billy Joe Hobert, who became free
agents on Friday as the Saints begin the rebuilding process.
</P>
<P>
	   New Orleans finished 3-13 last season, its seventh straight year without a
winning record, and coach Mike Ditka and general manager Bill Kuharich were
fired last month.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think over the next week to 10 days we should be able to help the team,"
new GM Randy Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Saints lost Ambrose, who signed a $22.5 million, five-year contract with
the Falcons, according to CBS Sportsline. The Web site also reported that the
Falcons signed Jefferson to a $14.2 million, four-year deal.
</P>
<P>
	   Ambrose has 24 career interceptions, including six in 1999. He signed a
two-year contract with New Orleans before last season, but the Saints voided the
final year of the deal. They hoped to re-sign him, but talks broke down this
week.
</P>
<P>
	   Jefferson had 40 catches for 698 yards and five touchdowns for New England
last season. He will fill the void left by Tony Martin, who was released by
Atlanta before the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Dallas is close to an agreement to trade its first-round pick to
Seattle for free agent receiver Joey Galloway. The Cowboys would then sign
Galloway -- the Seahawks' franchise player -- for more than $5 million a year,
according to today's Dallas Morning News.
</P>
<P>
	   One of the most coveted free agents, Jacksonville running back James
Stewart, visited Detroit on Friday as the Lions continued a search for a
replacement for Barry Sanders.
</P>
<P>
	   Stewart, who rushed for 931 yards and 13 touchdowns with the Jaguars last
season in place of injured Fred Taylor, will also visit Cleveland this weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   The Browns agreed to terms Friday with defensive tackle Darius Holland on a
two-year contract.
</P>
<P>
	   The Browns also said they will bring in free agent defensive ends Orpheus
Roye and Keith McKenzie for visits this weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   Cleveland had hoped to court Arizona's Simeon Rice and Jacksonville's Tony
Brackens during the free-agent signing period that began Friday. But the star
defensive ends were designated franchise players by their teams in the past
three days.
</P>
<P>
	   In other moves, Jacksonville re-signed linebacker Lonnie Marts, Baltimore
signed offensive lineman Damon Denson, and the Super Bowl champion St. Louis
Rams re-signed tight end Ernie Conwell to a $3.9 million, three-year contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
