<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Suspends Belfast Cabinet  </HEADLINE>
   By SHAWN POGATCHNIK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Britain resumed sole control of Northern
Ireland at the stroke of midnight today -- but was hopeful of a quick return of
power to the local Protestant-Catholic administration once the Irish Republican
Army's commitment to disarm becomes clear.
</P>
<P>
	   Hours after Britain decided to re-impose ``direct rule'' of Northern
Ireland, the committee overseeing disarmament made a surprise announcement that
it had made new progress in its latest talks with the IRA.
</P>
<P>
	   Britain's calculation is that suspending the Cabinet will encourage its
major Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists, to remain in a coalition that
includes the IRA-linked Sinn Fein party.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ulster Unionists scheduled a conference today to vote on whether to
withdraw from the Cabinet, a move that would trigger its collapse.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I very much regret this course of action,'' said Britain's Northern
Ireland Secretary Peter Mandelson, who stripped powers from the four-party
coalition just 72 days after its formation under terms of the Good Friday peace
accord of 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The crisis was triggered Jan. 31 when the province's independent disarmament
commission reported that the outlawed IRA had yet to indicate when, if ever, it
would start scrapping its hidden weapons.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ulster Unionists in November accepted an American-brokered deal that
required them to accept Sinn Fein as government colleagues on condition that the
IRA would gradually disarm in response.
</P>
<P>
	   Hopes of a resolution were raised by progress in a surprise second report
published late Friday by the disarmament commission -- just a few hours after
Mandelson's announcement.
</P>
<P>
	   The report said the IRA had spelled out ``the context'' in which the
outlawed group would ``initiate a comprehensive process to put arms beyond use,
in a manner as to ensure maximum public confidence.''
</P>
<P>
	   The commission, led by Canadian Gen. John de Chastelain, said the IRA's
latest position ``holds out the real prospect of an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
	   In Washington, President Clinton said this statement represented ``real
progress'' and he hoped all parties would ``build on that progress.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I regret that the IRA did not give the de Chastelain commission a more
timely commitment on arms decommissioning to maintain the momentum toward full
implementation of the accord,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   Mandelson said he welcomed the IRA's apparent shift as far as it went -- but
that it didn't appear to come close to the British government's requirement for
a clear pledge to disarm. The Good Friday accord empowered de Chastelain to seek
the IRA's total disarmament by May, a goal that looks increasingly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Of course it changes things for the better but it doesn't transform
things,'' said Mandelson, who characterized the IRA's true attitude to
disarmament as still ``shrouded in mist.''
</P>
<P>
	   Mandelson said he required ``a clear commitment by the IRA to decommission
-- we haven't got that commitment yet -- and a suggested time frame within which
this would occur. I think that would open the way for me to rescind the
suspension.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
