<DOCNO> APW20000212.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kwan Third in Short Program  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY WILNER-
AP Sports Writer-
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Michelle Kwan heard America's female kiddie corps paying
tribute to her. No one would have blamed her if she wondered why.
</P>
<P>
	It was Kwan who should have been doing the praising after Sasha Cohen, a wispy
15-year-old from California, and Sarah Hughes, a graceful 14-year-old from Long
Island, edged her in the short program Friday at the U.S. Figure Skating
Championships. And like the gracious champion she is, Kwan indeed complimented
the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
	``I do see the future, and it's incredible,'' said Kwan, at 19 hardly an
old-timer. ``I can see the great potential and where we're sitting at world
standards and how the U.S. looks against the world.''
</P>
<P>
	Forget the world. Heading into tonight's free skate, Kwan must worry about the
challenge from within her nation's borders. To win her fourth U.S. crown and
third in a row, she will need to outskate the kids.
</P>
<P>
	She knows it.
</P>
<P>
	``My life has definitely changed this year with school and all,'' said the UCLA
freshman. ``I have a lot to juggle.
</P>
<P>
	``When I am on the ice, I have one thing in mind and that's do well and keep
improving. I know I have to keep on top of things and not maintain what I have.
I have to keep on going forward.''
</P>
<P>
	If she doesn't move forward, she'll be dethroned. Cohen and Hughes certainly
are precocious enough to skate past her -- not that they expected it to happen
so soon.
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't really believe I could beat her, she's just so great,'' said
Cohen, who is 4-foot-9, 79 pounds and officially 15 -- but looks, younger.
</P>
<P>
	``That's quite right,'' chimed in veteran coach John Nicks after Cohen's
brilliant, innovative routine to music by Vivaldi and Albanini earned her first
place from five of the nine judges.
</P>
<P>
	``We all knew coming into this competition our wonderful champion Michelle, who
has been supreme and is still best in the world, would be challenged by the
youth of America. It's been a tradition the American ladies champion never rests
easy on the throne. She will be challenged in the next year or two years. But
(there is) nothing like Michelle, your consistency in performance, and all these
young skaters understand it.''
</P>
<P>
	Kwan understands the urgency of her situation, and why she is in it. She was
too confident, too comfortable, for the short, worth one-third of the total
score. She fell on the simplest triple jump, a toe loop, which Kwan hadn't done
in the short in four years.
</P>
<P>
	``I felt so at ease,'' the two-time world champion said. ``I think that I
didn't take my time and rushed right into it.''
</P>
<P>
	Kyoko Ina and John Zimmerman rushed past younger skaters to win the pairs
title. It was the third national crown for Ina, who won in 1997 and '98 with
Jason Dungjen, and the first for Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
	Ina was relieved their routine went so well. The couple has been together only
two years, and it's been an inconsistent ride.
</P>
<P>
	``We are notorious for having weird things happen after a great performance,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
	Nothing weird happened and they are headed for next month's world championships
in Nice, France, along with runners-up Tiffany Scott and Philip Dulebohn.
</P>
<P>
	Cohen might not be heading to worlds even if she wins. She's too young and will
need to medal at junior worlds in three weeks to qualify.
</P>
<P>
	That's not on her mind.
</P>
<P>
	``To be on top is really great, but I really didn't expect to do this well,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
	Dressed in white and looking like a ballerina in a music box, Cohen was magical
from the beginning of her first significant senior event. Combining unusual
strength for someone so small, she displayed marvelous flexibility. From her
triple lutz-double toe combination to a series of exquisite, difficult spirals
to a perfect triple flip, she wowed the crowd and won five judges.
</P>
<P>
	``That's the best short program she's skated in three years,'' Nicks said.
</P>
<P>
	Hughes, 14 and eligible for worlds because of her strong international
performances last year, took the ice directly after Cohen drew a standing
ovation. While she wasn't quite so energetic, Hughes was a winner with three
judges for her flowing program to ``Serenade for Klara.''
</P>
<P>
	``It's not always easy to skate after a standing ovation, but I am very pleased
with myself,'' Hughes added.
</P>
<P>
	The kids should be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
