<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grand Jury Indicts Lewis, 2 Others  </HEADLINE>
    By JAMES PILCHER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- Police claim that Ray Lewis lied. His lawyer claims he's
being railroaded.
</P>
<P>
	   Whatever the truth, a grand jury indicted Lewis and two associates on murder
charges for the stabbing deaths of two men killed after a Super Bowl party.
</P>
<P>
	   Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard Jr. announced the indictments
Friday, saying Lewis and the other two were involved in a Jan. 31 fight that
left the two victims dead.
</P>
<P>
	   Lewis, a three-time Pro Bowl linebacker for the Baltimore Ravens, remains in
the Atlanta Detention Center without bail, charged with the deaths of Richard
Lollar, 24, and Jacinth Baker, 21.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense lawyer Ed Garland said he would prove Lewis' "absolute innocence" at
a Monday bond hearing and called the prosecution's case "dishwater weak."
</P>
<P>
	   "You can almost hear the railroad whistle blowing as it goes down the
track," Garland said. "The first passenger was Richard Jewell -- this time it's
Ray Lewis. At the Olympics there was another innocent person trying to help, but
was in the wrong place at the wrong time. They have just done to Ray Lewis what
they did to Richard Jewell, and history is repeating itself."
</P>
<P>
	   Jewell, a security guard at Centennial Olympic Park at the time of the July
1996 park bombing, was named as a suspect, but later cleared by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
	   Garland said Lewis was not a participant in the fight, but tried to stop it.
</P>
<P>
	   Police say Lewis lied to them about who was in his limousine that morning
and tried to protect his friends.
</P>
<P>
	   Howard would not say if investigators believe Lewis stabbed one of the
victims, but he can be charged with murder if he was involved in the fight --
even if someone else killed the men.
</P>
<P>
	   "He participated by punching, encouraging and assisting in the commission of
this crime," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
	   Five of the victims' family members attended the district attorney's news
conference, and Vondie Boykin, Baker's aunt, read a brief statement.
</P>
<P>
	   "God is a just God and he will see to it that justice is served," she said
as Atlanta police chief Beverly Harvard consoled Baker's cousin Patrice Brown by
holding her hand.
</P>
<P>
	   The FBI has issued arrest warrants for the other two suspects, Reginald
Oakley of Baltimore and Joseph Sweeting of Miami. Atlanta police say Lewis lied
to officers to protect the two men.
</P>
<P>
	   Each of the men face six charges including felony murder and aggravated
assault with a deadly weapon. A murder conviction in Georgia brings a sentence
of life in prison or the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
	   Oakley, 31, and Sweeting, 34, are both being sought on federal charges of
unlawful flight to avoid prosecution. The FBI said they should be considered
armed and dangerous, and mug shots of the two men were released.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are appealing to them to turn themselves in," Harvard said.
</P>
<P>
	   Oakley has been convicted of a number of crimes, including assaulting a
police officer, shooting into an occupied dwelling, trafficking cocaine and
embezzlement, Atlanta deputy police chief C.B. Jackson said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Oakley was evicted from his apartment earlier this year, according to Mike
Zimenski, a spokesman for the apartment building's management company.
</P>
<P>
	   A Baltimore television station reported that a man who claims to be a legal
consultant for Oakley said Friday that Oakley is nothing more than a witness to
the murders. WBAL-TV quoted Jesse Ingram as saying Oakley has agreed to return
to Atlanta and cooperate with police.
</P>
<P>
	   Police in Dade County, Fla., said Sweeting has been charged with robbery,
possession of a firearm by a felon, and carrying a concealed firearm.
</P>
<P>
	   No one answered the telephone Friday at Sweeting's parents' home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0230 </TRAILER>
