<DOCNO> APW20000212.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Adapt To Threats  </HEADLINE>
   By RODEINA KENAAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- After the latest Israeli airstrikes, Lebanese are
hooking back up their noisy generators and filling their tubs to conserve water
-- adapting quickly to lives with power cutoffs and the threat of more punishing
raids.
</P>
<P>
	   Beirut has been transformed this week from a city famed for its nightlife to
a place where 1.2 million people cope with blackouts and water shortages, while
shrugging off the roar of Israeli jets overhead and the occasional fire of
anti-aircraft guns.
</P>
<P>
	   In a flare-up of violence this week between Hezbollah guerrillas and Israeli
troops in southern Lebanon, Israeli airstrikes Tuesday destroyed power stations
in Beirut and elsewhere. Parts of the country were plunged into darkness,
forcing the government to impose power cuts of up to 16 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
	   Apprehension then grew after Israeli officials threatened to bring the
battle once again to Beirut if guerrillas fired rockets into northern Israel.
Seven Israeli soldiers have been killed and 15 Lebanese civilians injured in the
past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   American singer Art Garfunkel, of the 1960s duo Simon and Garfunkel,
canceled a Valentine's Day concert in Beirut for security reasons. A
government-sponsored conference to promote Beirut as a media capital was
postponed. Some travelers canceled flights to Lebanon for this month's Shopping
and Tourism Festival.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Let's face it. War and tourism don't go together,'' said Pierre Ashkar,
president of the Hotel Owners' Association.
</P>
<P>
	   Lebanon has recovered from such setbacks before. It did so many times during
the 1975-90 civil war. Last June, Israeli warplanes knocked out two power
stations near Beirut, forcing electricity rationing for about four months. In
1996, Israeli planes also hit the Beirut power stations.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel's strategy of hitting infrastructure in an effort to turn the
Lebanese government and public against the guerrillas isn't working this time,
either.
</P>
<P>
	   Publicly, the government backs the guerrillas, who are supported by Iran and
tolerated by Syria, but it does not involve its armed forces in the conflict,
except to fire at Israeli jets.
</P>
<P>
	   People are angry at having to deal with little electricity, hot water, heat
and having to walk up the stairs because the elevators are not working.
</P>
<P>
	   But most blame Israel, and few speak out against the guerrillas, even in
Christian areas where many saw the Israelis as their allies 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Israel hates to see our economy growing. That's why it is targeting our
infrastructure just to see us go down the drain,'' said Walid Shwaifati, a
Christian who owns several clothing and shoe stores across the country.
</P>
<P>
	   Albert Moukhaiber, an anti-Syrian Christian politician and one of the rare
dissenting voices, has criticized the government's handling of the crisis. He
has asked why Syria, which is bound to Lebanon by a friendship treaty and keeps
15,000 troops in the country, does not deploy its air force against the Israeli
planes.
</P>
<P>
	   For Wadad Khalifeh, mother of two girls aged 5 and 7, this past week's
airstrikes meant a shift to another routine.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Don't forget to bring lots of candles and batteries,'' she shouted from
her fifth-floor balcony to her husband in the street below. ``Forget the
potatoes and the oranges. They'll be too heavy for you to carry up the stairs.''
</P>
<P>
	   In the new routine, children do their homework before sundown and laundry is
done at odd hours to use limited periods of electricity and water.
</P>
<P>
	   Some families kept their children away from school for a few days, fearing
more air attacks. Many elderly and those with heart problems changed the times
they went home to avoid having to climb the stairs of high-rise apartment
buildings.
</P>
<P>
	   The blackouts have put neighborhood generator operators back in business,
after some had thought of selling their machines and changing their line of
work. Now they charge hefty fees to feed electricity to homes.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the generally gloomy atmosphere, many Lebanese are confident the
attacks will not have a lasting effect.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This week, Lebanon is a nightmare. Next week, it will be different,'' said
the Lebanese promoter of the Garfunkel show, Naji Bazz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0239 </TRAILER>
