<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Saturday, Feb. 12, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Britain Resumes Control of N. Ireland
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Britain resumed sole control of Northern
Ireland at the stroke of midnight today -- but was hopeful of a quick return of
power to the local Protestant-Catholic administration once the Irish Republican
Army's commitment to disarm becomes clear. Hours after Britain decided to
re-impose "direct rule" of Northern Ireland, the committee overseeing
disarmament made a surprise announcement that it had made new progress in its
latest talks with the IRA. Britain's calculation is that suspending the Cabinet
will encourage its major Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists, to remain in a
coalition that includes the IRA-linked Sinn Fein party.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Midwest Express Averts Strike
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Midwest Express Airlines and its pilots agreed on a labor
contract early Saturday, averting a strike after more than a dozen weekend
flights were canceled and workers began picketing. "Flights will be resuming as
normal tomorrow," said Paul Omodt, a spokesman for the Air Line Pilots
Association. The deal was announced after the strike deadline of 11:01 p.m. CST
was pushed back two hours. Details were not announced.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Grozny Refugees Fear of No Return
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SLEPTSOVSKAYA, Russia (AP) -- A push by Russian troops to flush out the last
remaining rebels in Grozny raises little hope among refugees of returning soon.
There is hardly anything to go home to in the ruins of the Chechen capital.
Nearly a week after Russian troops claimed to have the city under control,
Russian authorities appear to have no firm plans on returning the population of
the nearly deserted city. For now, they remain in tent camps near the border.
"In principle, not one important question regarding the refugees has been
decided," said Timirkhan Akiyev, an official in the Migration Service in
Ingushetia, the Russian province on Chechnya's border.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Space Shuttle Endeavour Blasts Off
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Endeavour and a crew of six
roared into orbit Friday on a long-delayed mission to create the finest map of
Earth ever produced. "We're ready to map the world," said commander Kevin
Kregel. Just 5 1/2 hours later, the astronauts began extending a 197-foot radar
antenna mast from the shuttle cargo bay. It was a tense job and, by far, the
biggest challenge of the mission. Within 17 minutes, the towerlike mast was all
the way out -- and the longest rigid structure ever deployed in space. "A long
train out there," observed Mission Control.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Party Strikes Back at Ventura
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Reform Party is striking back at its dissenting
top officeholder, Jesse Ventura, by moving to oust chairman Jack Gargan, an ally
of the Minnesota governor. Ventura's break with the national party on Friday was
timed to pre-empt the national party's meeting here Friday, at which members
loyal to founder Ross Perot were expected to vote to topple Gargan. Gargan, who
took office Jan. 1, has been unable to control the warring factions loyal to
Ventura and Perot.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indonesia's Wiranto Said Resigning
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Indonesian security minister Wiranto, accused of
responsibility for the violence in East Timor, will resign, President
Abdurrahman Wahid said. Wahid, in Bangkok for a U.N. trade meeting, said
Saturday he would meet with Wiranto after his return to Indonesia and expects
him to resign within two days. Wahid, who has been traveling outside Indonesia
for about two weeks, first called for Wiranto's resignation on Jan. 31 after an
Indonesian government investigation blamed the general for the mayhem in East
Timor last year when the territory voted to break away from Indonesia in a
U.N.-supervised ballot.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Other Planes Have Wing Tail Glitch
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The same tail wing problem that has become the focus of
the investigation into last week's crash of an Alaska Airlines plane was found
during government-mandated inspections Friday in at least five other jetliners.
The Federal Aviation Administration ordered inspections of all MD-80 and similar
aircraft. Preliminary inspections, which affect about 1,200 planes, must be
completed by Monday, but the FAA is giving airlines 30 days to perform a more
detailed check.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Coach Landry's Condition Worsens
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DALLAS (AP) -- Former Dallas Cowboys coach Tom Landry has taken a turn for
the worse in his battle against leukemia, his son said. "While the results of my
father's latest chemotherapy treatments were at first encouraging, it is now
apparent that the leukemia has returned," Tom Landry Jr. said Friday. "Aided by
the efforts of doctors and nurses, dad has been battling this disease for the
last nine months. He is resting comfortably in a private room at Baylor
University Medical Center, surrounded by his family," Landry's son told The
Dallas Morning News.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0300 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Midwest Express Averts Strike  </HEADLINE>
    By SHAUN TANDON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Midwest Express Airlines and its pilots agreed on a labor
contract early Saturday, averting a strike after more than a dozen weekend
flights were canceled and workers began picketing.
</P>
<P>
	   "Flights will be resuming as normal tomorrow," said Paul Omodt, a spokesman
for the Air Line Pilots Association. The airline confirmed as much on its Web
site.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal was announced after the strike deadline of 11:01 p.m. CST was
pushed back two hours. No details were released, but union negotiators were
satisfied with the tentative agreement, said Karl Petersen, chairman of the
strike committee.
</P>
<P>
	   "It is satisfying to be recognized by our company as a valuable asset,"
Petersen said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
	   A ratification vote was expected within a week, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The union has negotiated with Midwest Express for 19 months to establish the
first contract between the two. The National Mediation Board held the talks in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   In preparation for a strike, the airline had canceled 15 flights scheduled
for Friday and Saturday morning. The 200 affected passengers were put on other
flights, airline spokeswoman Lisa Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
	   Before the announcement, about 30 of the airline's 320 pilots held an
informational picket outside the Midwest Express Center in downtown Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
	   The union held a similar protest at Mitchell International Airport, the
airline's hub. Midwest Express has 130 daily flights to 31 cities, including
Boston, Los Angeles, New York and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
	   According to fliers the demonstrating pilots passed out, final talks hinge
on wages, and pension and health insurance for retirees.
</P>
<P>
	   The union says the average salary for a five-year veteran pilot at Midwest
Express is $86,000, compared with an industry average of $145,000.
</P>
<P>
	   As for retirement benefits, the union says the airline would give retirees
less than 40 percent of their pre-retirement income vs. 58 percent at comparable
airlines. The union also wants the airline to guarantee insurance for retired
pilots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0300 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0072 </DOCNO>
