<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley, Gore Fight Out West  </HEADLINE>
   By SCOTT LINDLAW Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Al Gore and Bill Bradley are making personal
pitches to thousands of Democratic activists gathered here as California's
primary race enters its home stretch.
</P>
<P>
	   The candidates planned nearly back-to-back addresses today before more than
3,000 people at the California Democratic Party convention.
</P>
<P>
	   It is a crucial moment for both men, because more nominating delegates are
at stake in California than in any other state, and because the convention-goers
represent the core Democrats who tend to vote in primaries. The election here is
March 7.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These are the kind of people who knock on doors and lick envelopes,''
Democratic National Committee Chairman Joe Andrew said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Clearly, they're very influential, and there's a concentration of media
here that makes the stakes even higher for the candidates,'' Andrew said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore, seeking to protect a commanding lead in California polls, courted the
activists at late-night convention appearances Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   He sounded a laundry list of traditional Democratic themes at speeches
before both groups -- the first, a women's caucus, the second, a reception
hosted by Gov. Gray Davis, his most powerful political ally in the state. Each
gathering drew about 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore pledged to maintain affirmative action, fight for civil rights, clean
up the environment, work toward universal health coverage, beef up gun control
laws and help senior citizens buy prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
	   He received his most boisterous response of the night when he shouted to the
women's group: ``I will fight for a woman's right to choose!''
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley must overcome both his deficit in the polls and the strong support
Gore enjoys among top California Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   While the California Democratic Party is officially neutral in the race,
chairman Art Torres openly backs Gore. So do Sens. Barbara Boxer and Dianne
Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's more familiarity with the vice president,'' Torres said. ``He's
been here whenever we've had a nasty catastrophe, and people trust him.''
</P>
<P>
	   In a Field Poll of likely Democrats released earlier this week, Gore led
Bradley 54 percent to 13 percent, a gap that marked a widening over previous
surveys.
</P>
<P>
	   After his speech this morning, Bradley was headed to Oakland, where he
planned a high school appearance with other ex-NBA stars, including Julius
Irving, Phil Jackson and Bill Russell.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the 16 states that will vote on March 7, California offers the biggest
jackpot of delegates -- 367 of the 2,170 needed to clinch the nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0301 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
