<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 03:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Special Interests Underwrite Dems  </HEADLINE>
   By SCOTT LINDLAW Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Labor, corporate and other special-interest groups
spent tens of thousands of dollars to underwrite the California Democratic Party
convention, where they angled for face time with two presidential candidates,
two senators, the governor and others.
</P>
<P>
	   As party activists began to gather Friday, drug manufacturer Pfizer Inc.
rolled out a banner more than 100 feet wide that was to hang in main convention
hall.
</P>
<P>
	   Three groups of Indians had banners, too, as did Providian Financial Corp.,
which also set up a booth outside the hall. Sempra Energy -- owner of several
California utility companies -- got an ad in the glossy convention brochure seen
by thousands of activists, as did unions representing teachers, state workers
and Northern California carpenters.
</P>
<P>
	   All were convention sponsors.
</P>
<P>
	   While the party declined to release a complete list of them and their
contributions, interviews with the underwriters and Democratic officials found
the cost of admission for about two dozen interest groups ranged from $5,000 to
$25,000. Some paid more, if all donations throughout the year were counted, said
party spokesman Bob Mulholland.
</P>
<P>
	   Sponsorships at party gatherings is a popular way for special interests to
gain exposure to politicians.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, the California Republican Party charged sponsors about the same
as the Democrats -- between $5,000 and $25,000, said GOP spokesman Stuart
DeVeaux.
</P>
<P>
	   At the Democratic gathering, the California Teachers Association and Sempra
said they paid $10,000 each. Voter.com chipped in $25,000.
</P>
<P>
	   In return, the organizations received a variety of benefits, including floor
passes, admission to receptions and hospitality suites, booths, advertisements
in the convention guide, and banners, Mulholland said. The total cost of the
convention was about $250,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   With the special-interest donations and admission fees paid by activists,
the party usually has some money left over for get-out-the-vote and other
activities, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Some of the special-interest groups dispatched multiple representatives to
the gathering, and they stood a good chance of bumping into officeholders and
candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   Vice President Al Gore, rival candidate Bill Bradley, Sens. Dianne Feinstein
and Barbara Boxer and Gov. Gray Davis all were to attend, along with House
members and state lawmakers and officials.
</P>
<P>
	   Mulholland rejected the notion that the well-heeled interest groups were
buying exposure ordinary citizens cannot. ``Any Democrat can be a delegate here
for 75 bucks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Indeed, many of the sponsors said the convention was an opportunity to
heighten awareness of March 7 ballot initiatives that could affect them.
</P>
<P>
	   For the Indians, there is Proposition 1A, which would ratify gambling pacts
signed last year between the state and nearly 60 tribes.
</P>
<P>
	   Teachers' unions were promoting Proposition 26, which would allow local
school bonds to be approved by a simple majority vote instead of two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
	   Other sponsors simply saw the convention as a fertile business environment.
</P>
<P>
	   Craig Smith, director of Democratic outreach for Voter.com, said his
organization viewed the convention as a gathering of likely customers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It made sense to us from a visibility perspective,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0302 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 03:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Demand U.S. Intervene  </HEADLINE>
   By JASPER MORTIMER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Arab states condemned Israel for its airstrikes on
Lebanon this week, warning of damage to the Mideast peace process and demanding
the United State intervene.
</P>
<P>
	   After Israel's strikes damaged Lebanese power stations, Lebanon's Prime
Minister Salim Hoss urged the United States and France to ``take the necessary
steps to prevent Israel from carrying out new attacks against civilian
targets.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said he was singling out the United States ``because it is the country
that wields the greatest influence on Israel.''
</P>
<P>
	   Washington and Paris head a monitoring committee set up to oversee rules
agreed by all sides in the southern Lebanon conflict to avoid putting civilians
in the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
	   Syria's state-run Damascus radio blamed the United States for the Israeli
raids, which were part of a flare-up of fighting between Lebanese guerrillas and
Israeli forces in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These acts confirm American responsibility because the United States keeps
silent on Israeli crimes,'' the radio said Friday in a commentary. ``Had the
United States not hurried to cover Israel's actions whenever it commits a crime
or a massacre, the Israeli haughtiness would not have risen to this level.''
</P>
<P>
	   Just after Israel began its air offensive Tuesday, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright accused the Hezbollah guerrillas of attacking Israeli troops
from villages, in violation of an 1996 understanding that prohibits attacks on
or from civilian areas. That echoed Israel's justifications for the strikes on
civilian infrastructure, although Lebanon denied the claim.
</P>
<P>
	   The airstrikes destroyed power stations near Beirut and in the north and
east of the country. At least 15 civilians were wounded in the attacks, which
also blasted numerous suspected guerrilla positions in the south.
</P>
<P>
	   Seven Israeli soldiers have been killed in the last three weeks in southern
Lebanon. On Friday, Israel conducted a 13th straight day of strikes on guerrilla
targets.
</P>
<P>
	   Arab states said a major victim of the airstrikes would be Israel's peace
negotiations with Syria, Lebanon and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
	   Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdul-Illah Khatib said Israel's use of military
power was ``poisonous to the region's atmosphere and ... against the peace
process.''
</P>
<P>
	   His Syrian counterpart, Farouq al-Sharaa, warned that Israel's continued
offensive ``will kill any possible chance for peace in the region.''
</P>
<P>
	   There was little doubt that the air raids reduced the chance of an early
resumption of Israeli-Syrian negotiations, which were postponed indefinitely
last month. Lebanon says it will only sit down with the Israelis once the Syrian
talks have made progress.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Palestinian peace track, the fighting in Lebanon took attention from
Sunday's deadline for a framework for a final-status accord, although both sides
had already said they did not expect to meet that target.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Peace is not a gift from Israel to the Arabs, but (Israel) badly needs
peace,'' Arab League Secretary-General Esmat Abdel-Meguid said in a statement.
He warned Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak that his predecessor, Benjamin
Netanyahu, lost last year's elections because he was not serious about peace.
</P>
<P>
	   In Egypt, there was criticism of Arab governments for failing to do more
than protest Israel's air raids.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Today, we mourn the Arab states who stood watching when Lebanon was burned
to the ground,'' a student told a crowd of 1,500 protesters on the campus of the
American University in Cairo. The students, who shouted anti-Israeli slogans and
burned an Israeli flag, were confined to the campus by a cordon of anti-riot
police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0303 </TRAILER>
