<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 03:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plundered Sicilian gold completes U.S. odyssey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - It was the end of an odyssey spanning two continents -
and it was pure gold.
<P>
	   On Friday, an ancient platter plundered from Sicily in the 1980s came full
circle: It was returned to Italian officials by Manhattan's top federal
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
	   The round, foot-wide "phiale" was used in the 5th century B.C. to
ceremonially offer food to the gods.
</P>
<P>
	   "The gods have a long memory, but so do the carabinieri" - or Italian
police, said U.S. Customs Commissioner Raymond Kelly, praising Italian
investigators who helped trace the journey of the archeological masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
	   Sometime around 1984, the "phiale" was illegally excavated from a protected
site near Palermo, during construction of electrical utility poles.
</P>
<P>
	   It was sold to a Sicilian art collector and in 1991, spirited out of Italy
to a dealer in Zurich, Switzerland. Later that year, Manhattan collector Michael
Steinhardt, a former Wall Street financier, bought the antique for about $1.2
million, more than 10 times the value of its weight of several pounds in pure
gold.
</P>
<P>
	   The treasure arrived at Kennedy Airport, hand-carried on a flight from
Geneva by a Manhattan dealer who acted as intermediary. A customs form gave the
phiale's country of origin as Switzerland and its value at $250,000.
</P>
<P>
	   It was another four years before Italy sought U.S. help in tracking down the
illegally exported art. And in November 1995, customs special agents showed up
at a Fifth Avenue apartment with a seizure warrant issued by the Manhattan
federal prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is one of the most important cases to ever confront the museum world,"
said Manhattan federal prosecutor Mary Jo White, who was present Friday for the
return of the platter - which she said is essentially "priceless."
</P>
<P>
	   Her office and the U.S. Customs Service had filed a forfeiture complaint and
a Manhattan judge ordered the artifact repatriated; last July, an appeals court
upheld the ruling. Steinhardt, the collector, sought a Supreme Court appeal, but
the nation's highest court declined to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, the shimmering gold plate was the star of a news conference in a
skyscraper of Manhattan's World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
	   The Italian consul general in New York, Giorgio Radicati, balanced the
hand-carved gold on his fingers with the flatter side up. That's how the plate
inscribed in Greek was ceremonially used for offerings to the gods in about 450
B.C., when Sicily was ruled by Greece.
</P>
<P>
	   Later Friday, the treasure was packed in a cardboard box for a flight to
Rome, accompanied by an entourage including an Italian magistrate and a major of
the carabinieri police.
</P>
<P>
	   The phiale was on its way home - to a museum in a Sicilian village near
Palermo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-12-00 0306 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
