<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Deutch Recommended Aide  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A former CIA director recommended an agency official join
him at Citibank while she was still monitoring an investigation into whether he
had mishandled classified information, The New York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
	   John Deutch resigned as director in December 1996 and was almost immediately
elected to the board of Citibank, the nation's largest. That same month, CIA
officials found evidence Deutch had placed classified information on unsecure
computers at his home but reportedly didn't notify the Justice Department of
potential wrongdoing for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
	   The investigation monitor was Nora Slatkin, the CIA's executive director.
Citing a classified agency report, the Times reported that Slatkin notified the
agency in June 1997 that she was considering a job with Citibank and would
withdraw from consideration of any matters involving the bank.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet within a month, she reviewed an internal report of findings in the
Deutch investigation, according to the report. Slatkin resigned from the CIA in
September 1997 and joined Citibank as a vice president the next month, the Times
reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The agency's inspector general has found that Slatkin's actions delayed ``a
prompt and thorough investigation'' of the Deutch case, according to the
classified report.
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement, Slatkin said she had excused herself from the Deutch
investigation and that she only helped keep information flowing in the case.
</P>
<P>
	   An unidentified Citibank spokesman told the newspaper that that Slatkin was
referred to Citibank by Deutch as she was considering where to move after
leaving the agency.
</P>
<P>
	   CIA Director George J. Tenet would not comment to the Times about the
Citibank matter. The Justice Department decided last spring not to prosecute
Deutch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 0411 </TRAILER>
