<HEADLINE> Midwest Express Averts Strike  </HEADLINE>
    By SARAH WYATT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Pilots for Midwest Express Airlines celebrated today after
reaching a tentative agreement with airline management that averted a strike
over the terms of their first labor contract.
</P>
<P>
	   Details were not released, but union strike committee chairman Karl Petersen
said the deal provides pilots with enhanced compensation, retiree health
insurance and a retirement plan "that will protect and enhance the careers of
our pilots."
</P>
<P>
	   Airline officials canceled 15 flights late Friday and early today in
preparation for a potential strike. Airline spokeswoman Lisa Bailey said flights
were expected to resume as scheduled today.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're extremely pleased. The customers are No. 1 and we wanted to make sure
we could continue serving the customers," Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
	   Midwest Express, which has its headquarters in Milwaukee, has 130 daily
flights to 31 cities, including Boston, Los Angeles, New York and Philadelphia.
Labor talks involving the company and the Air Line Pilots Association have gone
in for 19 months.
</P>
<P>
	   The union said key issues included wages, and pension and health insurance
for retirees.
</P>
<P>
	   The union said the average salary for a five-year veteran pilot at Midwest
Express is $86,000, compared with an industry average of $145,000. It also said
current airline policy gives retirees less than 40 percent of their
pre-retirement income, compared with 58 percent at comparable airlines. Union
officials also wanted the airline to guarantee insurance for retired pilots.
</P>
<P>
	   Union spokesman Paul Omodt said a ratification vote on the proposed contract
could come in four to five days.
</P>
<P>
	   "There were a lot of people hugging, giving high-fives, shaking hands. But
we were relieved. No one wanted to strike," Omodt said. "The pilots want to stay
here, frankly. They want to make this a career airline."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
