<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Proposes Family Leave  </HEADLINE>
   By ANNE GEARAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Recalling his own mother's struggle as a widow with a
family, President Clinton today proposed spending $20 million to study new ways
for states to offer paid leave for working parents.
</P>
<P>
	   If approved by Congress in the next budget, the money would underwrite
studies and test projects nationwide. Clinton said he also wants the Family and
Medical Leave Act expanded to benefit 10 million employees of small companies
who are now not covered by the law he signed in 1993.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I've often wondered how my own mother, when she was a young widow, would
have been able to go away to train as a nurse if my grandparents hadn't been
there to take care of me,'' Clinton said in his weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
	   ``My mother and I were lucky. So were many other American families. But none
of our families should have to rely on luck alone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said the family leave law, which guarantees up to 12 weeks off
without pay to care for a new child or needy family member, has been good for
workers and families.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Everywhere I go, people come up to me and tell me how much this law has
meant to their lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The administration says 20 million Americans have taken advantage of the
law, and that in 85 percent of cases the leave cost employers nothing.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In fact, in many cases it has actually helped save them money by cutting
down on turnover and reducing the expense of training new workers,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Judith Lichtman, president of the National Partnership for Women and
Families, welcomed the opportunity for states to expand the leave program.
</P>
<P>
	   ``At a time when we have such a strong economy, and working families need
relief so urgently, this initiative is a major step forward that can make a real
difference to millions of Americans,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   In November, Clinton announced plans to allow states to pay unemployment
benefits to new parents. Four states are testing the feasibility of doing so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
