<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hijacked Plane Crew Details Escape  </HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT BARR Associated Press Wrter
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- The crew of a hijacked Afghan airliner decided to escape
after despairing of persuading their captors to surrender, a flight captain said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The hijackers had taken over the Ariana jet early Sunday during what should
have been a short domestic flight from the Afghan capital of Kabul to the
northern town of Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
	   The four members of the flight crew, who say they all want to return to
Afghanistan, talked with reporters two days after the hijackers surrendered at
Stansted airport, north of London.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the passengers from the flight were preparing to move to an
immigration center in western England on Saturday, the government said. Some 74
of them have applied for asylum, and police are questioning 22 others who are
suspected of involvement in the hijacking.
</P>
<P>
	   By the time the crew scrambled out a cockpit window Tuesday night, it had
spent nearly two full days with the hijackers and had been unable to persuade
them to give up, said Nabi, the second captain on the flight.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Finally, we saw we could not do anything. We thought if we escaped, the
hijackers would be stranded and probably would not dare to harm any
passengers,'' Nabi said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the worst moment for the crew came Monday morning at daybreak, when
the hijackers first saw that the aircraft was surrounded by armed security
personnel.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They became very hysterical and very nervous,'' and threatened to kill
some of the passengers, Nabi said. He did not say how calm was restored.
</P>
<P>
	   Police have said that the hijackers also became extremely agitated after
discovering the crew had escaped. One flight attendant bore the brunt of their
wrath and was shoved down the back stairs of the Boeing 727.
</P>
<P>
	   Said Mehdi Saidi, the first captain, said the crew did not attempt to resist
the hijackers when they first took over the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The hijackers entered the aircraft cockpit and rushed inside with pistols
and very bad faces,'' he said. ``The crew told them: 'Don't do anything please.
What is your command? We will follow your command.'''
</P>
<P>
	   A planed chartered by the Geneva-based International Organization for
Migration was waiting Saturday at an air force base to return any passengers who
wished to go home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1126 </TRAILER>
