<DOCNO> APW20000212.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget Gridlock Likely This Year  </HEADLINE>
   By ALAN FRAM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress has begun dissecting President Clinton's fiscal
2001 budget, a $1.84 trillion proposal he introduced last week to negative
Republican reviews. A guide to the likely twists and turns of this election
year's budget battle:
</P>
<P>
	   Q: What happens next?
</P>
<P>
	   A: Republicans who control the House and Senate will write their own budget
for next year, a broad blueprint that plans tax and spending policy but makes no
actual changes in the law. Republicans hope to complete the budget in March --
weeks earlier than usual. Accelerating the congressional work schedule would
allow lawmakers to head home early to campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress will alter tax and spending law later, when it writes 13 separate
bills financing federal agencies, plus other legislation cutting taxes and
perhaps changing some benefit programs. For example, lawmakers are likely to
work on a prescription drug benefit for Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
	   Q: Are Republicans close to writing their budget?
</P>
<P>
	   A: Not yet. They disagree internally over how much to spend for the
one-third of the budget that Congress controls every year, covering all federal
programs but automatic benefits like Social Security. That figure is key because
it helps determine the size of the surplus, and therefore how much money will be
available for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
	   Q: What are the chief disputes between Republicans and Democrats?
</P>
<P>
	   A: The big fight is over how to use enormous federal surpluses projected
through the next decade.
</P>
<P>
	   Arguing that now is the time to invest in education, health care and other
programs, Clinton favors higher spending and smaller tax cuts than the GOP
prefers. Republicans want extra funds for selected programs like education and
defense but emphasize tax cuts, saying the government's excess money should be
returned to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
	   They also disagree over how big surpluses will be. Clinton says it will be
$746 billion through 2010, excluding Social Security money that the parties
agree should go for debt reduction. Republicans have yet to produce their own
surplus estimate. Because Republicans want lower spending than Clinton, they are
certain to say the surplus will be hundreds of billions bigger than the
president's figure.
</P>
<P>
	   Q: Can't they compromise?
</P>
<P>
	   A: Eventually, they will in some areas. By year's end, Congress doubtlessly
will approve several billion dollars more in spending than Republicans will
initially propose for schools, conservation and other domestic programs, and
probably more than Clinton requested for defense.
</P>
<P>
	   There also should be agreement on some minor tax cuts, perhaps raising the
amount of money senior citizens can earn without losing Social Security
benefits.
</P>
<P>
	   Deals are also possible -- but could be tough to strike -- on prescription
drug benefits and easing the ``marriage penalty,'' the tax code quirk that
requires millions of married couples to pay higher taxes than they would if they
were single.
</P>
<P>
	   Q: Both sides say they favor action on prescription drugs and the marriage
penalty. Why is agreement there difficult?
</P>
<P>
	   A: Because of political and philosophical differences. Democrats prefer a
more generous prescription drug benefit than Republicans, while the GOP wants
marriage penalty relief to be deeper and affect more people than Clinton wants.
Though federal surpluses abound, every dollar used for a tax cut is one less
dollar available for spending, making each side reluctant to give in.
</P>
<P>
	   Many Democrats believe failure to enact a prescription drug program would be
a wonderful issue to use against Republicans in the upcoming elections. At the
same time, many in the GOP would be thrilled to blame Democrats for stalemate on
the marriage penalty.
</P>
<P>
	   Q: Any chance for overhauling Medicare and Social Security, the giant health
care and pension programs for the elderly and disabled, for the coming
retirement of the baby boomers?
</P>
<P>
	   A: Virtually none. To do that would mean reducing the programs' benefits or
boosting the payroll taxes that pay for them, enormously controversial ideas
that the politicians studiously will avoid in an election year.
</P>
<P>
	   Q: What about both parties plans to ``save'' and ``protect'' the two
programs this year?
</P>
<P>
	   A: Do not be fooled. What they really are doing is using the surplus -- most
of it generated by Social Security -- to reduce the national debt. Doing that
should strengthen the economy, which should help the government raise the
revenue it will need in the future to pay the baby boomers' Social Security and
Medicare benefits. But that is indirect. Neither party seriously is pursuing the
benefit cuts or tax increases that most analysts say are needed to keep both
programs solvent.
</P>
<P>
	   Q: So another year of gridlock. Is that bad?
</P>
<P>
	   A: Not completely. With each side likely to block the bulk of the other's
plans for spending and taxes, that means most of the 2001 surplus -- likely to
exceed $170 billion -- will go for debt reduction, a plus for the economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1141 </TRAILER>
