<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advocates for Africa Urge Change  </HEADLINE>
   By PAULINE JELINEK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Advocates for Africa are meeting this week to emphasize
the positive about the continent and change Americans' views of -- and their
government's policies on -- its impoverished and war-torn nations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The philosophy is ... that the glass is half full, not half empty,'' said
Leonard Robinson, president of the National Summit on Africa. A former assistant
U.S. secretary of state, Robinson is among those arguing for greater trade, aid,
cultural exchanges and other programs for Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   It's hard for many to see it that way.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Americans and Europeans will get together, talk and feel good -- and not a
... thing will happen for Africa,'' says Walter Williams, head of the economics
department at George Mason University in Virginia. ``This stuff is for domestic
consumption.''
</P>
<P>
	   At the summit, Robinson will preside over a five-day meeting of an estimated
5,000 people starting Wednesday. Selected delegates will vote, essentially, on
what the United States should be doing on the 54-nation continent.
</P>
<P>
	   The effort, funded by the Carnegie Foundation, Ford Foundation, businesses
and others, has been in the making since late 1996 and has three main goals:
</P>
<P>
	   Summit organizers want:
</P>
<P>
	   --Unify and strengthen what organizers say has been a weak and sometimes
at-odds-with-itself lobby for Africa in America. They point to an American
Jewish lobby they say has been effective in shaping U.S.-Israeli policy.
</P>
<P>
	   --Improve Africa's image in the states, where they say the media have
focused too much on the negative.
</P>
<P>
	   --Get the U.S. government to change its policy toward Africa, a continent
they say has been either ignored or mishandled over the decades.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We want to ensure that policy-makers accept the reality that Africa
matters,'' said Robinson. ``We want to create an atmosphere where Africa will be
respected and treated with equity, not automatically relegated to the back
burner of U.S. foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
	   The goals echo some of the ideas of President Clinton, scheduled to speak to
the summit Thursday. Others invited include current or former presidents of
South Africa, France and Kenya as well as officials from the United Nations and
the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton has promoted, with only limited success, a greater partnership with
Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   House and Senate leaders hope to pass an African trade bill by next month,
the first major trade bill in five years. The legislation primarily would cut
tariffs on imported African clothing and promote U.S. sales and investment on
the continent.
</P>
<P>
	   Summit organizers are trying to get leading U.S. presidential candidates to
speak about their prospective policies toward Africa. They and some black
American leaders say the Clinton administration has paid more attention to
Africa than any other White House in years. They want to ensure that after he
leaves office, that policy not only will continue but be expanded.
</P>
<P>
	   To that end, they have produced a plan of action for U.S. African policy
that will be completed Sunday and will be sent to Congress, administration
officials and leaders of American civil, social and religious organizations as
well as city mayors, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics doubt it will do much good.
</P>
<P>
	   Where summit organizers see an Africa with three of the four fastest-growing
economies in the world, a continent making progress toward democracy, critics of
the summit see an Africa that remains ``a basket case,'' said George Mason
economist Williams.
</P>
<P>
	   He said that except for a handful of nations making some headway with their
economies, ``I wouldn't invest a dime in any country in Africa.'' Most African
nations still lack the rule of law, respect for contracts and other essentials
to make them safe places to invest, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   George Ayittey, a Ghanaian and assistant professor of economics at American
University, agreed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They have held so many of these summits that this one just looks like
another talk shop,'' he said. ``If you ask most Africans, they will tell you the
first priority ought to be to stop all these stupid civil wars,'' many of which
Ayittey blames on ``incumbent despots'' who won't give up power.
</P>
<P>
	   In Sub-Saharan Africa alone, countries wracked by conflict include Ethiopia,
Eritrea, Somalia, Sudan, Rwanda, Burundi, Congo, Liberia and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
	   Others are ``standing in line to blow up,'' Ayittey said. ``Until you clean
that up, nobody is going to sink a million dollars into Africa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1248 </TRAILER>
