<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DiCaprio's 'The Beach' Opens  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID GERMAIN AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Leonardo DiCaprio became king of the heartthrobs when he
followed the ship down in "Titanic" -- adoring female fans helped make the film
an all-time box-office juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
	   Now that DiCaprio has hit dry land in "The Beach," the question is whether
fans will flock to theaters to see their idol playing a dark, rather ignoble
character.
</P>
<P>
	   Opening yesterday, "The Beach" stars DiCaprio as Richard, an American
backpacker in Thailand who embarks on a quest for paradise after obtaining a map
to an idyllic island.
</P>
<P>
	   While it's another journeyman's role for DiCaprio, his character is a
weak-willed cousin to the intrepid, artistic vagabond Jack Dawson of "Titanic,"
which took in $1.8 billion at theaters worldwide.
</P>
<P>
	   There's more weasel than hero about Richard. Instead of dancing jigs in
steerage and freezing in the North Atlantic to save his true love, Richard
sleeps around, lies unabashedly and goes savage and sneering in the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
	   Richard is a juvenile braggart, a feeble philosopher and a bit of a coward
to boot. He also swills snake's blood, unable to back away from a dare.
</P>
<P>
	   Not a pretty picture for your typical teen idol.
</P>
<P>
	   But it's a picture DiCaprio may have needed to paint to keep his career
moving forward, said Nancy Krulik, author of a biography and a trivia book about
the actor.
</P>
<P>
	   "To continuously play the handsome artist from Paris, that only goes so
far," she said. "It's wise to move away from that because it will increase his
longevity."
</P>
<P>
	   Being a heartthrob "is a very short-lived career," Krulik said. "You don't
want to end up as the next 'E! True Hollywood Story' of David Cassidy."
</P>
<P>
	   DiCaprio, 25, has borne the heartthrob mantle for only two of the dozen or
so films he's done: "Titanic" in 1997, and "William Shakespeare's Romeo +
Juliet" the year before.
</P>
<P>
	   He's taken on much chancier roles for other movies. In "The Basketball
Diaries," DiCaprio played a teen-age junkie who fantasizes about going on a gun
rampage in his school. He was Meryl Streep's surly son in "Marvin's Room," and
Robert De Niro's abused stepson in "This Boy's Life." He earned an Oscar
nomination as Johnny Depp's retarded brother in "What's Eating Gilbert Grape?"
</P>
<P>
	   "There's nothing cynical in his choices," said Tom Rothman, president of the
film group for 20th Century Fox, which released "The Beach" and co-produced
"Titanic" with Paramount. "He chose to do 'The Beach' when he basically could
have done any movie Hollywood had to offer."
</P>
<P>
	   But Fox figures the movie plays as well to men as an adventure tale as to
women for the DiCaprio romantic element, Rothman said. But the film will lose
some of DiCaprio's faithful teen audience -- it's R rating for violence means
anyone under 17 is supposed to be accompanied by a parent or guardian.
</P>
<P>
	   Robert Bucksbaum, a film analyst for Reel Source Inc., said DiCaprio's
darker persona in "The Beach" may win him new fans among adults who were "kind
of disgusted with how much attention he got from 'Titanic."'
</P>
<P>
	   "The worst thing that could happen for this movie is that with new ID
procedures at theaters, most of his teen-age following around 13 and even
younger will not get a chance to see it," Bucksbaum said. "You may get a lot of
girls paying for another movie then slipping in to see 'The Beach."'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1301 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Expand Family Leave  </HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton proposed Saturday spending $20 million
to help states find ways to offer paid leave to working parents in need.
Americans should not be forced to choose between their families and their jobs,
he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton also said in his weekly radio address he wants the family and
medical leave law he signed in 1993 expanded to include 10 million employees of
small companies not covered now.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans reacted cooly to both ideas.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the past seven years, the law has allowed more than 20 million
Americans to take as many as a dozen weeks of unpaid leave to care for a newborn
child or deal with a medical crisis at home.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Today there are still large numbers of families who need to take leave
from work, but can't afford to give up the income,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
	   If approved by Congress, the $20 million would fund competitive grants to
help develop the states develop new approaches to making paid leave more
available. States could identify workers facing the greatest financial barriers
and use unemployment insurance or temporary disability insurance to offer them
paid leave.
</P>
<P>
	   Congressional Republicans cast doubt on Clinton's plan.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The president told us he would never demand that taxpayers pay for people
to leave work,'' said Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., chairman of the House Republican
Conference. ``Now he wants the states to do it out of working Americans pockets.
This is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
	   Watts also raised concerns about how the family leave law is being used.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Now employers don't know if someone is permitted to leave for something
serious like breast cancer or something frivolous like an ingrown toenail,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   But Clinton said the issue has touched the lives of so many Americans,
including his own.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I've often wondered how my own mother, when she was a young widow, would
have been able to go away to train as a nurse if my grandparents hadn't been
there to take care of me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``My mother and I were lucky. So were many other American families. But none
of our families should have to rely on luck alone,'' he said. ``And no American
should ever have to choose between the job they need and the parent or child
they love.''
</P>
<P>
	   The administration says that in 85 percent of cases, family leave costs
employers nothing.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In fact, in many cases it has actually helped save them money by cutting
down on turnover and reducing the expense of training new workers,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Endorsing the president's proposal, the AFL-CIO president said two-thirds of
eligible workers who decline to take family or medical leave did so because they
cannot afford to skip a paycheck.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The fact that the United States stands alone among industrialized nations
in failing to provide job-protected, paid parental leave is a national
disgrace,'' John Sweeney said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   He said organized labor will fight to extend paid family leave to all
working families.
</P>
<P>
	   Judith Lichtman, president of the National Partnership for Women and
Families, welcomed the opportunity for states to expand the leave program.
</P>
<P>
	   ``At a time when we have such a strong economy, and working families need
relief so urgently, this initiative is a major step forward that can make a real
difference to millions of Americans,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1310 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
