<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trimble Seeks IRA Weapons Promise  </HEADLINE>
   By SHAWN POGATCHNIK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The senior Protestant in Northern
Ireland's impotent administration said Saturday that the Irish Republican Army
must promise to disarm if the government is to have its powers restored.
</P>
<P>
	   Ulster Unionist Party leader David Trimble emerged unscathed from a party
conference in downtown Belfast, where his many critics had originally planned to
demand his ouster and the party's withdrawal from the 10-week-old
administration.
</P>
<P>
	   But Britain had already stripped the Cabinet's authority Friday and resumed
direct control from London -- effectively saving Trimble's political skin.
</P>
<P>
	   The Belfast coalition of two British Protestant and two Irish Catholic
parties, including the IRA-linked Sinn Fein, was the central goal of Northern
Ireland's Good Friday peace accord of 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   At a news conference in Catholic west Belfast, a downcast Gerry Adams, the
leader of Sinn Fein, said Britain's determination to safeguard Trimble's shaky
hold over his party confirmed that the Ulster Unionists could wield ``a veto
over progress.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Cabinet was formed in November under a compromise plan mediated by
American diplomat George Mitchell. But it fell apart this month over the IRA's
continued refusal to start scrapping its secret weapons dumps, as the accord
envisioned.
</P>
<P>
	   Trimble said his principal objective now was ``to see the administration
re-formed -- but re-formed on a sound basis, so that people are in fact
implementing all the principles of the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
	   To the Ulster Unionists, whose status as the largest party means its
participation is essential for the Cabinet to work, ``a sound basis'' means
gaining an unprecedented disarmament commitment from the IRA.
</P>
<P>
	   The outlawed group called a cease-fire in 1997 after killing about 1,800
people during a 27-year campaign to abolish Northern Ireland as a
Protestant-majority state linked with Britain.
</P>
<P>
	   The Good Friday accord empowered an independent disarmament commission led
by Canadian Gen. John de Chastelain to seek the IRA's total disarmament by May.
</P>
<P>
	   Hours after Britain revoked the Cabinet's powers, de Chastelain reported
that, in their most recent talks, an IRA representative said the group would
``consider how to put arms and explosives beyond use,'' and would actually do
this if the right context was created by politicians. That, De Chastelain said,
``holds out the real prospect of an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Trimble said he had talked Friday to Sinn Fein's Adams and Martin
McGuinness -- both reputed former IRA commanders -- and neither could tell him
what the IRA had in mind.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Even though claims are being made of important proposals, no detail has
become available to anyone,'' said Trimble, who intends to meet the Sinn Fein
leaders again this week.
</P>
<P>
	   Using the umbrella term for the IRA and Sinn Fein, he added: ``We need the
republican movement to tell us: Are they committing themselves to (weapons)
decommissioning? How are they going to do it? When are they going to do it? And
of course we'd be delighted to see them do it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Adams insisted the IRA's latest plans, which he declined to detail,
contained sufficient merit for Britain to have withheld plans to suspend the
Cabinet. He said Britain appeared ``fixated'' on helping Trimble.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If we had delivered the IRA lock, stock and barrel -- in a way the British
government had never been able to do in 30 years of militarism -- it would not
have been enough yesterday,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
	   But Trimble said his party should never again be expected to share power
with Sinn Fein on the basis of ``ambiguous language,'' as he conceded happened
in November.
</P>
<P>
	   Trimble said no democratic society would ``willingly include in their
government a party that was organically linked to a terrorist organization. We,
however, decided to stretch that point.''
</P>
<P>
	   Should another deal emerge, he said, it would be ``obviously unreasonable to
expect us to proceed in any other way than on the basis of absolute clarity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1315 </TRAILER>
