<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Details on Africa Summit  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   How the National Summit on Africa works, and its activities this week:
</P>
<P>
	   Since its inception in 1996, organizers assembled what they say was an
unprecedented grass-roots program. Scholars, business people, charities,
development organizations and ``people from all walks of life'' including
African immigrants met in several regional summits across the country and come
up with a draft plan to bring about what they say would be improved U.S.
policies toward Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   The draft contains 236 recommendations, which will be debated and finally
approved next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   It suggests action to be taken in trade, investment, development, education,
peace, security, human rights, the environment and development of democracy.
</P>
<P>
	   Ideas range from the monumental -- the United States should arrange an
international Marshall Plan of reconstruction and reparations in Africa -- to
the small -- the State Department should make sure embassy employees in Africa
know local languages as a sign of respect to host nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
