<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Wiranto Said Resigning  </HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McDOWELL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Asserting his authority after a two-week political
standoff, Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid said Saturday that his security
minister must either resign or be fired for his role in the rampage last year in
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
	   The dispute between Wahid and Gen. Wiranto has dogged the president during
his two-week tour abroad, which ends Sunday. The trip began with Indonesian and
U.N. human rights panels releasing reports holding Wiranto responsible for the
violence in his former role as armed forces commander.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid said repeatedly that he expected Wiranto to resign, but Wiranto
refused, fueling speculation that the standoff could lead to a coup.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid played down those fears Saturday during his visit to Bangkok for a
U.N. trade conference, but subtle shifts in his position throughout the day
reflected the apparent tightrope he was walking.
</P>
<P>
	   In a speech to a Thai-Indonesian business luncheon early Saturday, Wahid
said that the reason Wiranto had not yet resigned was because the two men had
not met face-to-face since the East Timor reports were issued.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid said he would meet Wiranto after returning home early Sunday and the
resignation would be announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Shortly afterward, Wahid's aides softened the Monday deadline. Wahid told a
subsequent news conference only that an announcement about resignation would be
made Monday, but stopped short of saying whether Wiranto would actually quit.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked to clarify his comments, Wahid said Wiranto was out one way or
another.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's up to him whether to resign or not,'' Wahid said Saturday night. ``If
he does not resign, I will change the Cabinet anyway, without him. I respect him
very much and will give him a respectful place, but not in the Cabinet.''
</P>
<P>
	   The dispute has tested Indonesia's jerky transition from decades of
authoritarian rule toward democracy since Wahid became president in October and
attempted to reduce the military's long-standing sway over politics.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid, also known as Gus Dur, said he understood Wiranto's concerns that
resigning could leave him open to prosecution for war crimes, but said it would
be better for Indonesia if he steps down now.
</P>
<P>
	   It would show that the nation of 200 million people, undergoing severe
economic and political turmoil over the past three years, is serious about
democratic reforms and restoring stability.
</P>
<P>
	   ``His resignation will be seen by other countries as a sign we are serious,
that you can invest in Indonesia,'' Wahid said.
</P>
<P>
	   In Jakarta, Wiranto's aides refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, Wiranto allowed his troops to arm and train anti-independence
militias in East Timor as the territory headed for a U.N.-organized referendum
on independence. When East Timorese voted overwhelmingly to end a
quarter-century of Indonesian rule, the militias went on a rampage of burning
and killing.
</P>
<P>
	   Jose Ramos-Horta, an East Timorese leader and co-winner of the Nobel Peace
Prize in 1996, said Wiranto's removal had become inevitable.
</P>
<P>
	   The former general was ``totally isolated, even within the Indonesian armed
forces,'' Ramos-Horta said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Upon the decision of President Wahid to fire Wiranto, we must all, the
whole international community, back Gus Dur,'' Ramos-Horta said. ``At stake is
the credibility of the democratic regime in Indonesia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
