<DOCNO> APW20000212.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The "human trade" - wealth for smugglers, woes for smuggled  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Chen Jian looks scared and uncertain when asked about
his prospects. The 29-year-old illegal immigrant, after three years in the
United States, still owes $40,000 to cover the cost of being smuggled from
China.
<P>
	   In November, he discovered his kidney was rapidly failing and he needed a
transplant. Now he receives dialysis three times a week, which makes it
impossible for him to work and pay off his debt.
</P>
<P>
	   "I owe a lot of money so I waited a long time before I got this checked out.
I was barely able to stand by the time I saw the doctors," Chen said, speaking
in a voice strangely calm given his desperate situation.
</P>
<P>
	   His problems are compounded because his sister - who doctors say may be the
only source for a kidney - cannot get a U.S. visitor's visa. Immigration
officials worry that once here, she would try to stay on illegally.
</P>
<P>
	   While Chen's situation is extreme, Chinatown community activist Steven Wong
says the man from coastal Fujian province in southern China is also typical of
the thousands of Chinese illegal immigrants caught on a treadmill in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
	   They come to escape poverty and hopelessness in China, then get trapped
between greedy immigrant smugglers and the bureaucratic rules of the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service, said Wong.
</P>
<P>
	   Illegal immigration from China has skyrocketed since the Tiananmen Square
massacre in 1989. Although more than 280,000 Chinese are admitted to the United
States each year, estimates are that an additional 30,000 to 70,000 come
illegally.
</P>
<P>
	   "Many people would say they wouldn't even bother with trying to get a visa-
what was the use," said Li Yong Qian, the former head of a Chinatown community
organization.
</P>
<P>
	   Wong complained that INS and State Department officials refuse to recognize
some immigrants have real problems or genuine grounds for asylum. He said
officials fall back on bureaucratic attitudes and what he called racist
policies, which only add to the smuggling of aliens as families try to reunite.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is a belief that all Chinese want to come and stay here illegally,"
he said. "Why does there have to be this double standard?"
</P>
<P>
	   A State Department official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said
conditions within an applicant's home country may be taken into account in
deciding on a visa but that no country is discriminated against.
</P>
<P>
	   The source said the applicant's economic situation and ties to the community
are fully studied, then a consular officer decides whether there is a risk the
person will try to stay illegally in the country.
</P>
<P>
	   Aside from those who have obvious reasons for immigrating - like Chen's
sister - many Chinese are unhappy with the pace of economic reforms at home and
are drawn by the belief that pay is higher and opportunity greater in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
	   According to Ko-Lin Chin, author of "Smuggled Chinese: Clandestine
Immigration to the United States," (Temple University Press), the reality is
that immigrants often work 70 or 80 hour weeks in Chinatown restaurants or
garment factories for below minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
	   "People in Chinatown have a saying: 'We kiss the stove during the day and
kiss the pillow at night,"' Wong said, describing the daily routine of many
illegal Chinese immigrants.
</P>
<P>
	   Chen Jian says that after working in a candy factory for seven years he was
enticed to leave China by a smuggler's alluring description of the "American
Dream."
</P>
<P>
	   "The economy was bad and unpredictable where I was living. I was told that I
would be able to make a lot of money in the United States, and I wanted to
improve my situation," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
	   For most, the cost of the trip is high and the journey complex and
frightening. Prices run from $45,000 to $65,000 depending on how vigilant the
INS is at any time and the skills of the smuggler, said Ko-Lin Chin.
</P>
<P>
	   The smugglers - called "snakeheads" because their clients supposedly slither
across borders like snakes - run elaborate international networks of safehouses
and often use bribery to obtain passports and visas.
</P>
<P>
	   Since most Chinese do not have $45,000 or more, they usually borrow money
from relatives in the United States or from village or family organizations.
</P>
<P>
	   Chen Jian said that he gave his snakehead a deposit of $1,000, and borrowed
the rest from relatives. In return he was given a Chinese passport with a Thai
visa and was flown to Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
	   In Thailand, Chen waited only for two days in a safehouse for his smuggler
to get him a U.S. tourist visa, although many wait for weeks or months. He said
he then flew to San Francisco and simply "walked on through" - meaning he had no
problems with INS when he entered U.S. territory.
</P>
<P>
	   Chinese immigrants have long been smuggled to the West Coast in reeking ship
holds, by plane, or by road from Mexico and Canada. In the past two years,
smugglers have even taken to packing people in cargo containers for the trip
across the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
	   Illegal immigrants are difficult to catch, too. INS spokesman Don Mueller
says the agency tries to nab people at sea so they have fewer legal options.
Once the immigrants reach U.S. soil, he said, they have "a whole avenue of
options."
</P>
<P>
	   Many apply for political asylum, which can take "a significant amount of
time," Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Those that have a good case are likely to show up for their hearings and
those that don't aren't likely to show up and often disappear into the
underground economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The vast majority of those coming from China are economic migrants and INS
tries to return them, Mueller said. But last year, only 1,000 illegal Chinese
immigrants were sent home and 2,500 others applied for political asylum.
</P>
<P>
	   Mueller stressed that the United States' situation is not unique. "The
United Nations estimates that 500,000 to a million people leave China every year
to go to other countries so it is a worldwide problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ultimately, most illegal Chinese immigrants to America are sent to New York
because the city is home to the smuggling networks and to relatives of many
immigrants. The arrivals are often held in smugglers' safehouses until relatives
pay the full smuggling price, Ko-Lin Chin said. If the payment does not come
quickly, migrants are often beaten.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've seen guys come out of these places with hammer marks on their chest
or missing fingers. It's pretty ugly," Wong said.
</P>
<P>
	   For smugglers, the human trade pays very well and involves minimal danger.
</P>
<P>
	   "At $60,000 a head and with as many people as are being moved, we are
talking a billion dollar business. This is more lucrative than smuggling drugs,"
Wong said.
</P>
<P>
	   Mueller said the smugglers usually do not face much prison time if caught.
In extreme cases, some get up to five years per alien smuggled but that "it's
usually far less severe than that," he said. Ko-Lin Chin says some snakeheads
get as little as 15 months in jail.
</P>
<P>
	   Wong believes that the spread of immigrant smuggling can only be solved if
both the U.S. and Chinese governments stop pointing fingers at each other and
sit down to discuss a new approach to stemming the human tide.
</P>
<P>
	   "A better policy would be to wrongly admit 100 into this country," he said,
"rather than refuse to admit one person who is experiencing true hardship."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
