<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Adjusted for inflation, Whitman's spending patterns hit two-decade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman's second term budgets, when
adjusted for inflation, so far show a growth rate in spending the likes of which
New Jersey has not seen in 15 years.
<P>
	   The growth trends are concealed within dry, year-by-year budget summaries
and boasts of controlled spending.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've built a record of fiscal responsibility, a record of which we can be
proud," Whitman said in her Jan. 24 budget address. "We've held the annual rate
of growth of the state budget to its lowest level in 30 years."
</P>
<P>
	   But an Associated Press budget analysis that tracked spending over 20 years,
matching it against the Bureau of Labor Statistics' numbers on inflation, showed
a growth in government spending that rivaled the spending of former Gov. Thomas
Kean, a fellow Republican, in the revenue-rich 1980s.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman's budgets since her 1997 re-election have set several landmarks:
</P>
<P>
	   - State spending to provide services to New Jersey's 8 million residents
will bypass the magical $20 billion mark in July, and perhaps before then,
exceeding $2,600 for every man, woman and child.
</P>
<P>
	   - State spending last year increased enough to more than double what would
have been the normal growth caused by inflation over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1980, the budget was $4.89 billion. With inflation, that would equal
$9.89 billion in 1999. State spending in fiscal 1999, the last year audited, was
double that amount at $18.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   - The annual growth of state spending has hit 7.3 percent in the three years
of Whitman's second term, which is about 170 percent above the rate of
inflation. By comparison, Kean in his final term raised spending to about 100
percent above inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   In Kean's second term, January 1986 to January 1990, budgets increased an
average of 8.8 percent, but inflation in those four years was much higher than
now, averaging 4.5 percent. Inflation in Whitman's last three years has averaged
2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, it is quite possible the Legislature will add its own spending to
the $21.3 billion budget Whitman unveiled last month: Lawmakers have tacked on
additional spending in each of the past six years.
</P>
<P>
	   Judging from the last two years, legislative add-ons likely this spring and
additional spending by the Whitman administration next year probably will push
actual spending for the 2000-2001 fiscal year to $22 billion or beyond.
</P>
<P>
	   Even if the budget holds at its initial total of $21.3 billion, Whitman has
exceeded the spending increases under former Gov. Jim Florio, who is a frequent
target of Whitman's fiscal criticism.
</P>
<P>
	   "Less than 10 years ago, the state budget was balanced through higher taxes
on things like toilet paper and practices such as the state selling itself a
highway it already owned," the governor said in her Jan. 24 speech.
"Fortunately, those are now distant memories."
</P>
<P>
	   In his four years, Florio increased budgets an average of 5.5 percent during
a period when inflation averaged 2.6 percent. By contrast, Whitman over her six
budgets has increased spending an average of 5.3 percent in a period with
roughly the same inflation rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
