<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> For spot movement Sat. Feb. 12 for Sun. Feb. 13  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Far fewer mentally ill people have been ordered to
take their medication by courts under the state's "Kendra's Law" than some
advocates for the program predicted when the law took effect Nov. 8.
<P>
	   Only 20 people are under court order to take medication and only one of
those has been committed to a mental facility for failing to do so. County
mental health officials are reviewing 288 other cases to see if they should also
be brought before judges or some other treatment arrangement can be worked out,
state Mental Health Commissioner Dr. James Stone told a legislative budget
hearing last week.
</P>
<P>
	   Those numbers are a far cry from the estimates by some officials of how many
people would be subject to Kendra's Law when it was created by Gov. George
Pataki and the state Legislature last summer.
</P>
<P>
	   Those estimates varied from several hundred to one New York City official's
projection of 7,000 people falling under the program in the city alone.
</P>
<P>
	   But Roger Klingman, a spokesman for the state Office of Mental Health, said
that the Kendra's Law is being administered properly.
</P>
<P>
	   "Given the fact the program has been implemented for only three months,
those are significant numbers," Klingman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kendra's Law is named after Kendra Webdale, a woman who was pushed to her
death under the wheels of a New York City subway train in January 1999 by a man
with a long history of psychiatric troubles and treatment.
</P>
<P>
	   The program is chiefly administered by county mental health officials. They
get referrals from doctors, hospitals, family members and others of people who
are suffering from severe mental illnesses and not taking their medication. If
people could pose a danger to themselves or to others, they are subject to the
Kendra's Law provisions.
</P>
<P>
	   County mental health workers try to work out a treatment and medicine-taking
regimen with those people.
</P>
<P>
	   Stone told legislators that 91 people have been evaluated and voluntarily
accepted treatment rather than face court orders.
</P>
<P>
	   Harvey Rosenthal, executive director of the New York Association of
Psychiatric Rehabilitation Services, said his group questions how "voluntary"
those 91 cases really were.
</P>
<P>
	   "Is there a subtle form of coercion because people have to accept what is
offered because they'll have to go to court if they don't?" Rosenthal asked. "I
have heard rumors that people have been told, 'Either agree to this now or we'll
see you in court.' But we have no hard data."
</P>
<P>
	   If a case ends up before a court under Kendra's Law, a mental hygiene legal
services representative must be present to represent the interests of the
mentally ill person. Rosenthal suggested that such a legal representative should
also be present when the mentally ill are brought in by county mental health
officials to discuss treatment and medication options.
</P>
<P>
	   Rosenthal's group opposed the involuntary commitment aspects of Kendra's
Law. He said, however, that the law has forced county mental health officials to
become more closely involved in the cases of the seriously ill in their
counties.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, Gov. George Pataki has proposed spending $125 million more in
the 2000-2001 state budget on the mentally ill. That will include significant
new resources on the screening and treatment of the seriously mentally ill,
Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor also declared a moratorium for 2000 on the downsizing of state
mental institutions to give officials more time to evaluate how many beds are
needed to treat the seriously mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
	   Stone told legislators last week it is too early to tell if the moratorium
should continue past this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-12-00 1410 </TRAILER>
