<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Albanians Flee Serb Area  </HEADLINE>
   By ELENA BECATOROS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Despite new security measures, ethnic
Albanians fled from the Serb part of this city Saturday, complaining that angry
Serbs had forced them to leave and that the United Nations was powerless to stop
it.
</P>
<P>
	   An ethnic Albanian human rights group demanded French peacekeepers leave
Kosovska Mitrovica because they had lost control to ``Serb criminals.'' Kosovo's
most multiethnic city has been wracked by violence since a grenade attack last
week on a U.N. bus killed two elderly Serbs.
</P>
<P>
	   Since then, Serbs have been forcing ethnic Albanians to leave their homes in
the northern part of the city despite appeals by U.N. chief administrator
Bernard Kouchner and others. On Friday, Kouchner announced new security
measures, including more police and U.N. troops to protect the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
	   Kouchner's announcement, however, did little to calm the deteriorating
situation. Ethnic Albanians, carrying a few belongings in plastic bags, lumbered
Saturday across the bridge over the Ibar River to the safety of the southern,
Albanian-dominated side.
</P>
<P>
	   Sylejman Deliv said about 20 bearded Serb men came to his apartment building
at 5 a.m., banged on the apartments of ethnic Albanian residents and ordered
them to leave immediately or ``we will kill you.''
</P>
<P>
	   Deliv said the terrified residents telephoned the U.N. civilian police.
``But they didn't do anything,'' so the residents left.
</P>
<P>
	   Sylejman Plana, 55, and his wife, Advie, 52, said they were expelled earlier
in the week but tried to return to their apartment to pick up personal
belongings. After peacekeepers refused to escort them home, the couple returned
to the north side on their own.
</P>
<P>
	   Sylejman Plana said they were intercepted by Serbs ``who beat me'' and
turned them back.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's not enough to have just one policeman,'' he said as he stood,
bewildered, on the bridge trying to decide what to do next. ``They will attack
us. They will kill us.''
</P>
<P>
	   It was unclear how many of the estimated 4,500 ethnic Albanians living in
the Serb area had been expelled during the past week. The U.N. High Commissioner
for Refugees said Friday that about 650 ethnic Albanians had registered with the
United Nations for humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
	   Many others probably did not bother to register and simply moved in with
friends or relatives in the ethnic Albanian part of the city, U.N. officials
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Halit Berani, head of the local ethnic Albanian ``Committee for the Defense
of Human Rights,'' said that, over the past two days, a total of 71 expulsion
cases had been reported to his group.
</P>
<P>
	   He urged NATO to remove the French troops from the city.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The French army and U.N. police left the positions they were at, they
withdrew and they didn't do anything,'' he said. ``The Serb criminals then had
their hands free to do whatever they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
	   A French spokesman, Lt. Col. Patrick Chanliau, described the situation in
the city Saturday as ``calm but tense.'' He said someone threw a grenade and
opened fire late Friday at a Serb house in the north of the city, but there were
no injuries.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of the increased security, Kouchner said the United Nations would
enforce a decree issued last year authorizing police and troops to expel from
the city or even the province any ``troublemakers'' who foment discord.
</P>
<P>
	   He also said a ``security zone'' would be established where public protests
would be banned.
</P>
<P>
	   About 140 British reinforcements have moved into the city, joining 150
German, Dutch and Italian reinforcements that already had arrived. Several U.N.
policemen have complained that the French were slow to respond when the violence
exploded last week.
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere, NATO said an American peacekeeper, whose name was not released,
was in stable condition Saturday after suffering a gunshot wound to the leg late
Friday. An Army spokeswoman, Maj Debbie Allen, said investigators were looking
into whether the wound was accidentally self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
	   Three ethnic Albanians were arrested after shooting in the direction of
Norwegian soldiers near Obilic, NATO said. No one was hurt. Also Friday, a
vehicle carrying Russian soldiers struck a dynamite device buried along a road
near Glogovac in central Kosovo, NATO said. There were no injuries, but the
vehicle was heavily damaged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
