<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hiroshima Tail Gunner Mementos Sold  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHEAT RIDGE, Colo. (AP) -- Items collected by the tail gunner on the plane
that dropped a nuclear bomb on Hiroshima will auctioned off.
</P>
<P>
	   The photos, books, clothing and other mementos are part of the estate of
George Robert Caron. He was on the Enola Gay, the B-29 that dropped the bomb on
Aug. 6, 1945.
</P>
<P>
	   Caron, who was given a camera at the last moment, snapped a roll of
photographs as the mushroom cloud ascended. His photographs of the explosion
were printed on millions of leaflets that were dropped over Japan the next day.
</P>
<P>
	   Kay Caron, his widow, and their four children are auctioning the material
Sunday. Among the objects is a photograph signed by five of the bomber's 12-man
crew.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We want it to be in the hands of people who will appreciate the history,''
said his daughter, Jane Wunder.
</P>
<P>
	   After the war, Caron worked as a design engineer for Sundstrand Corp. He
died in 1995 of complications from pneumonia at age 75.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
