<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Fragrance Museum offers visitors an aromatic experience  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The Metropolitan Museum of Art is so big it's hard to
decide what to see, and at the Guggenheim you just go round and round. But now a
new museum is adding some scents to the art scene in New York.
<P>
	   	   The Museum of Fragrance is housed in a small loft on East 32nd Street,
far from Fifth Avenue's tony "museum mile." While it has no Old Masters, its
history of fragrance in America offers pleasures for both the nose and eye.
</P>
<P>
	   Along with a display of 250 fragrance flacons, there's a 25-foot timeline
showing which fragrances were introduced from 1949 through the 1990s and how
they were tied to social trends.
</P>
<P>
	   In the 1950s, the decade that brought us TV dinners and Elvis, women wooed
men with scents called "Hope," "Ambush" and "Intimate." Twenty years later, with
the women's movement in full swing, marketing experts reflected that with
fragrances like "Charlie," "Blazer" and "Woman."
</P>
<P>
	   There's also a "Smelling Scenter," where visitors can sniff popular
ingredients from each decade, and a "Seeing Scents" corner to view fragrance
commercials through the years.
</P>
<P>
	   The 45-minute video narrated by television pioneer Imogene Coca may not
appeal to those who heard enough of the "Charlie" jingle in the 1970s, but it is
a great mirror into the social goings-on in the past.
</P>
<P>
	   A 1950s Avon commercial tells us that even drab housewives in bathrobes can
become princesses with a dab of perfume (theirs, of course). In the '60s,
mini-skirted women found the man wearing "High Karate" irresistible. But by the
1970s, the "Enjoli" woman could do it all herself - "bring home the bacon, and
fry it up in a pan."
</P>
<P>
	   Annette Green, president of the industry group, The Fragrance Foundation,
worked for years to develop the museum, which opened in November. She said it's
the first of its kind in America; similar fragrance museums exist in Paris and
Oita Island in Japan.
</P>
<P>
	   "Smell is the most misunderstood and ignored of all our senses," said Green.
And with the explosion in the U.S. fragrance industry - its annual retail sales
have grow from $250,000 in 1950 to $6 billion today - it's a profitable one as
well. Those figures do not even include the booming home fragrance, bath and
body, and aromatherapy markets.
</P>
<P>
	   The current exhibit, "50 Years of Fragrance in America," commemorates the
foundation's 50th anniversary and runs through April 28.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1949, when the foundation was organized to convince American women that
perfume, toilette water and cologne could add romance to their otherwise dull
lives, fragrance meant two things: French and expensive.
</P>
<P>
	   "Those lucky enough to have it would only use it for special occasions, and
then they would put on their string of pearls and put exactly two dabs behind
each ear," Green said.
</P>
<P>
	   In the 1950s, European manufacturers introduced 30 new women's fragrances
and six for men. It wasn't until the 1960s that Revlon introduced the first
American-born fragrance, Norell.
</P>
<P>
	   If the '50s belonged to America's housewives, the '60s were owned by the
hippies, Green said. "It was the first time a fragrance came from the streets,"
she said, after a group of back-to-nature Californians bottled and sold musk oil
as a scent.
</P>
<P>
	   By the early 1970s, Jovan capitalized on the musk trend and its musk oil
perfume became the hottest selling fragrance in America. The '70s was also the
decade of "Annie Hall," menswear for women and "Charlie," a fragrance that
appealed to young, independent women.
</P>
<P>
	   Beginning in the '60s, men also became fragrance wearers. In the 1950s, 90
percent of all fragrances sold were for women. Today the gap is closing: 60
percent of scents sold are women's fragrances and 40 percent men's.
</P>
<P>
	   The '80s brought perfumes by American designers like Ralph Lauren and Calvin
Klein and, said Green, for "the first time women began to think of fragrance as
a must-have fashion accessory."
</P>
<P>
	   Like everything else in the driven 1980s, fragrances introduced in that
decade - with names like "Poison" and "Obsession' - were big and over-the-top.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was a voluptuous, egocentric decade and fragrances were too," Green
said. "People wanted you to be able to smell them from across the room."
</P>
<P>
	   In the 1990s, Green said, fragrance fans were choosing different scents to
match their moods - whether they wanted to be energized or relaxed.
</P>
<P>
	   Green predicts the next trend will be fragrances to help stressed out
workers and harried homebodies relax.
</P>
<P>
	   "They're already working on virtual reality cable boxes that will release
smells of the ocean or rainforest into our living rooms at the touch of a
button," Green said.
</P>
<P>
	   She said alarm clocks may release spritzes of citrus or peppermint in the
air to awaken and energize, adding it all part of the new importance of
fragrance.
</P>
<P>
	   "For the first time in history," she said, "smell is being recognized as an
influential sense."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
