<HEADLINE> Giuliani calls for release of national oil reserve  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, accusing President Clinton of
ignoring the pain of New Yorkers, called Saturday for the release of the
country's oil reserve to offset this winter's staggering increase in home
heating oil costs.
<P>
	   Clinton was "clearly turning his back on the suffering of all New Yorkers
around the state," the mayor said at City Hall. "What I've learned is that the
only way to reach the White House is to make it a political issue."
</P>
<P>
	   White House deputy press secretary Jim Kennedy responded that selling the
Strategic Petroleum Reserve to lower oil prices was not allowed by law.
</P>
<P>
	   "The president has taken strong measures to help struggling families pay
their energy bills," Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer contradicted Kennedy, saying sale of the reserve
was legal in an emergency. The Clinton administration has not labeled the
current situation as meeting that standard.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani released a three-paragraph letter that he sent to the White House,
urging the sale of a portion of the reserve to create competition that would
drive prices down.
</P>
<P>
	   Many other politicians in the Northeast, including Schumer, have also called
on the president to provide relief for the oil prices.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, which pays the nation's highest home heating oil costs, the
price per gallon has shot up from 72 cents to $2.50 since the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   Schumer said he welcomed Giuliani's efforts.
</P>
<P>
	   "My attitude is, 'The more, the merrier,"' said Schumer, who first called
for sale of the reserve in September. "We can use all the support we can get."
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani estimated the drastic increase would end up costing the city as
much as $14 million, while the average New Yorker would pay an extra $350 this
winter to heat their home.
</P>
<P>
	   "New Yorkers are feeling real pain," Giuliani said. "Unfortunately,
President Clinton is not feeling the pain of New Yorkers."
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani's shots at Clinton came as first lady Hillary Clinton, his opponent
in November's U.S. Senate election, made campaign stops in four of the city's
five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
	   The mayor urged the sale of 2 percent of the reserve to lower oil prices.
The prices began soaring after the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
rolled back production by 4.3 million barrels a day last year.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal government earlier this week announced $130 million in
assistance to help the indigent cover their heating costs. But Energy Secretary
William Richardson said there were no plans to sell the reserve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
