<HEADLINE> Aussie, Kenya Tribes Fight for Land  </HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE MWANGI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOODOARAIAK, Kenya (AP) -- At first glance, the two peoples couldn't be more
different.
</P>
<P>
	   The four Australian Aborigines were clad in jeans and T-shirts. Sitting
nearby under an acacia tree were 30 Maasai tribal elders draped in traditional
red shawls called shukas, with beads dangling from their elongated ear lobes.
</P>
<P>
	   Although distinct in appearance and usually separated by language and 7,000
miles, Kenya's Maasai and Australia's Aborigines are bound together by their
special, often troubled, tie to the land.
</P>
<P>
	   As cattle herders, they rely on the land for their livelihood. As indigenous
peoples, they have been victimized by British colonists who stole the land. And
as tiny minorities, they are fighting to keep the land or get it back.
</P>
<P>
	   That common legacy brought representatives of the two peoples together one
week ago near Loodoaraiak, about 55 miles southwest of the Kenyan capital of
Nairobi, where they held daylong discussions sponsored by the London-based
non-governmental organization Pilotlight.
</P>
<P>
	   Under current Kenyan law, the government holds land in trust for the Maasai,
an arrangement ripe for exploitation. A bill now pending in the country's
Parliament would recognize the land rights of the Maasai and other pastoralist
tribes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our land is being taken away from us systematically using a pen and
paper,'' said Joseph Ole Simel, a Loodoaraiak community leader. ``Influential
people come here driving very expensive cars and say, 'This is my land.' And
when we ask them to prove it, they produce title deeds.''
</P>
<P>
	   Aborigines, who are believed to have inhabited Australia for about 50,000
years prior to white settlement, also are engaged in a struggle over land. Now
numbering about 353,000, they make up only a tiny minority in the nation's
mostly white population of 18.7 million people.
</P>
<P>
	   Relations between their leaders and the government have soured because of
Prime Minister John Howard's restrictions on Aboriginal land rights.
</P>
<P>
	   Howard also enraged many indigenous leaders last year by stopping short of
saying the word ``sorry'' after Australia's Parliament passed a motion
expressing regret for the treatment of Aborigines.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is still no proper recognition of Aboriginal rights to land,'' said
June Oscar, director of the Kimberly Land Council in western Australia and one
of the four Aborigines who traveled to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
	   During the daylong discussions on Feb. 6, the Aborigines and Maasai compared
strategies and obstacles.
</P>
<P>
	   Chief among their complaints was the belief, still held by many people, that
until white colonizers arrived in Kenya and Australia, the land belonged to no
one.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We share similar sacred sites which are being threatened by the
encroachment of our land,'' said Joanne Willmot, 46, head of the Uluru-Kata
Tjuta National Park Board of Management in Australia.
</P>
<P>
	   The Maasai, encouraged that the Aborigines shared their dreams, were
defiant.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We shall resist any attempt to take this land from us even if it means we
die here,'' Simel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1445 </TRAILER>
