<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 17 Killed in India State Vote  </HEADLINE>
   By MANISH KUMAR Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PATNA, India (AP) -- Violence marred an election in one of India's largest
and poorest states Saturday, with land mine explosions and gunfire killing 17
people -- mostly police.
</P>
<P>
	   The three-phased election in the northeastern state of Bihar featured a race
for the chief minister's job that included one of India's most colorful leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   In the worst of the five land mine explosions in Bihar, eight policemen were
killed in a rural area Friday night. In four mine attacks Saturday, six police
and two poll workers were killed and six others were wounded.
</P>
<P>
	   One policeman was shot dead in a gun battle after one of the explosions.
</P>
<P>
	   Police said they suspected the Maoist Communist Center, which had called for
an election boycott. The leftist group has been blamed for many attacks on
upper-caste villages.
</P>
<P>
	   In the last state assembly election in 1995, more than 70 people were killed
in clashes among rival political activists or in battles with police.
</P>
<P>
	   More than half the 20 million eligible voters cast their ballots in the
first day of the election for the state government, which the colorful Laloo
Prasad Yadav and his wife, Rabri Devi, have headed for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
	   The second stage of voting is Thursday, the third is Feb. 22, and results
will be released Feb. 25.
</P>
<P>
	   Police put on a show of force and authorized local forces to open fire at
political vandals. But despite the heavy security, unidentified gunmen shot at a
candidate in central Bihar, seriously injuring him, the United News of India
reported.
</P>
<P>
	   At least 36 of the more than 3,000 candidates have criminal records or are
facing serious charges in court, police said.
</P>
<P>
	   Among those candidates still embroiled in criminal cases is Yadav, the
former chief minister who changed the face of Indian politics by fashioning a
powerful voting block of low-caste Hindus and ousting political parties
dominated by higher castes.
</P>
<P>
	   While polls showed a tight race for the state's top political position,
analysts predicted Yadav would likely fall from power because of corruption
cases and public frustration over the lack of development in Bihar.
</P>
<P>
	   Yadav, who was first voted chief minister in 1989, was jailed for five
months in 1997 in connection with a scandal over the government paying bogus
bills for animal fodder. He has been released on bail but could still serve jail
time if convicted.
</P>
<P>
	   When Yadav was forced to resign while in prison, his party named his wife to
head the state government, although she could barely read and write. She is the
current chief minister.
</P>
<P>
	   The main opponents of Yadav and his Rashtriya Janata Dal party are the
National Democratic Alliance -- the ruling coalition of the federal government
under Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee -- and the chief federal opposition,
the Congress party.
</P>
<P>
	   Violence also marred polling in the northeastern state of Manipur, the only
other Indian state voting Saturday for a new state legislature. At least six
people were killed and 10 others were injured in two attacks by armed militants,
The Press Trust of India reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
