<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Princeton proposes sweeping smoking ban  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Your house. Outside. The cigar shop.
<P>
	   If the Princeton Regional Health Commission has its way, those will be only
three places a smoker will be able to light up.
</P>
<P>
	   The commission, which oversees public health in Princeton Borough and
Princeton Township, on Tuesday will introduce the most far-reaching municipal
smoking ban in New Jersey. A public hearing and vote will follow next month.
</P>
<P>
	   Other New Jersey towns have passed ordinances prohibiting smoking in a more
piecemeal fashion. Glassboro, Highland Park, Lawrence Township, Marlboro,
Secaucus and South Brunswick restrict smoking in a variety of sites, according
to antismoking activists.
</P>
<P>
	   But no town has proposed as sweeping a ban as Princeton's. It covers it all
- almost.
</P>
<P>
	   The only exception written into the proposed ordinance is for retail tobacco
shops, according to regional Health Officer Bill Hinshillwood. Otherwise, butts
out, under the proposed code.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're looking at something comprehensive that ties in everything that some
other towns have done," he said. "It covers all public places, workplaces,
restaurants and bars."
</P>
<P>
	   In the works for about six months, the proposal started as a garden variety
smoking ban in specific locations. But then commission members began to think
globally, according to Hinshillwood.
</P>
<P>
	   "The commission considers any environmental smoke as a health hazard, so
it's not justified from a public health standpoint to make exemptions," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hence, bars, where smoking bans are politically difficult to enact, were
included, he said. Bartenders have as much right to a smoke-free environment as
any other kind of employee, the commission believes.
</P>
<P>
	   Hinshillwood declined to supply a copy of the draft proposal, saying
commission members are still "playing around with it." It will be available for
Tuesday's 7:30 p.m. meeting at Borough Hall, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   While unprecedented in New Jersey, outright bans are the rule in the state
of California and in scores of communities elsewhere in the nation, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The two municipalities surrounding Ivy League Princeton University in leafy
northern Mercer County have long been out front on antismoking efforts. They
were among the earliest communities to prohibit cigarette vending machines,
smoking around schools and smoking in municipal buildings, according to Regina
Carlson, executive director of the New Jersey Group Against Smoking Pollution.
</P>
<P>
	   So it didn't surprise her when the two communities became the first in New
Jersey to propose such an exhaustive ban, given the affluence and education of
residents there.
</P>
<P>
	   "Those kinds of places provide more protection (for nonsmokers) than poor,
struggling towns," Carlson said. "Smoke-free air is a luxury when you can't
afford to eat."
</P>
<P>
	   Although Hinshillwood predicted residents will support the new proposal, one
Princeton restaurant owner said the commission can expect a fight.
</P>
<P>
	   "They have not asked my employees what they thought," said Tom Schmierer,
owner of the Alchemist and Barrister, an upscale fixture in the local restaurant
scene. "It sounds like they've done a lot of nonsmoking research but not any
business research. I don't smoke, but I realize it's part of the business."
</P>
<P>
	   Schmierer, whose three dining rooms are all smoke-free, said his waiters
volunteer to work in the smoky bar. Tips there are plentiful, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   A smoking ban would chase loyal customers to bars in neighboring towns where
smoking is still allowed, he complained.
</P>
<P>
	   "They keep comparing us to the state of California, but this is a smaller
area. Smokers can go a couple miles up the road. It's not a level playing
field," Schmierer said.
</P>
<P>
	   Although his establishment is exempt from the proposed ban, Jorge
Armenteros, owner of the Little Taste of Cuba cigar shop, said he, too, opposes
the proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   "This might help my business if this is the only place where people are
allowed to smoke, but I'm not happy as an American citizen," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-12-00 1453 </TRAILER>
