<HEADLINE> Teen-ager's Last Wish Unfulfilled  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID KINNEY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMP HILL, Pa. (AP) -- A teen-ager with a brain tumor died Saturday without
being able to fulfill a last wish: to donate his vital organs.
</P>
<P>
	   Nicholas Breach, 14 of Camp Hill, went into cardiac arrest and died at home.
His heart couldn't be restarted in the ambulance en route to Hershey Medical
Center, and by the time he arrived, it was too late to harvest his heart, lungs,
kidneys and liver.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If the heart cannot be restarted, there is too much damage to organs and
they cannot be recovered for transplant,'' said Kevin Sparkman, director of the
Gift of Life Donor Program in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
	   Nicholas was able to donate his corneas for sight-restoring surgery,
however, Sparkman said.
</P>
<P>
	   The eighth-grader had decided to donate his organs after learning in
November that a brain-stem tumor -- the second diagnosed by doctors -- would
take his life.
</P>
<P>
	   Nicholas' last wish may not have been in vain. His reaction to imminent
death by calling an organ donation agency brought attention from as far as South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Breaches got numerous e-mails from people, people wishing them well,
people waiting for transplants, people who had received transplants,'' Sparkman
said. ``We got inquiries literally from around the world.''
</P>
<P>
	   Family members declined comment Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Nicholas is survived by his parents, Rick and Kim Breach, and his
17-year-old brother, Nathan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1502 </TRAILER>
