<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabweans Vote on Constitution  </HEADLINE>
   By ANGUS SHAW Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- President Robert Mugabe's waning popularity was put
to the test in a referendum Saturday, but lines for scarce fuel were longer than
those at polling stations -- underscoring the seriousness of Zimbabwe's economic
woes.
</P>
<P>
	   Voter turnout was generally low nationwide on the first of two days of
voting, election officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite a spate of political violence in the runup to the poll, there were
no reports of injuries or arrests Saturday, said Police Chief Augustine Chihuri.
However, police dealt with a few minor scuffles and were investigating reports
of intimidation to prevent ballots being cast in some areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Zimbabweans were voting on proposed changes to the constitution that would
allow Mugabe to retain most of his powers despite growing opposition to his
rule. The constitutional changes also would allow the government to seize land
owned by white descendants of British settlers without paying compensation.
</P>
<P>
	   Lovemore Madhuku, an official of the National Constitutional Assembly, a
coalition of civic, human rights, church and lawyers' groups opposed to the
revised constitution, accused the government of preventing election monitors
from reaching 3,600 polling stations across the country -- opening the way for
rigging.
</P>
<P>
	   The locations of polling stations were announced Friday and monitors
provided by civic groups to the state Electoral Supervisory Commission only
managed to get to 60 percent of the stations in time, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's as if the government wanted to go through this election alone,
without monitors,'' said Priscilla Misihairabwi, a monitoring coordinator.
</P>
<P>
	   She said poll officers took names of voters, enabling their identity to be
linked to a serial number on each ballot paper.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is intimidatory. People fear their vote will be known to the
authorities and they'll vote accordingly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Monitors reported ruling party supporters tearing down opposition posters
Saturday and favored politicians and pro-government tribal chiefs being given
free access to polling stations in violation of voting rules.
</P>
<P>
	   The state Elections Directorate had ``arrogantly'' refused to meet monitors
or NCA officials to discuss their concerns Saturday, Madhuku said.
</P>
<P>
	   An economic crisis has spurred the biggest opposition challenge to Mugabe's
ruling party since he led the former British colony of Rhodesia to independence
in 1980 as Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
	   Inflation and unemployment have soared and diesel, gasoline and power
shortages since December have crippled transport, industry and agriculture. In
Harare, lines for kerosene and gasoline contrasted sharply with the small
clusters of voters passing through polling stations.
</P>
<P>
	   Results are expected Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
