<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Guerrillas Attack Israel  </HEADLINE>
   By ZEINA KARAM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Hezbollah guerrillas mounted a fresh attack against
Israeli troops in southern Lebanon on Saturday, a day after they killed a
seventh Israeli soldier and seriously wounded another.
</P>
<P>
	   A Hezbollah official promised more ``humiliating'' attacks.
</P>
<P>
	   Security officials said the guerrillas fired several U.S.-made TOW missiles
at the Israeli outpost in Bayyada overlooking the southern port city of Tyre,
which is about a mile from the Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
	   There were no reports of casualties from the afternoon attack, the officials
said on condition of anonymity. The United States accused the Hezbollah
guerrilla group of using civilian areas to attack Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
	   The Israeli army said its troops returned fire. ``The army views with
severity the firing from villages in the security zone,'' a statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   Israeli officials said Hezbollah has become more efficient recently through
its use of TOW missiles, which are being supplied by Hezbollah's backer, Iran.
The guerrillas have killed seven Israeli soldiers in less than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   The attack Saturday occurred amid an upsurge in violence on the last active
Arab-Israeli warfront. Israeli warplanes recently have knocked out three power
stations in Lebanon and made daily strikes against guerrilla targets in southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   International monitors met Friday to defuse tensions, but Israeli
representatives walked out of the meeting after guerrillas killed an Israeli
soldier and wounded another in a rocket attack.
</P>
<P>
	   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said he would retaliate for the casualties
in his own time with ``very harsh strikes in Lebanon,'' but he reaffirmed a
pledge to withdraw his troops by July.
</P>
<P>
	   Undaunted, the leader of Hezbollah vowed more attacks with the aim of
driving Israeli forces out of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The bombing of infrastructure in Lebanon will not protect the (Israeli)
occupation troops. Rather, it will expose them to more painful strikes,''
Hezbollah leader Sheik Hassan Nasrallah told Egypt's Al-Ahram newspaper Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   A Hezbollah legislator said Saturday that his group had not given up on
launching rockets at northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking at a rally in the city of Baalbek in eastern Lebanon, Ammar Musawi
said the settlements in northern Israel were ``tempting targets.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``If Israel wants to put an end to its losses and humiliation, it should
withdraw (from Lebanon) as soon as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The recent fighting has seriously eroded the chances of resuming
Israeli-Syrian peace talks, which were postponed indefinitely last month. Israel
has said Syria -- the main power broker in Lebanon -- should rein in the
guerrillas if it is serious about negotiating peace.
</P>
<P>
	   Syrian state-run newspaper Tishrin said Israel would not have escalated the
conflict in Lebanon without U.S. support. Israeli arrogance, the editorial said,
``would have never reached what it has attained without the unlimited supply of
American weapons pouring into Israel and without the blind (U.S.) political
support that pampers aggression...''
</P>
<P>
	   On Saturday, Arab League Secretary-General Esmat Abdel-Meguid phoned Daniel
Kurtzer, the U.S. ambassador to Egypt, to express the ``anger and condemnation
prevailing in the Arab and Muslim world toward this dangerous aggression.''
</P>
<P>
	   A statement issued by the 22-member league said Abdel-Meguid asked Kurtzer
to relay a message to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, urging the United
States to help end Israel's aggression ``in order for just and comprehensive
peace to prevail in the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
	   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak also called for a resumption of peace talks
between Syria and Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1511 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gloves off in both nomination races  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - No more Mr. Nice Guys. Not George W. Bush, not John
McCain, not Bill Bradley, and certainly not Al Gore.
<P>
	   This was going to be the different campaign for the White House, positive
and polite, above attack politics and all that - until it got competitive, first
for the Democrats, then the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   The hardening line between GOP rivals Bush and McCain mirrored the earlier
shift in Democratic tactics, begun when the vice president stopped ignoring
Bradley's challenge and went after him in the fall.
</P>
<P>
	   At the time, Gore's campaign was off to a faltering beginning, so Gore
reinvented it and said he would run like an underdog.
</P>
<P>
	   He challenged Bradley to weekly campaign debates, attacked his rival's
centerpiece health care coverage proposal, and said the former New Jersey
senator was too left-of-center to win.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said that showed he was gaining ground because Gore had ignored him
for 10 months, not even mentioning the challenger. When they did debate, in
October in Hanover, N.H., Gore took the offensive, while Bradley ventured only
mild rebuttals.
</P>
<P>
	   Not now.
</P>
<P>
	   The exchanges escalated debate by debate, seven so far. In the last one,
just after Gore's victory by a 2-to-1 margin in the Iowa Democratic caucuses,
Bradley was the attacker. He accused Gore of a dishonest campaign, of coddling
special interests, of "a thousand promises and a thousand attacks."
</P>
<P>
	   After Gore's narrow victory in the New Hampshire primary, Bradley reversed
the debate challenge; now he wants them weekly.
</P>
<P>
	   But Gore already had moved past that point: He demands two a week as part of
a deal in which both candidates would stop broadcasting television commercials.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley called that a gimmick, aimed at handicapping him because he is the
lesser-known candidate. He said it was typical of old-style Washington politics.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said Bradley was being negative. Bradley said Gore was.
</P>
<P>
	   Which sounds like Bush vs. McCain in their argument about rival ads, each
accusing the other of breaking pledges against negative campaigning.
</P>
<P>
	   A McCain spot said Bush was twisting the truth like President Clinton. A
Bush ad said McCain was trying to mislead voters, and charged the Arizona
senator was soliciting campaign money from special interest lobbyists while
running as a reformer.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain offered to drop his hostile ads if Bush would. "Pull your ads and
we'll pull our ads and we'll all be nice guys again," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's a Washington, D.C., political trick," the Texas governor retorted.
He said he had been smeared and he meant to defend himself.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, in an abrupt change in strategy, McCain unilaterally disarmed. He
pulled from the air his ads attacking Bush after advisers determined the
commercials were compromising his campaign as a self-styled political outsider.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush did not budge. "It's a bait-and-switch trick," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Democratic campaign, Bradley is making an issue of Gore's role in the
Democratic fund-raising excesses of the 1996 campaign, saying the Republicans
could clean house on that front in the fall.
</P>
<P>
	   Back to the Republicans: McCain argues Bush would not be able to confront
Gore about his conduct because Bush does not support campaign finance reforms to
do away with unregulated donations to the political parties.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush challenges McCain's credentials as a reformer, saying that while McCain
campaigns on the issue, he is soliciting money from special interest lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush now styles himself as "a reformer with results" in Texas. McCain
dismisses the claim to his central issue.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bush offensive began after he took an 18-point beating from McCain in
the New Hampshire primary Feb. 1. Bush won earlier in Iowa and then again in
Delaware last week.
</P>
<P>
	   "Somehow I got defined as the insider and he got defined as the outsider and
those days are over with," Bush said, campaigning in South Carolina, which holds
its primary Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said Bush was getting desperate.
</P>
<P>
	   It only has been a month since McCain and Bush agreed during a campaign
debate not to use attack ads.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'd like to shake hands on that right now," McCain said, and they did.
Steve Forbes, for whom hard-line ads became a trademark, would not join them. No
matter; he quit the campaign for lack of support in first round of voting.
</P>
<P>
	   It was only little more than two months ago that Bush volunteered words of
praise for McCain, when McCain's temper and temperament for the White House was
being challenged.
</P>
<P>
	   "Let me say one thing, before I start, about Senator McCain," Bush prefaced
a debate answer. "He's a good man. He's a good man."
</P>
<P>
	   "Thanks," McCain said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't know what compelled me to say that about you, senator," Bush said.
"He's a good friend."
</P>
<P>
	   The smile is gone now.
</P>
<P>
	   "The days of smiling and letting John McCain define me are over," Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   ----
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears has reported on Washington and national
politics for The Associated Press for more than 35 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
