<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   High pressure brought mostly clear and dry conditions to the Great Lakes and
Northeast on Saturday, while clouds and rain spread across much of the West.
</P>
<P>
	   The high pressure kept conditions clear but cool for areas north of the Ohio
River.
</P>
<P>
	   A disturbance pushing out of the Tennessee Valley brought snow to Delaware,
Maryland and Virginia. The same system carried rain showers into the Carolinas.
The rest of the Southeast was partly cloudy and dry, with a few showers in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
	   Skies were mostly cloudy through the northern Plains, and a few light snow
showers pushed into Minnesota and western Wisconsin. To the south, conditions
were mostly clear through much of Missouri, Arkansas, Louisiana, Texas and
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
	   Clouds covered much of the western part of the country. Moisture pushing
inland from the Pacific Ocean continued to bring scattered showers to northern
California and sections of Washington and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
	   Scattered showers also fell in Idaho, Utah, Nevada, Colorado, Wyoming and
Arizona, with snow in the higher elevations.
</P>
<P>
	   Saturday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a morning low
of 23 below zero in Iron Mountain, Mich., to a midday reading of 77 in
Harlingen, Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
