<HEADLINE> Hillary tours NYC as an official candidate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton schmoozed and smiled her way
through New York City on Saturday, planning five campaign stops in four boroughs
in an effort to rally support from minorities and elderly voters, whose help
she'll need in her run for U.S. Senate.
<P>
	   Clinton returned to the city after a whirlwind week upstate following the
official announcement of her bid last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   She met with black Democrats and senior citizens in Queens, and made
campaign stops at the Caridad Restaurant, a Hispanic eatery in Washington
Heights; and a Democratic rally in the Bronx. She was also attending a dinner in
Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
	   The well-chosen crowds loved her.
</P>
<P>
	   "We will be behind you, and we will be able to march you on to victory in
November," U.S. Rep. Gregory Meeks, D-N.Y., told a beaming Clinton before about
150 black Democrats at York College in Jamaica, Queens.
</P>
<P>
	   The crowd cheered and chanted "Hillary, Hillary, Hillary!" as Clinton vowed
to push for new jobs and affordable health care, teacher training and a tax
deduction for college tuition.
</P>
<P>
	   "She has nearly total support in the black community," said Jeff Diggs, a
Queens resident at the rally.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is no choice in the black community except her," Diggs said. "Not
only is Mr. (Rudolph) Giuliani so unpopular, but the issues that she espouses
are clearly those that appeal to the black community."
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton will need heavy turnout from neighborhoods like Jamaica - a working
class black enclave with a powerful Democratic organization - if she is to
defeat Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
	   Without mentioning the mayor by name, Clinton alluded to the criticism that
has flown between the two campaigns this week over issues like campaign
fundraising and posting the ten commandments in public school classrooms.
</P>
<P>
	   "I intend to run a campaign on issues and ideas, not on insults," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   At a Queens senior citizens residence, Clinton proposed a $3,000 tax credit
for families caring for sick or disabled relatives.
</P>
<P>
	   "Many of you know how difficult it is and exhausting to care for a loved one
who is physically or psychologically having difficulty," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   A tax credit, she argued, "will help support the diverse needs that people
have in long-term care." Clinton also said that government should provide more
services and information to such families.
</P>
<P>
	   The seniors cheered her pledges of support for Medicare, Social Security and
cheaper prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
	   "I am so elated that you are here," one woman gushed. "You have my vote."
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton was also cheered by party stalwarts at Bronx Democratic
headquarters, where she received a jacket that said "I'm a proud Bronx
Democrat." She told supporters she was proud to be running in New York, "the
place that beckons everyone, including immigrants from Washington, D.C., like
me."
</P>
</TEXT>
