<HEADLINE> Pinochet's Condition Said Improved  </HEADLINE>
   By EDUARDO GALLARDO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Gen. Augusto Pinochet has improved slightly since a
serious worsening of his health earlier this week, a spokeswoman said Saturday,
but he remains deeply depressed.
</P>
<P>
	   The 84-year-old former Chilean dictator, who has diabetes and suffered two
small strokes recently, is refusing to eat normally, said Monica Wehrhahn, a
spokeswoman for the Pinochet Foundation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``As we say, he gave up,'' she said. ``When family members call him he grabs
the phone, says hello, a couple of words, and that's all.''
</P>
<P>
	   Pinochet was arrested in October 1998 while recuperating from back surgery
in London on a warrant by a Spanish judge who wants to try him for alleged human
rights abuses during his 17-year dictatorship. He remains under police guard at
a rented mansion west of London.
</P>
<P>
	   But British Home Secretary Jack Straw said last month that he is inclined to
release Pinochet based on a medical report that said he was unfit to stand
trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier, foundation director Luis Cortes reported that Pinochet spends most
of the time in his room, refusing to come down to the first floor of the house
where he remains under police custody as his lawyers fight his extradition to
Spain.
</P>
<P>
	   The spokeswoman had reported Friday night that Pinochet suffered a ``serious
and worrisome'' crisis related to his diabetes two days earlier. ``He is doing a
little bit better today,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   A report by the civilian government that succeeded Pinochet says 3,197
people died or disappeared during the general's rule.
</P>
<P>
	   Belgium, which is also seeking Pinochet's extradition, opposed Straw's
decision and went to court demanding access to the medical report. Six human
rights groups, led by Amnesty International, filed a similar request.
</P>
<P>
	   Last Tuesday, the High Court in London accepted the right of Belgium and the
human rights organizations to argue for access to Pinochet's medical records. A
ruling is expected next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
