<DOCNO> APW20000212.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Siegel: Police misconduct is deeply ingrained  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Community leaders, civil rights activists and NYCLU
members from across the state converged on the city Saturday for a summit on
police brutality.
<P>
	   Opening the day-long meeting, the head of the New York Civil Liberties Union
called for a reversal in the "deeply ingrained" cop culture that he blamed for
many law enforcement ills.
</P>
<P>
	   "Police misconduct, excessive force, abuse of authority, discourtesy,
racial, ethnic and homophobic slurs have long been a serious problem with
enormous racial overtones in New York," Norman Siegel told several hundred
participants.
</P>
<P>
	   The Rev. Al Sharpton and ex-mayor David Dinkins echoed Siegel's call.
</P>
<P>
	   "We need not to deal with this incident by incident, but through broad
systemic change," Sharpton said. "... This is not an anti-police movement, but
an anti-police brutality movement."
</P>
<P>
	   In recent years, the issue of police brutality has dominated headlines with
the 1997 assault of Abner Louima and the fatal shooting in 1999 of Amadou
Diallo. The officer who assaulted Louima pleaded guilty to violating his civil
rights, and the four officers involved in Diallo's death are currently on trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Former Mayor David Dinkins said that it was the government's responsibility
- not only to its citizens- but to police as well, to establish a more effective
commission to investigate police brutality.
</P>
<P>
	   "What about the morale of thousands of good cops who take their
responsibilities to heart.... What message is being sent to them by the refusal
to weed out those who undermine the confidence of those they serve?" Dinkins
asked.
</P>
<P>
	   Siegel, a frequent critic of the police department, called for the creation
of civilian review boards to oversee the police; more ethnic diversity in the
police departments; better police training; more community involvement with
police; and an end to the "blue wall of silence."
</P>
<P>
	   He cited statistics on the racial makeup of several police departments.
Upstate, in Troy, where the population is about 8 percent black, there is only
one black officer - and he's currently in training. In Westchester County's
Mount Vernon, the population is 55 percent black, but the police department is
75 percent white, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Dinkins was particularly critical of the current Civilian Complaint Review
Board procedure and had harsh words for the Giuliani administration.
</P>
<P>
	   "Police conduct is not consistently condemned ... Such messages say to
officers whose inclination might be to misbehave, 'You can take liberties, you
can overstep the line, you are above the law,"' Dinkins said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We need to expose the myths about police misconduct and develop a
comprehensive program to ameliorate the problem," Siegel said, speaking at the
CUNY Center for Worker Education in lower Manhattan. "Short of that, explosive
headlines will continue to appear and more lives will be ruined."
</P>
<P>
	   The myths about brutality included assertions that such cases were often
"isolated incidents" and that they were not race-related, Siegel said.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is no more pertinent and volatile issue that we have to deal with
than police brutality," Sharpton said, adding that the issue should become part
of this year's national presidential debate.
</P>
<P>
	   Citing the legacy of Martin Luther King Jr., Sharpton called on those in
attendance to band together in peaceful group action. Sharpton reminded the
audience that "there has never been a perfect time for a movement. A movement
creates its own time."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-12-00 1554 </TRAILER>
