<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plane Crashes Take Toll on Rescuers  </HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTINE HANLEY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PORT HUENEME, Calif. (AP) -- In an instant, Rachel Fowler can recall the
horrifying details: the floating teddy bears, children's clothes and shoes. All
it takes to trigger the memories is the sight of a toy. Or another plane crash.
</P>
<P>
	   Just three months prior to the crash of Alaska Airlines Flight 261, Fowler
was among the first to view wreckage of a doomed EgyptAir jetliner, which
slammed into the Atlantic, killing all 217 on board.
</P>
<P>
	   Fowler, a 20-year-old Coast Guard seaman, remembers the sleeplessness and,
in place of that, the nightmares.
</P>
<P>
	   Counseling and support from fellow crew members and family helped her
overcome some of the aftershock, but they haven't enabled her to entirely
forget.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I was on this boat when I first saw the news (about Alaska Airlines). I
picked up the phone and called a friend to see if they had seen it,'' Fowler
said from the USCGC Monomoy, based in Woods Hole, Mass. ``It's very upsetting.''
</P>
<P>
	   When Flight 261 crashed on Jan. 31, killing all 88 on board, the Coast Guard
crew at Channel Islands station joined a fraternity no one seeks out.
</P>
<P>
	   Uniforms aside, the search-and-rescuers are people with names, families, and
stories -- just like the victims they carry home from the seas after these
disasters.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the Channel Islands crew is Larry O'Donnell, an old-school sailor.
Mitzi Boughner can hold her own at sea -- and run circles around some of the
guys on the basketball court. Andy Jones is a well-respected, compassionate dad,
and Marshall Glickman, a high-spirited and polite young man, just got married.
</P>
<P>
	   All of them -- along with reinforcements -- went to work when Flight 261
took its plunge. Fighting off emotions and exhaustion, they piled every last
grim detail onto their decks, bouyed by hope for a miracle.
</P>
<P>
	   Now they, like everyone else, are settling back into routines.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was kind of like a bad movie, like a dream state you're in,'' said Matt
Vaughn, a matter-of-fact 23-year-old. ``It's really sad. But it's one of those
things, when it happens, you have to go through it.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Work began when a ranger on Anacapa Island reported seeing a plane fall from
the sky at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
	   The station's 44-foot motor lifeboat was dispatched at once, carrying four
men. A lighter 41-foot utility boat followed minutes later, with Vaughn and five
others aboard. Cruising in swells of 6 to 8 feet, they wondered whether there
had been a crash at all.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In my mind, I was thinking, if anything, it was a small plane crash out of
Oxnard,'' Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Back at the station, Chief Warrant Officer Randy Mitchell and Lt. Cmdr. J.J.
Jones were trying to hold down the fort. Both had gone home for the day before
the crash was reported. By the time they got back, the switchboard was lit up
and the media had arrived.
</P>
<P>
	   They weren't used to the attention. Until now, they had existed in obscurity
in a town centered around a Navy base. And most of the calls were routine:
occasional drownings, disabled boats, man overboards.
</P>
<P>
	   Mitchell knew how traumatic it had been as soon as the men got back.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I saw it in their eyes when they stepped off the boats,'' he said. ``They
had that empty stare. They were like zombies.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   As workers aboard the two Coast Guard boats plied waters thick with wreckage
and reeking of jet fuel, their hopes of finding survivors faded faster than the
setting sun.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We were focusing on finding people, rushing around trying to find
anyone,'' Glickman said. ``We all pretty much knew from the size of the debris,
that to find a survivor would be a godly thing.''
</P>
<P>
	   They picked up everything -- plane parts, luggage, seats, shoes and bathing
suits. Glickman's boat picked up a chart bag sealed with flight plans and a pair
of prayer books. Vaughn picked up an ice chest, engraved with ``M. Thompson,''
later making a connection when Morrie Thompson's photo appeared in his local
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   And then -- a baby.
</P>
<P>
	   The crew of Vaughn's boat spotted the child just adrift of its bow. The
infant was covered in a blanket after it was swept to the deck.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It hit home for a lot of people. Especially for the younger guys. It was
tough for them,'' Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
	   Lt. Mark Fedor, commander of the USCGC Monomoy at the EgyptAir crash,
witnessed much of the same.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I guess they were the things you could really emotionally connect to,'' he
said. ``People with kids, it reminded them of their own.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Members of the Coast Guard's Critical Incident Stress Management Team were
ready to greet the first crews. The unit, similar to those with police and fire
departments, was put into full swing in the 1996 crash of TWA Flight 800.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In this instance, they pulled hundreds of remains out of the water,'' said
Tiffani Collier, the team's coordinator. ``No matter how much training someone
has, no one is ready for doing this kind of work.''
</P>
<P>
	   Feelings of guilt or failure for not doing their job -- saving lives -- can
be magnified by the sheer size of the disaster. Eighty-eight people killed means
88 people who weren't rescued.
</P>
<P>
	   Flashbacks, nightmares or irritability are common, and can last months and
even longer. The best therapy is to talk things out.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We remind them that they are the best support system for each other,''
Collier said.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Vaughn and Glickman recalled how their work grew more stressful and hopeless
as that first night wore on.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We kept saying it would be nice to find at least one person alive -- at
least give us some hope,'' Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
	   They were relieved of duty about six hours after they started, soaking wet
and coated in grime.
</P>
<P>
	   To help rid the events from his head, Vaughn replayed them before falling
asleep. He dreamed of being on the plane and ``going through the steps'' the
passengers might have gone through before the crash.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I try thinking about it as much as I can right off the bat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   He was back at the crack of dawn, along with Glickman, resuming a slot in a
rotation that would last until the next morning, when they swept the shores of
Anacapa Island. Even then, they hoped.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We were let down in a way. But you try not to let it beat you up to
much,'' Vaughn said. ``You would hope that if something like that happened to
you, somebody would do for you what we did for these people.''
</P>
<P>
	   The very next day, the Channel Islands station got a call. A fisherman was
missing. They launched a helicopter and a boat, and went looking for someone to
rescue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
