<HEADLINE> Four Accused of Sierra Leone Plot  </HEADLINE>
   By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- West African peacekeepers said Saturday they
have arrested four former soldiers who plotted to kill Sierra Leone's ex-junta
leader to undermine the country's fragile peace accord.
</P>
<P>
	   The soldiers were arrested Thursday at the Freetown residence of ex-junta
leader Johnny Paul Koroma, said Lt. Col. Chris Olukolade, spokesman for the
Nigerian-led West African intervention force known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
	   Koroma uncovered the alleged plot among his followers and turned them in,
Olukolade said. Olukolade did not give details of the plot, but said the
suspects were cooperating with authorities.
</P>
<P>
	   The four men -- George Johnson, Fodaybah Marah, Ibrahim Kamara and Foday
Kamanda -- are all well-known bush commanders based in the Okra Hills, near
Freetown.
</P>
<P>
	   Koroma's ex-junta soldiers are nominally allied to the country's brutal
rebel movement, which killed tens of thousands of people and hacked off arms,
legs and lips of many others during a grisly eight-year war to unseat the
government.
</P>
<P>
	   A peace accord was signed in July. But now many rebels and ex-junta soldiers
accuse their leaders, Koroma and rebel chief Foday Sankoh, of abandoning them
after securing government posts in a coalition government under the deal.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, many rebels and ex-junta soldiers have refused to give up their guns,
as required by the deal. Cease-fire violations are commonplace, and U.N. human
rights experts have reported cases of rebels looting villages, burning houses,
raping women and mutilating civilians in former rebel-held towns. Some
disgruntled fighters openly admit to using their weapons to terrorize and rob
villagers, calling that their only means of survival after the unsatisfactory
peace deal.
</P>
<P>
	   Rebels have refused to allow ECOMOG troops and their counterparts in a U.N.
peacekeeping force to enter much of the rebel-held North and East. The U.N.
force began deploying last November and is eventually expected to number at
least 6,000 troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
