<HEADLINE> Bradley argues for converts at California Democratic Convention  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) - The room was stacked against him and polls gave
his opponent nearly a 4-1 lead in the state, but Bill Bradley argued
passionately for converts Saturday at the California Democratic convention,
offering a romantic vision of the party that hopes to hold the White House.
<P>
	   "We have in our best moments always been the party of big ideas and big
ideals," said Bradley. As for his opponent, Vice President Al Gore, "There is a
difference in boldness," Bradley said, going first in the presidential rivals'
back-to-back speeches.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore, the party favorite who filled the cavernous San Jose convention center
with activists hoisting "Gore 2000" placards, was speaking after a long lineup
of state officials - party chairman Art Torres, Sen. Dianne Feinstein, Sen.
Barbara Boxer, Gov. Gray Davis - who used their turns on the massive podium to
promote the vice president's ascension.
</P>
<P>
	   In this state, which elects on March 7, 367 of the 2,170 national convention
delegates needed to clinch the Democrratic nomination, Gore is backed by all but
a handful of elected officials. Davis has pledged the work of his "entire
operation" in Gore's service.
</P>
<P>
	   "Nominate Al Gore!" Boxer ordered Saturday's crowd of about 3,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley tried to make his own show of muscle, leading a march of some 500
supporters through downtown San Jose to the convention center. The party barred
entrance to most of them, allowing Bradley just 200 or so guest passes to the
convention.
</P>
<P>
	   Party officials cited space limitations, but the hall inside was nearly a
quarter empty.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley spoke of dreams, saying his goals are universal health care, the
elimination of child poverty, registration of all handguns, deeper racial
understanding, and "a qualified teacher in every classroom in every school."
</P>
<P>
	   "I believe to the bottom core of my being that the Democratic Party can be
the agent for that kind of dream, for that kind of accomplishment, as long as we
do one thing: we must not settle," Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   His speech, delivered with barely a glance at his notes, left Jane Marcus
shaking and in tears. "He tells me the truth and I believe him," said Marcus, a
Stanford University administrator.
</P>
<P>
	   She watched as, during Bradley's remarks, Gore aides distributed a press
release labeling Bradley a "special agent" of the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was appalled," said Marcus, who said Gore allies want to make Bradley
supporters feel like disloyal Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's dirty tricks. As a Democrat, don't I have as much a right as any other
person in this room to say who I want to be president?"
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
