<HEADLINE> Annan Upbeat on Cambodia Mission  </HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW PENNINGTON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan said Saturday he
was optimistic a new U.N. mission to Cambodia could resolve differences with the
government over establishing a tribunal to try surviving leaders of the Khmer
Rouge.
</P>
<P>
	   Prime Minister Hun Sen was also upbeat. ``The two sides agree that the door
is still open for discussions,'' he told reporters after a 30 minute meeting
with Annan on the sidelines of a major U.N. trade conference in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
	   The United Nations has been at loggerheads with Cambodia for months over
international participation in a tribunal to judge Khmer Rouge chieftains, under
whose communist rule in the late 1970s an estimated 1.7 million Cambodians died
from starvation, disease and execution.
</P>
<P>
	   U.N. blessing is crucial to Hun Sen for the tribunal to be viewed by the
world community as legitimate. There are concerns that Cambodia's corrupt and
politicized judiciary would be open to manipulation by the dominant premier, who
has cut deals with Khmer Rouge to end two decades of civil war.
</P>
<P>
	   Annan hoped that a U.N. legal team going soon to Phnom Penh would be able to
resolve ``all outstanding issues,'' including the participation of foreign
judges. ``Nothing is off the table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The mood was upbeat after a week during which both sides issued statements
digging their heels in.
</P>
<P>
	   Annan's spokesman said Friday that the secretary-general would be laying
down the ``bottom line'' of what was required to get U.N. backing in Saturday's
meeting, suggesting there was little more room for compromise.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Hun Sen accused the United Nations on Friday of treating Cambodia
no better than a dog guarding a prize catch. He asserted Cambodia should be able
to run the tribunal on its own terms after fighting the Khmer Rouge for decades
and arresting and jailing the suspects.
</P>
<P>
	   But after the meeting with Annan -- their second in five months -- Hun Sen
said they had overcome misunderstandings sown through the media and a recent
exchange of letters between the United Nations and Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
	   This week Annan sent a letter to the Cambodian government rejecting Hun
Sen's latest tribunal plan, which would give Cambodia a majority of judges on a
joint panel, although it would require the agreement of at least one foreign
judge for a ruling.
</P>
<P>
	   The Cambodian plan would also require indictments to be issued by
co-prosecutors, a formula critics say would give the Cambodian judiciary veto
power over prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.N. wants prosecutors to be able to issue indictments independently of
each other.
</P>
<P>
	   The lingering dispute over the tribunal is holding up attempts both to
arrest several Khmer Rouge leaders living freely in Cambodia, and to put on
trial the two held in custody. The leaders are accused of causing one in five
Cambodians to die during a reign of terror between 1975 and 1979.
</P>
<P>
	   The Khmer Rouge were ousted from power by a Vietnamese invasion, but waged
guerrilla war against successive governments until finally collapsing in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1634 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary tours NYC as an official candidate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton schmoozed and smiled her way
through New York City on Saturday, planning five campaign stops in all five
boroughs in an effort to rally support from minorities and elderly voters, whose
help she'll need in her run for U.S. Senate.
<P>
	   Clinton returned to the city after a whirlwind week upstate following the
official announcement of her bid last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   She met with black Democrats and senior citizens in Queens, and made
campaign stops at the Caridad Restaurant, a Hispanic eatery in Washington
Heights; and a Democratic rally in the Bronx. She was also expected to stop in
Brooklyn before attending a dinner in Staten Island Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
	   The well-chosen crowds loved her.
</P>
<P>
	   "We will be behind you, and we will be able to march you on to victory in
November," U.S. Rep. Gregory Meeks, D-N.Y., told a beaming Clinton before about
150 black Democrats at York College in Jamaica, Queens.
</P>
<P>
	   The crowd cheered and chanted "Hillary, Hillary, Hillary!" as Clinton vowed
to push for new jobs and affordable health care, teacher training and a tax
deduction for college tuition.
</P>
<P>
	   "She has nearly total support in the black community," said Jeff Diggs, a
Queens resident at the rally.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is no choice in the black community except her," Diggs said. "Not
only is Mr. (Rudolph) Giuliani so unpopular, but the issues that she espouses
are clearly those that appeal to the black community."
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton will need heavy turnout from neighborhoods like Jamaica - a working
class black enclave with a powerful Democratic organization - if she is to
defeat Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
	   Without mentioning the mayor by name, Clinton alluded to the criticism that
has flown between the two campaigns this week over issues like campaign
fundraising and posting the ten commandments in public school classrooms.
</P>
<P>
	   "I intend to run a campaign on issues and ideas, not on insults," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   At a Queens senior citizens residence, Clinton proposed a $3,000 tax credit
for families caring for sick or disabled relatives.
</P>
<P>
	   "Many of you know how difficult it is and exhausting to care for a loved one
who is physically or psychologically having difficulty," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   A tax credit, she argued, "will help support the diverse needs that people
have in long-term care." Clinton also said that government should provide more
services and information to such families.
</P>
<P>
	   The seniors cheered her pledges of support for Medicare, Social Security and
cheaper prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
	   "I am so elated that you are here," one woman gushed. "You have my vote."
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton was also cheered by party stalwarts at Bronx Democratic
headquarters, where she received a jacket that said "I'm a proud Bronx
Democrat." She told supporters she was proud to be running in New York, "the
place that beckons everyone, including immigrants from Washington, D.C., like
me."
</P>
<P>
	   At the Caridad Restaurant in the Washington Heights section of Manhattan,
Clinton was joined by fashion designer Oscar de la Renta, as well as by
Dominican and other Hispanic leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
