<HEADLINE> French Woman Test Pilot Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Jacqueline Auriol, France's first woman test pilot who set
several world aviation speed records in the 1950s and 1960s, has died, her
family said Saturday. She was 82.
</P>
<P>
	   Auriol, the daughter-in-law of former French President Vincent Auriol, set a
world speed record for women aviators in 1951. On three occasions she was
awarded the Harmon International Trophy by an American president in recognition
of aviation exploits.
</P>
<P>
	   President Jacques Chirac said in a statement Saturday that Auriol was ``a
great woman who for decades was the incarnation of courage and modernity for the
French people.''
</P>
<P>
	   Auriol was born in November 1917 in the western Vendee region. She is
survived by her two children. There were no immediate details of funeral
arrangements. The cause of her death was not known.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
