<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Deutch Aide Got Bank Job  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A CIA official who monitored the investigation into whether
former agency head John Deutch mishandled classified information later went to
work for a bank where Deutch was a director, The New York Times reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Deutch resigned as CIA director in December 1996 and was elected to the
board of Citibank. That same month, CIA officials found evidence he had placed
classified information on unsecure computers at his home, although they
reportedly didn't notify the Justice Department of potential wrongdoing for more
than a year.
</P>
<P>
	   The investigation monitor was Nora Slatkin, the CIA's executive director.
Deutch recommended her for a management job at Citibank even as she was still
monitoring the case, the Times reported, citing CIA records and interviews with
officials.
</P>
<P>
	   Although Slatkin notified the agency in June 1997 that she was considering a
job with Citibank and would withdraw from consideration of anything involving
the bank, within a month she reviewed an internal report of findings in the
Deutch investigation, the Times reported, citing a classified agency report.
</P>
<P>
	   Slatkin resigned from the CIA in September 1997 and joined Citibank as a
vice president the next month, the Times reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The CIA's inspector general has found that Slatkin's actions delayed ``a
prompt and thorough investigation'' of the Deutch case, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Times reported there was no evidence that Slatkin's hiring at Citibank
was a quid pro quo for actions she took in the Deutch investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Slatkin said she had excused herself from the investigation and only helped
keep information flowing.
</P>
<P>
	   The Times quoted an unidentified Citibank spokesman as saying Deutch
referred Slatkin to the bank as she was considering where to move after leaving
the agency.
</P>
<P>
	   CIA Director George J. Tenet would not comment on the Citibank matter. The
Justice Department decided last spring not to prosecute Deutch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1650 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
