<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serbia Govt. Rejects Public's Anger  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbia's government on Saturday rejected public
outrage over the vice premier's suggestion that independent media should be
``liquidated,'' claiming supporting protests by professional groups abroad only
proved his allegation that they colluded with foreign powers.
</P>
<P>
	   Information Minister Aleksandar Vucic stood behind Vice Premier Vojislav
Seselj's Thursday accusation that Serbia's leading independent media were
traitors working in the interest of the country's Western foes.
</P>
<P>
	   Seselj heads the far-right, ultranationalist Radical Party and Vucic is one
of its members.
</P>
<P>
	   Seselj accused independent journalists Thursday of being ``accomplices'' in
the recent assassination of Defense Minister Pavle Bulatovic and said they
should be ``liquidated.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bulatovic's death is still being investigated, but Seselj has accused the
U.S. and west European governments of masterminding the killing.
</P>
<P>
	   Virtually all opposition parties and independent media registered strong
protests after Seselj's statement. They also said they would take legal action
against him, even though the courts are controlled by the government.
</P>
<P>
	   The New York-based Human Rights Watch, the International Federation of
Journalists, the Paris-based Reporters Without Borders and other groups have all
denounced Seselj's statement.
</P>
<P>
	   On Saturday, Vucic claimed the reaction from his critics, and the support
given them by the international groups, only testified that he was right.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The reaction only proved that we from the Radical Party hit the nail on
the head,'' Vucic said in a statement broadcast by Serbia's state-run television
network in its main Saturday evening newscast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1706 </TRAILER>
