<DOCNO> APW20000212.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton campaigns in NYC; Giuliani calls for oil relief  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton promoted a tax credit for
families caring for sick or disabled relatives Saturday at campaign stops
directed toward minority and elderly voters.
<P>
	   Her likely opponent in the U.S. Senate race, Republican Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, meanwhile took a shot at Clinton's husband, saying the president was
"turning his back on the suffering of all New Yorkers" who are facing huge
increases in the cost of heating oil.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani called for the release of a portion of the country's oil reserve to
offset the price hikes.
</P>
<P>
	   "What I've learned is that the only way to reach the White House is to make
it a political issue," the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hillary Rodham Clinton's spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said when asked about
the comments: "I'm not going to respond to Mayor Giuliani."
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton met Saturday with black Democrats and senior citizens in Queens,
where she proposed a $3,000 tax credit for families caring for sick or disabled
relatives.
</P>
<P>
	   "Many of you know how difficult it is and exhausting to care for a loved one
who is physically or psychologically having difficulty," she told those gathered
at a senior citizens residence.
</P>
<P>
	   She also stopped at a Queens college and a Hispanic eatery in Manhattan,
spoke at a rally in the Bronx and planned to attend a dinner in Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is no choice in the black community except her," said Jeff Diggs, a
Queens resident who attended the rally at York College in Queens. "Not only is
Mr. Giuliani so unpopular, but the issues that she espouses are clearly those
that appeal to the black community."
</P>
<P>
	   In response to Giuliani's criticism about oil prices, White House deputy
press secretary Jim Kennedy said selling the Strategic Petroleum Reserve to
lower oil prices was not allowed by law.
</P>
<P>
	   "The president has taken strong measures to help struggling families pay
their energy bills," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., contradicted Kennedy, saying sale of the
reserve was legal in an emergency. The Clinton administration has not said the
current needs and oil prices meet that standard.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, which has the nation's highest home heating oil costs, the
price per gallon has shot up from 72 cents to $2.50 since the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani released a three-paragraph letter that he sent to the White House
urging the sale of a portion of the reserve to drive the prices down.
</P>
<P>
	   "We can use all the support we can get," said Schumer, who first called for
sales from the reserve in September.
</P>
<P>
	   The prices began soaring after the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries rolled back production by 4.3 million barrels a day last year.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal government earlier this week announced $130 million in
assistance to help the indigent cover their heating costs. But Energy Secretary
William Richardson said there were no plans to sell the reserve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-12-00 1721 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Serb Socialists Fight On  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- President Slobodan Milosevic's ruling Socialist
party is planning aggressive campaigns to win back control of Serbia's
opposition-governed municipalities, an independent Belgrade daily reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The ruling party and its ultranationalist and neocommunist allies want to
fend off increasingly popular democratic opposition parties and take back
localities they lost in 1996 elections, the newspaper Glas said. It quoted a
Socialist official whom it did not identify.
</P>
<P>
	   Four years ago, allied opposition parties won local elections in Serbia's
main urban areas. Milosevic tried to annul the results, but the move triggered
massive protests and he eventually acknowledged defeat.
</P>
<P>
	   Dates for new municipal elections have not yet been set. They could take
place as early as May, Glas quoted the official as saying.
</P>
<P>
	   Regardless, a substantial change of authority in Serbia depends on crucial
parliamentary elections, not due before 2001. Confident of defeating Milosevic,
the opposition has demanded early parliamentary balloting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1724 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani Criticizes President  </HEADLINE>
   By BETH GARDINER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
