<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Midwest Express Resumes Service  </HEADLINE>
    By JENNY PRICE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Midwest Express resumed its regular flight schedule
Saturday after averting a pilots strike over wages and retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
	   The agreement reached early Saturday is the first labor contract between the
company and the Air Line Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
	   "They had the tool, they had the weapon if they felt they needed to use it,"
said Hal Myers, a spokesman for the pilots union. "The company understood that
and they found the agreeable middle ground that would be beneficial for both of
the parties."
</P>
<P>
	   Pilots are expected to vote on the agreement within a week, Myers said. A
majority of the airline's 330 pilots must approve the contract.
</P>
<P>
	   Strike committee chairman Karl Petersen said the deal gives pilots higher
pay and retirement benefits "that will protect and enhance the careers of our
pilots." No other details were released.
</P>
<P>
	   The 16-year-old airline employs nearly 2,800 people, 80 percent of them in
Milwaukee. Midwest Express averages 130 daily flights to 31 cities.
</P>
<P>
	   "While the negotiation process is often long and tedious, both the company
and the pilot group rose to the occasion to come to an agreement that is fair to
all," said Timothy Hoeksema, chief executive officer of Midwest Express.
</P>
<P>
	   Airline officials canceled 15 flights scheduled for late Friday and early
Saturday in preparation for a potential strike. Service resumed by sunrise and
flights were running on schedule, airline spokeswoman Lisa Bailey said Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
