<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 51 Mexican Students To Be Tried  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A Mexico City judge ordered 51 students held for trial
without bail Saturday, after they led a bitter university strike that canceled
classes for more than nine months.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the 745 strikers arrested Feb. 6 have been released from jails and
juvenile detention centers ahead of Monday's reopening of the National
Autonomous University of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
	   The strike broke out April 20 over a plan to increase tuition to the
university, Latin America's largest.
</P>
<P>
	   Many members of the 260,000-student university community have called for
dropping the charges against the students, who were arrested after federal
police marched onto campus and broke up the strike.
</P>
<P>
	   However, university officials and police apparently wanted the hard-line
leftist leaders of the strike to remain in jail, at least until classes resumed,
to avoid possible demonstrations at Monday's reopening.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge ruled that 49 students accused of illegally occupying the
university's Mexico City campus be denied bail on the grounds they pose a danger
to society, though under the charges -- a lesser form of robbery -- they would
be eligible for bail. Defense attorneys have five days to appeal.
</P>
<P>
	   Top strike leaders Alejandro Echeverria and Albert Perched -- know by their
nicknames as ``El Moss'' and ``The Devil'' -- were ordered held until trial on
more serious charges of causing injuries and robbery. By law they are not
eligible for bail, the government news agency Notimex reported.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, 75 strikers under the age of 18 were released from a juvenile
detention center; only two, suspected of more serious crimes, were still being
held in that center.
</P>
<P>
	   University Rector Juan Ramon de la Fuente urged prosecutors to drop charges
against most of the strikers, according to written testimony submitted through
his lawyers at a hearing Saturday for students at a Mexico City prison.
</P>
<P>
	   The strike started as a protest of the university's plans to increase
tuition from a token few cents a year to the equivalent of $140. Administrators
backed off the fee increase, but strikers' demands grew to include sweeping
policy changes and a call for greater student control.
</P>
<P>
	   In a Saturday radio speech, President Ernesto Zedillo pledged to support the
nation's public universities with government funds, and said ``they can
administer themselves under the principles of freedom of instruction, research
and discussion of ideas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
