<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Bush, McCain Tied in S.C.  </HEADLINE>
   By WILL LESTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- John McCain and George W. Bush are locked in a dead heat
in the campaign to win the crucial South Carolina primary a week from now, says
a Newsweek poll released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Texas governor was supported by 43 percent and McCain, a senator from
Arizona, was supported by 40 percent in the poll conducted Wednesday through
Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The poll supported the McCain camp's belief that it will need a heavy
turnout of independents to win in the state. McCain got the backing of 55
percent of independents in the poll, while Bush was backed by 53 percent of
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   The campaign turned sharply negative in recent days, a development that
could depress voter turnout and hurt McCain. His campaign announced late in the
week it would pull negative ads and focus on a more positive message. Bush's
campaign planned to keep up the aggressive approach against McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush had an edge among conservatives, with almost half, while McCain had the
support of just over a third. McCain had an edge among moderate and liberal
likely voters in the GOP primary.
</P>
<P>
	   More than half said Bush would have the better chance of defeating the
Democratic Party's candidate, while 31 percent said that of McCain. Four out of
10 said McCain's experience as a Navy pilot and prisoner of war in Vietnam will
make them more likely to vote for him.
</P>
<P>
	   An analysis of the data by Princeton Survey Research Associates said
independents were as likely to vote as Republicans, and both were more likely to
vote in the primary as Democrats. Based on voting intentions in the poll at this
point, about six out of ten voters will be Republican, three out of 10
independents and one out of 10 would be Democratic. But the pollsters cautioned
that could shift with a week to go in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   The poll of 507 South Carolina residents who intend to vote in the
Republican primary has an error margin of plus or minus 5 percentage points,
larger for subgroups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1800 </TRAILER>
