<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Oil Refinery Secures $600M  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) -- The largest oil refinery in
the Western Hemisphere has received $600 million in financing to build a crude
oil processing plant and repay bank debts, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Construction at the Hovensa refinery in the U.S. Virgin Islands will begin
by June and should be completed by June 2002, Hovensa Vice President Alex
Moorhead said Friday. The plant will convert pitch, the least valuable portion
of crude oil, into higher-value products.
</P>
<P>
	   Bank of America is the lead underwriter to finance the new project and debt,
Moorhead said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hovensa was formed in October 1998 when Amerada Hess Corp. joined Petroleos
de Venezuela S.A. in a joint venture to operate Hess' St. Croix refinery. Its
refining capacity of 545,000 barrels a day is the hemisphere's largest.
</P>
<P>
	   With 2,000 workers, the refinery is also the Virgin Islands' biggest private
employer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1920 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Cubans Feel 'Elian Fatigue'  </HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GUTKIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HAVANA (AP) -- It's hard to find anyone on the streets of Havana who doesn't
think Elian Gonzalez should be returned to his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   But once they get past the party line, Cubans can be surprisingly frank
about what they think of the international custody battle over the 6-year-old
boy.
</P>
<P>
	   Some say they think Cuban President Fidel Castro is using the case for
political ends. Others say they're just plain sick of hearing about Elian.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's the same thing all the time. It gets tiring,'' said Carlos Ortiz, a
young man who asked to end the interview when he noticed a policeman staring at
him.
</P>
<P>
	   Although opinion polls don't exist here, there's no doubt that most Cubans
believe the little boy rescued at sea and now living with a great uncle in Miami
should be returned to his father.
</P>
<P>
	   Interviewed in bars and in restaurants, on street corners and in food
markets, Cubans said failure to return Elian would amount to breaking up a
family and keeping a father from the son he loves.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is not a political problem. It's a human problem,'' said 25-year-old
accountant Maryanis Romero.
</P>
<P>
	   But it's also clear that a certain amount of Elian fatigue has set in. The
island's communist government has turned the case into a major national crusade,
staging daily public rallies, bombarding the airwaves with news about the boy's
``kidnapping,'' and plastering the walls of major cities with ``Save Elian''
posters.
</P>
<P>
	   Almost every evening, Castro himself joins Elian's father and grandparents
in elaborate demonstrations for the boy's return accompanied by choir and dance
performances and speeches extolling Cuba's communist revolution.
</P>
<P>
	   Elian was found clinging to an inner tube in the Atlantic on Nov. 25 after
the boat he was riding in sank. His mother and 10 other people on the boat died
in an attempt to reach U.S. shores.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. relatives taking of Elian believe the boy should not be returned,
saying his mother died trying to bring him to freedom. Cuba says keeping him in
the United States is a violation of international law.
</P>
<P>
	   One woman, Carmen Vasquez, said she thinks Castro is capitalizing on the
Elian case to stir up revolutionary fervor and divert attention away from the
country's economic ills.
</P>
<P>
	   A man, Jorge Vasquez, recalled with amusement a rumor now making its way
through Havana that a television announcer was fired after forgetting to turn
off his microphone and saying on the air that he was sick of reading news about
Elian.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He was just saying what a lot of us think,'' Jorge said. State-run
television employees said the incident never occurred.
</P>
<P>
	   Another man, Eugenio Izquierdo, said he believed Elian's father and
grandparents, now celebrities in Cuba, were receiving economic favors from the
government, and that those privileges could end once Elian is returned.
</P>
<P>
	   Alexander Rodriguez, 24, said he doesn't understand why Elian's father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, hasn't traveled to Miami to pick up his son personally.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I would go to the bowels of the earth to get my son,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Rodriguez'sfriend, Keyner Piedra, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If they kidnapped his son, they could kidnap him, too,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
	   At that, Izquierdo said the government was wrong to call Elian's situation a
``kidnapping.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``The boy was not kidnapped. He was rescued,'' he said, adding that he knows
what it's like to cross the Florida Straits in a makeshift boat because he tried
and failed to do it himself in 1979.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite such skepticism, many Cubans say they are deeply moved by Elian's
story, and consider the fact that he remains in the United States to be an
affront to their national pride.
</P>
<P>
	   They attend rallies, sometimes by the hundreds of thousands, to press for
his return. At one demonstration last week inside the walls of a Havana
fortress, hundreds of young people clamored for a chance to touch the hands of
Elian's maternal grandmother.
</P>
<P>
	   At one point, they chanted: ``Fidel, for sure, hit the Yankees hard!''
</P>
<P>
	   Yet for most, it seems, the case is more about love than politics.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We Cubans by idiosyncrasy are extremely tied to our families,'' said
Manuel Baltar, a 46-year-old man employed as a driver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
