<HEADLINE> Hijacked Plane Crew Explains Escape  </HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT BARR Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- The crew of a hijacked Afghan airliner decided to escape
after despairing of persuading their captors to surrender, a flight captain said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The four members of the flight crew, who say they all want to return to
Afghanistan, talked with reporters Saturday, two days after the hijackers
surrendered at Stansted airport, north of London.
</P>
<P>
	   The hijackers took over the Ariana jet last Sunday during what should have
been a short domestic flight from the Afghan capital of Kabul to the northern
town of Mazar-e-Sharif. By the time the crew scrambled out a cockpit window
Tuesday night, it had spent nearly two full days with the hijackers and had been
unable to persuade them to give up, said Nabi, the second captain on the flight.
Like many Afghans, he uses only one name.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Finally, we saw we could not do anything. We thought if we escaped, the
hijackers would be stranded and probably would not dare to harm any
passengers,'' Nabi said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the worst moment for the crew came Monday morning at daybreak, when
the hijackers first saw that the aircraft was surrounded by armed security
personnel.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They became very hysterical and very nervous,'' and threatened to kill
some of the passengers, Nabi said. He did not say how calm was restored.
</P>
<P>
	   Police have said the hijackers also became extremely agitated after
discovering the crew had escaped. One flight attendant bore the brunt of their
wrath and was shoved down the back stairs of the Boeing 727.
</P>
<P>
	   Said Mehdi Saidi, the first captain, said the crew did not attempt to resist
the hijackers when they first took over the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The hijackers entered the aircraft cockpit and rushed inside with pistols
and very bad faces,'' he said. ``The crew told them: 'Don't do anything please.
What is your command? We will follow your command.'''
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the passengers from the flight were preparing to move to an
immigration center in western England on Saturday, the government said. Some 74
of them have applied for asylum in England, and police are questioning 22 others
who are suspected of involvement in the hijacking.
</P>
<P>
	   Britain's Foreign Office said late Friday that Britain has been holding
talks with countries near Afghanistan about ``various aspects'' of the
hijacking, but did not elaborate. A spokeswoman denied a report in the Sunday
Telegraph that Pakistan had been approached specifically because of its Afghan
community, with a view to sending all the freed hostages there.
</P>
<P>
	   The newspaper said Prime Minister Tony Blair's office did not want to
endanger the freed hostages by sending them back to Afghanistan, but wanted to
send out a message that Britain is not a ``soft touch'' for asylum seekers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 1927 </TRAILER>
