<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florida Judge OKs Lethal Injection  </HEADLINE>
   By MIKE SCHNEIDER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- A judge on Saturday gave state corrections officials
the go-ahead to carry out Florida's first lethal injection since the state
changed its primary execution method from the electric chair.
</P>
<P>
	   Circuit Judge O.H. Eaton Jr. rejected arguments that the method was
unconstitutional and that corrections officials were ill prepared.
</P>
<P>
	   Death row inmate Terry Sims had challenged the constitutionality of the
state's new lethal injection law, passed last month. His execution is scheduled
for Feb. 23 for the death for the 1977 murder of a retired New York City Police
officer during a pharmacy robbery.
</P>
<P>
	   Sims' attorney, Steven Malone, had argued during a two-day hearing last week
that the chances of a botched execution using lethal injection were significant
and could cause Sims pain and suffering in violation of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A foul-up on this can be a horrifying and excruciatingly painful death,''
Malone said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Sims has an appeal before the Florida Supreme Court and arguments are
scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   During the hearing, Florida State Prison Warden James Crosby couldn't answer
questions about what chemicals or dosages would be used during the lethal
injection. Malone said that and the lack of detailed instructions in writing
showed that state corrections officials weren't prepared to carry out lethal
injections.
</P>
<P>
	   Malone also argued that Sims didn't have enough information from the
Department of Corrections to choose a method of execution. The new law gives
death row inmates the option of choosing the electric chair, but corrections
officials will opt for lethal injection if inmates refuse to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge disagreed with the argument, saying all Sims needed was a general
knowledge of the execution methods, which corrections officials had provided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
