<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Music Pioneer George Jackson Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- George Jackson, a former president of Motown Records who
produced the movies of some of Hollywood's leading black actors, has died. He
was 42.
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson died in New York on Thursday after suffering a stroke, the Los
Angeles Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   He co-produced the films ``A Thin Line Between Love and Hate'' starring
Martin Lawrence, ``New Jack City'' with Wesley Snipes and ``Krush Groove''
starring Blair Underwood. Other films included ``Jason's Lyric'' and the second
and third installments of the ``House Party'' series featuring the hip-hop duo
Kid N' Play.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In a business that is very self-centered and is very tough to stay in,
George helped everyone, whether he was in competition with them or not,'' said
Doug McHenry, who co-founded Elephant Walk Entertainment with Jackson.
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson also co-produced UPN's ``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie'' comedy under the Elephant
Walk banner.
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson's most recent effort was creating Urban Box Office Network,
described as a media company for the ``urban mindset.'' UBO will establish a
media lab in Harlem to honor Jackson, McHenry said.
</P>
<P>
	   A Harvard University graduate, Jackson became president and chief executive
of Motown in 1997. He oversaw several acts, including the group 98 Degrees and
the Temptations.
</P>
<P>
	   McHenry and Jackson considered the films they made to be ``edutainment'' --
movies that both educated and entertained. Jackson described his philosophy in
1991, saying: ``What we try to do is connect all of the many aspects of our
community into our stories.''
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson is survived by his wife, Yuko; daughter, Kona Rose; mother, Henie
Hogan Jackson Stancil; sister, Dr. Sharon Jackson; and brother, Bobbie Stancil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 2009 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Revs Up Campaign in S.C.  </HEADLINE>
   By LEIGH STROPE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DARLINGTON, S.C. (AP) -- John McCain hit 100 mph in a spin around
Darlington's famed speedway Saturday and George W. Bush told people in Columbia
he's ``a tough competitor'' and hinted he's found a policy mistake by the McCain
campaign to use against him in next week's debate.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain kept his campaign in high gear with several town meetings and other
stops the rest of the weekend. Bush made a couple of campaign stops in the
state, before heading back to Austin to spend some time with family, returning
to the campaign trail on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   As Bush was telling an audience at a Columbia restaurant that ``my faith
allowed me to handle a short-term adversity,'' McCain was hopping behind the
wheel of a blue Pontiac Grand Prix NASCAR's Darlington Raceway for a few turns
around the track Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The most important news of the day is I went over 100 miles an hour,''
McCain said. ``I hope I do a better job driving this car than I did on my last
mission.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was a Vietnam POW after his plane was shot down over Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
	   The candidate jumped in the car wearing a suit and tie -- but not a helmet
-- and had his wife Cindy in the passenger seat. He gave a thumbs-up to track
officials and reporters before flooring the gas pedal, kicking up dust in his
wake. He took two laps around the track, stopping once for photographers, and
then emerged from the car with a huge grin.
</P>
<P>
	   The Darlington track has a rich tradition in South Carolina politics. Bob
Dole in 1995 explored the early stages of his presidential bid here and other
candidates have made the mandatory campaign stop at Darlington. The track is in
the heart of tobacco country, where McCain's sponsorship of failed legislation
to raise taxes on tobacco has been a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier the Arizona senator walked through a neighborhood in nearby
Florence, knocking on doors and asking for votes. He surprised Steve Coker, who
answered his door with his children peering from behind him, hiding from the
television cameras.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He'll let all his work show,'' Coker said of McCain. ``We know all about
the Keating Five, we know he's divorced, we're not guessing about his drug
use.''
</P>
<P>
	   Both campaigns on Saturday were still preoccupied with campaign tactics,
trading attacks on everything from push polling to rude telephone calls to
fund-raising. Bush told reporters Saturday that his campaign has hearing from
supporters that they're getting calls from someone claiming to be with the Bush
campaign, who starts ``trashmouthing'' the person answering the phone.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I warn the people of South Carolina, Republicans, if you get a phone call
from some voice purporting to be me that is rude, just ignore it,'' Bush said.
``I can assure you our people are not calling to make it hard for me to win the
election.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush did not blame the calls on McCain. Earlier in the week, McCain demanded
that the Bush campaign stop calling voters and misleading them about his record
after a woman complained her 14-year-old son received such a call. The woman
didn't know if the Bush campaign had made the call.
</P>
<P>
	   State Sen. Mike Fair of Greenville told Bush at Seawell's Restaurant in
Columbia that the Bush campaign ``hasn't even hit (McCain's) soft spots.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm going to,'' Bush said in a conversation picked up by boom mikes
overhead. ``But I'm not going to do it on TV.''
</P>
<P>
	   Campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer said Bush was referring to ``a major policy
blunder McCain made this week'' and hinting that he would bring it in Tuesday
night's debate.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush South Carolina spokesman Tucker Eskew said Bush was not referring to
any change in television advertising strategy.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Senator McCain had hoped his olive branch would be taken up by Governor
Bush, but it appears by Governor Bush's own comments he intends to continue his
push polling and other negative tactics,'' said McCain spokesman Howard Opinsky,
who said he didn't know what policy area the Bush people were referring to.
``That's too bad. The people of South Carolina deserve better.''
</P>
<P>
	   A Newsweek poll out Saturday showed the race was a dead heat, with Bush
doing better among Republicans and McCain better among independents.
</P>
<P>
	   In New Hampshire, McCain rode his strong support from both groups to an
18-point victory. Bush said Saturday that his faith sustained him after his loss
there. But he told the crowd of about 100 at Seawell's Restaurant that he's wary
of people in public office who say: ``Vote for me, I'm more religious than my
neighbor.'''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Faith, to me, is strength. It puts life in perspective. I recognize that
I'm a humble sinner and I've sought redemption, and I recognize that I'm no
better than anybody else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   After his visit to the capital city of Columbia, Bush traveled to Orangeburg
for a speech and question-and-answer session before a crowd of more than a
thousand. Then he flew back to Texas to spend Sunday with his family. Bush
planned to spend the rest of the week in South Carolina after his return on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bush campaign was also looking ahead to future primaries. In California,
Bush is launching his ad campaign with the positive ``reformer with results''
spot, a seven-figure buy running for the next couple weeks in large media
markets such as Los Angeles and in heavily Republican areas, including
Bakersfield and San Diego. The McCain campaign has said it will spend less than
the $12.5 million allowed by state law and expects to be outspent 2-to-1 by
Bush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
