<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	    William Andres
</P>
<P>
	   FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Former Dayton Hudson executive William Andres, who
helped the retailer triple in size during the seven years he ran the company,
died Wednesday after suffering from lymphoma. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
	   From 1976 to 1983, when he was Andres was chief executive officer, Dayton
Hudson grew from 400 stores to more than 1,000 and from $1.9 billion in revenues
to more than $5.6 billion. He was chairman of the board until his retirement in
1985.
</P>
<P>
	   During his tenure, the company bought Mervyn's, a California-based
department store. The company also diversified under his leadership, expanding
such subsidiaries as Target and B. Dalton Bookseller.
</P>
<P>
	   Andres became an executive in 1968 and later was the company's first chief
executive office outside the Dayton family.
Jacqueline Auriol
</P>
<P>
	   PARIS (AP) -- Jacqueline Auriol, France's first female test pilot who set
several world aviation speed records in the 1950s and 1960s, has died, her
family said Saturday. She was 82.
</P>
<P>
	   Auriol, the daughter-in-law of former French President Vincent Auriol, set a
world speed record for female aviators in 1951. On three occasions she was
awarded the Harmon International Trophy by an American president in recognition
of aviation exploits.
Jay Hawkins
</P>
<P>
	   PARIS (AP) -- Screamin' Jay Hawkins, the larger-than-life American blues
singer and pianist who shocked the music world at the dawn of rock with his
crazed shrieking and bizarre stage antics, died Saturday. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
	   Hawkins, from Cleveland, was best known for his song ``I Put a Spell On
You,'' which he recorded on the Okeh label in 1956 and which helped win him cult
status in the United States, Europe and Japan. He planned the tune as a ballad,
but after a night of heavy drinking he took another crack -- screaming, yelling
and groaning -- and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
	   Some of his groans had to be edited out so that ``I Put a Spell On You''
could be played on the radio. Hawkins once said the song, written to woo back a
girlfriend, was at first banned by some radio stations because it supposedly
sounded cannibalistic.
</P>
<P>
	   Hawkins went on to use the same demented style again and again. An
outrageous performer, he used bizarre stage props, often emerging out of coffins
during shows. He would wield rubber snakes and fake tarantulas and wear a boar's
tooth around his neck or a bone clipped to his nose.
George Jackson
</P>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- George Jackson, a former president of Motown Records who
produced the movies of some of Hollywood's leading black actors, has died. He
was 42.
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson died in New York on Thursday after suffering a stroke, the Los
Angeles Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   He co-produced the films ``A Thin Line Between Love and Hate'' starring
Martin Lawrence, ``New Jack City'' with Wesley Snipes and ``Krush Groove''
starring Blair Underwood. Other films included ``Jason's Lyric'' and the second
and third installments of the ``House Party'' series featuring the hip-hop duo
Kid N' Play.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In a business that is very self-centered and is very tough to stay in,
George helped everyone, whether he was in competition with them or not,'' said
Doug McHenry, who co-founded Elephant Walk Entertainment with Jackson.
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson also co-produced UPN's ``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie'' comedy under the Elephant
Walk banner.
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson's most recent effort was creating Urban Box Office Network,
described as a media company for the ``urban mindset.'' UBO will establish a
media lab in Harlem to honor Jackson, McHenry said.
</P>
<P>
	   A Harvard University graduate, Jackson became president and chief executive
of Motown in 1997. He oversaw several acts, including the group 98 Degrees and
the Temptations.
Vicki Moore
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Vicki Moore, a campaigner against cruelty to animals in
Europe, died Feb. 6 of cancer. She was 44.
</P>
<P>
	   Moore came to public attention as an animal-rights campaigner in 1987 when
she purchased a donkey from a Spanish village where it would have been ridden
through the streets until it collapsed. The donkey was taken to an English
sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
	   Moore and her husband established their own group, Fight Against Animal
Cruelty in Europe, and campaigned widely.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1995, Moore was badly gored while videotaping a bull-running ceremony in
Spain in which the animal runs around a plaza with flaming gobs of tar on its
horns.
Guy Waterman
</P>
<P>
	   FRANCONIA, N.H. (AP) -- Guy Waterman, a hiker and author best known for
chronicling the history of New Hampshire's White Mountains, has died. He was 67.
</P>
<P>
	   Waterman's friends retrieved his body from near the summit of Mount
Lafayette on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   His wife and writing partner, Laura Waterman, said he had climbed to an area
near the 5,260-foot summit last week to take his life, something they had
discussed for many years.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He could feel his loss of strength,'' she told The Valley News of Lebanon.
``I think he wanted to go while he was still strong, while he could still climb
the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
	   Fish and Game officials said Waterman left his East Corinth, Vt., home Feb.
6, leaving behind notes to his family.
</P>
<P>
	   Waterman's books include ``Wilderness Ethics'' and ``Backwoods Ethics.'' He
is considered one of the first writers to address the need to be responsible
while hiking, said Mike Dickerman, a friend of Waterman.
</P>
<P>
	   Dickerman said Waterman had some ``personal demons,'' and had lost two sons
in mountaineering accidents.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He contributed an awful lot to the White Mountains community,'' said Peter
Crane of the Mount Washington Observatory. ``His writings provided a sense of
history and real thoughtfulness and consideration of our role in the woods and
mountains.''
</P>
<P>
	   Waterman and his wife moved to Vermont in 1973. Before then, he had worked
as a jazz pianist in Washington and a speech writer for three presidents.
Lenore Wingard
</P>
<P>
	   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Lenore Kight Wingard, an Olympic swimmer who competed in
front of Adolf Hitler in the 1936 Berlin Games, died Wednesday. She was 88.
</P>
<P>
	   Wingard, once dubbed ``one of the fastest mermaids in the world,'' set world
and U.S. records in freestyle events. She won a gold and a silver medal in the
1932 Olympics in Los Angeles and a bronze in 1936.
</P>
<P>
	   During a 1991 interview, she recalled the tight security in Berlin. At one
point, she needed two hours to get back to her dormitory, forced to take the
subway because soldiers wouldn't let her cross the street.
</P>
<P>
	   In one of her best-known races, she lost the 400-meter freestyle by
one-tenth of a second in the 1932 Olympics. She matched world champion swimmer
Helene Madison stroke for stroke until Madison won with a world-record time of
5:28.5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
