<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Mourn Airline Employees  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- About 3,500 people connected to Alaska Airlines and its
sister company Horizon Airline gathered at a corporate memorial service Saturday
to remember co-workers who died when Flight 261 crashed in the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We gather to celebrate all five brave crew members, heroes all and
consummate heroes who did everything in their power -- everything -- to save
their stricken aircraft and care for their passengers,'' said John Kelly,
chairman and chief executive officer of Alaska Air Group, the parent company of
both airlines.
</P>
<P>
	   All 88 people aboard the Alaska Airlines MD-83 jetliner died when it plunged
into the ocean Jan. 31 off the southern California coast.
</P>
<P>
	   During Saturday's service at the Washington State Trade and Convention
Center, two employees lit candles for each of the five crew members and seven
other vacationing employees who died. Also among the victims were 32 family
members and friends of airline employees.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This loss has brought us all together in a way we could not have
imagined,'' said Captain Mike Swanigan, an Alaska Airlines pilot.
</P>
<P>
	   The corporate memorial service followed a series of private and public
services to remember the victims of the crash.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane was on its way from Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, to Seattle via San
Francisco when it went down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
