<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Council Rules Against Wash. Paper  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) -- A new privately funded council created to help handle
complaints against media outlets acted on its first formal complaint Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Washington News Council voted 9-6 to endorse an unsuccessful city
council candidate's contention that a newspaper editorial in The Olympian
unfairly attacked his character and damaged his reputation last fall.
</P>
<P>
	   The council's conclusion carries no legal weight. The only penalty is
publicity about the decision.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm just happy the organization exists,'' Bernie Friedman said after the
council sided with him. ``People now have a place to go when The Olympian or
other media defame people.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Olympian declined to participate in the council's process.
</P>
<P>
	   Executive Editor Vickie Kilgore wrote in an opinion-page column published
Saturday: ``This is a page of opinion, including ours. They are often bold,
sometimes unpopular. But we are exercising our right to express them, and we
cannot let ourselves be intimidated in that.''
</P>
<P>
	   The council has received only one formal complaint, which requires a waiver
of the right to sue. Friedman, a lawyer, said pursuing a defamation lawsuit was
a risk not worth the expense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 2202 </TRAILER>
