<HEADLINE> No. 6 Mich. St. 61, Wisconsin 44  </HEADLINE>
    By GREG BEACHAM AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Morris Peterson had 18 points and 10 rebounds as No. 6
Michigan State kept a share of the Big Ten lead with a 61-44 victory over
Wisconsin on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
	   The Spartans (18-6, 8-2 Big Ten) never trailed and never were really
threatened by the Badgers, who lost for the third time in four games.
</P>
<P>
	   Michigan State recovered from its 70-67 loss at Purdue on Tuesday night and
exacted revenge for its 66-51 loss at Wisconsin last season, the Spartans' only
conference defeat in the 1998-99 campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Michigan State's win and Ohio State's 88-75 victory over Penn State set up a
showdown for the Big Ten lead Tuesday night when the No. 5 Buckeyes visit the
Spartans in East Lansing. Each team has two conference losses.
</P>
<P>
	   Against the undersized Badgers (12-11, 4-7), Michigan State built a 35-20
lead with a 13-2 run in the closing minutes of the first half. Peterson, who had
just five points in the Spartans' loss at Purdue, had 13 first-half points and
scored five straight shortly after halftime.
</P>
<P>
	   Jerry Richardson dunked an alley-oop pass from Mateen Cleaves that gave
Michigan State a 45-28 lead with 12 minutes to play. The lead stretched to 23
points moments later as the Spartans cruised to the victory.
</P>
<P>
	   Michigan State outrebounded Wisconsin 51-24 and outran the Badgers, who have
lost three of their last five home games while sinking into a tie for eighth in
the conference.
</P>
<P>
	   A.J. Granger had 11 points and 11 rebounds for Michigan State, which won
even though Cleaves struggled in a 2-of-10 shooting performance.
</P>
<P>
	   Mark Vershaw, Wisconsin's leading scorer, went 1-for-10 from the field.
Maurice Linton had 10 points to lead Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
	   The Badgers could have used some help from Ron Dayne, who got a standing
ovation when he and his Heisman Trophy made a halftime appearance at center
court.
</P>
<P>
	   A physical game occasionally brought bad feelings between the teams to the
surface. Cleaves and Vershaw had to be separated after an argument with three
minutes to play, and at least two minor skirmishes erupted in the stands.
</P>
<P>
	   The Wisconsin student section's chants of "Alcoholic" -- a reference to
Cleaves' troubles with the law over allegedly stealing a bottle of beer in April
-- were nearly drowned out by chants of "All-American" from the sizable Michigan
State cheering section in the upper deck of the Kohl Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
