<HEADLINE> Canadian Benefits Bill Criticized  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRANDE PRAIRIE, Alberta (AP) -- Reform Leader Preston Manning called the
federal government's proposed legislation giving same-sex couples the same
benefits as heterosexual couples a Liberal smokescreen.
</P>
<P>
	   Manning said that while he supports the traditional definition of marriage
as the basis for family life and the provision of government benefits, there may
be exceptions.
</P>
<P>
	   ''(But) these relationships should not be based on sexual preference, they
should be based on a relationship of dependency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal Justice Minister Anne McLellan introduced a bill Friday that would
extend legal benefits to gay and lesbian couples, such as being able to collect
survivor benefits under the Canada Pension Plan.
</P>
<P>
	   While the proposal avoided the issue of equating same-sex marriages with
heterosexual marriages, gay and lesbian advocates praised the proposal for
aiming to give same-sex couples recognition under the law.
</P>
<P>
	   Manning said his party will debate the same-sex bill but ``we have no
intention of letting up on that Human Resources Development scandal at all.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a diversion by the federal Liberals to try to take attention off this
scandal in Human Resources Development,'' Manning said after a meeting Saturday
in northern Alberta to promote the fledgling Canadian Alliance party.
</P>
<P>
	   For weeks, Manning and his caucus have blasted Liberal Human Resources
Minister Jane Stewart over millions of dollars in job creation grants.
</P>
<P>
	   An audit made public last month uncovered serious problems among grants in
seven programs, including job creation, literacy training and help for the
disabled and aboriginals. There were missing or incomplete documents and
insufficient monitoring.
</P>
<P>
	   Reform is calling for Stewart's resignation and a full accounting of where
the money has gone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
