<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harvey Gets NAACP Best Actor Award  </HEADLINE>
    By CADONNA M. PEYTON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- Steve Harvey took best actor in a television comedy
series Saturday during the 31st NAACP Image Awards, saying the honor meant much
more to him than others because of the organization presenting the award.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is from us, for us, that's why it means something to me," said Harvey
of "The Steve Harvey Show," in which he plays the vice principal of an urban
high school. The series appears on the Warner Bros. WB television network.
</P>
<P>
	   Best actresses in a comedy series went to twins Tia and Tamera Mowry for
their roles in "Sister, Sister," also on the WB network.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
announced that a shortage of minority characters in television made it difficult
for Image Award organizers to select nominees in the TV categories this year.
</P>
<P>
	   The NAACP has confronted the networks for months about the lack of minority
characters.
</P>
<P>
	   The issue of minorities in the entertainment industry came to a boil in July
when NAACP and a coalition of Hispanic groups condemned a near-total lack of
minority characters in fall series. The groups threatened lawsuits and boycotts.
</P>
<P>
	   But within the past months, NAACP officials met with TV network executives
who promised to work toward enhancing diversity on their shows.
</P>
<P>
	   In the television categories, CBS had 18 nominations. ABC was next with 15,
followed by HBO with 14, Warner Bros. with 12 and NBC with 10.
</P>
<P>
	   Although CBS had the most nominations, critics say both CBS and Fox are not
putting enough minorities to work in television. Both networks recently
announced that they will have more minority characters this fall.
</P>
<P>
	   Agreements by Fox and CBS are similar to those signed by NBC and ABC last
month, focusing on changes in minority representation through the companies --
both on-screen and off.
</P>
<P>
	   The 31st NAACP Image Awards, which honors minorities in film, television,
music and literature, took place Friday and Saturday at the Pasadena Civic
Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, CBS won for outstanding drama series for "Touched by an Angel,"
co-starring Della Reese. Fox took the outstanding variety series or special for
"1999 Essence Awards." Civil rights heroine, Rosa Parks, won for supporting
acress in a drama series for her appearance on "Touched by an Angel."
</P>
<P>
	   Angela Bassett won outstanding supporting actress in the motion picture,
"Music of the Heart." Halle Berry won outstanding actress in a television movie,
mini-series or dramatic special for the lead role in "Introducing Dorothy
Dandridge," an HBO movie about the first black woman nominated for an Academy
Award as best actress. Berry also won a Golden Globe for her role.
</P>
<P>
	   The Image Awards show is scheduled to air April 6 on Fox.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-12-00 2318 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000212.0247 </DOCNO>
