<DOCNO> APW20000212.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No. 4 La. Tech 93, W. Kentucky 72  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    RUSTON, La. (AP) -- Louisiana Tech's game plan -- strike quickly on offense
and handcuff Western Kentucky star ShaRae Mansfield -- worked to perfection.
</P>
<P>
	   Tamicha Jackson made five 3-pointers and scored 23 points Saturday night as
No. 2 Louisiana Tech built a 31-point halftime lead on the way to a 93-72 Sun
Belt Conference victory over Western Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
	   "That first half we really played great basketball, we kept Mansfield from
scoring a basket and did good job not sending her to the free-throw line,"
Louisiana Tech coach Leon Barmore said.
</P>
<P>
	   Mansfield, the Sun Belt's leading scorer (18.9 points) and rebounder (10.1),
had 13 points and eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's what coach stressed in practice all week," Jackson said. "Mansfield
had so many rebounds the first time we played and that was our goal to stop
her."
</P>
<P>
	   Tech's ninth straight victory was its 21st in a row at home and 34th
straight in the conference. The Lady Techsters (19-2 overall, 10-0 Sun Belt)
completed a season sweep of Western Kentucky (15-8, 9-3), which had won 10 of 11
since an 85-61 loss to Tech last month.
</P>
<P>
	   Tech hit 25-of-35 shots (71.4 percent), including 7-of-12 3-pointers, in
taking a 61-30 halftime lead. Tech finished 8-for-18 from long range in the
game.
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson was 5-of-9 on 3-pointers and 9-of-15 from the field overall.
</P>
<P>
	   "They were playing a zone defense," Jackson said. It left me open and it
just so happens my shots were going down."
</P>
<P>
	   Ayana Walker added 17 points for Tech, Betty Lennox had 14 and reserve Chery
Ford 13.
</P>
<P>
	   Jaime Walz led Western with 26 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
